1776555346924206	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtkAM		item.create	bn-l9a	{"description":"# Context\n\nEnd-to-end test of the happy path (`kb init` → `kb ingest <file>` → `kb compile`) breaks because the two halves use different on-disk schemas.\n\n# Repro\n\n```\nkb init --root /tmp/test\nkb ingest --root /tmp/test /some/file.md\nkb compile --root /tmp/test\n```\n\n# Observed\n\n- Local file ingest writes `raw/inbox/<src-id>/<rev-id>/*.md` plus `source_document.json` / `source_revision.json` sidecars. **Nothing** is written to `normalized/`.\n- URL ingest writes `normalized/<src-id>/source.md` and `normalized/<src-id>/metadata.json`, but the metadata.json schema is `{title, original_url, fetched_at_millis, content_hash, source_revision_id}` — NOT a `NormalizedDocument` struct.\n- Compile fails: `error: read normalized document src-xxxx`.\n\n# Root cause\n\nNeither `crates/kb-ingest/src/lib.rs` nor `crates/kb-ingest/src/url.rs` calls `kb_core::write_normalized_document`. They write their own ad-hoc shapes, but compile's `read_normalized_document` expects the canonical struct (`metadata: EntityMetadata`, `source_revision_id`, `canonical_text`, `normalized_assets`, `heading_ids`).\n\n# Fix\n\nBoth ingest paths should produce a `NormalizedDocument` via `write_normalized_document(root, &doc)`. For URL ingest, build canonical_text from the HTML-to-markdown output, populate heading_ids from the markdown, derive source_hashes from the raw blob. For file ingest, read the file as canonical_text and extract headings.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] `kb ingest <file>` followed by `kb compile` succeeds\n- [ ] `normalized/<src-id>/metadata.json` round-trips through `read_normalized_document`\n- [ ] Existing compile tests still pass (they already exercise `write_normalized_document`)\n\n# Priority\n\nBlocker for v1 — without this, the headline happy path doesn't work.","kind":"bug","title":"ingest does not write NormalizedDocument — compile never sees ingested sources"}	blake3:VEozxfvwbHELfbS99KkEhRPN-fMeH__W3nKfIYfboGc
1776555365560628	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtkQM		item.update	bn-l9a	{"field":"urgency","value":"urgent"}	blake3:MQw_o0vC14Ilsx9scE6lfIHh9BRWrGS6NMAY0tY43aE
1776555365727278	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtkgM		item.create	bn-37j	{"description":"# Context\n\nRunning `kb init` in an empty dir creates kb.toml directly in that dir. But running any subsequent command from the same dir fails with 'No KB root found'.\n\n# Repro\n\n```\nmkdir /tmp/test && cd /tmp/test\nkb init\nkb status  # error: No KB root found\n```\n\n# Root cause\n\n`crates/kb-cli/src/root.rs` only walks up from cwd looking for `<ancestor>/kb/kb.toml`. It never checks if `<pwd>/kb.toml` exists. The rule assumes the KB always lives under a `kb/` subdirectory (the project-scoped pattern from the plan), but `kb init` in an arbitrary dir doesn't match that layout.\n\n# Additional evidence\n\n`kb --root=/tmp/test status` also fails with `Provided --root '/tmp/test' does not contain 'kb/kb.toml'`, which reinforces the misassumption: --root is treated as a project root that must contain `kb/`, not as the KB root itself.\n\n# Fix\n\nTwo reasonable options:\n\n1. Make `kb init` default to creating `./kb/` (so `kb init` in /tmp/test produces /tmp/test/kb/). Matches the plan's project-scoped convention.\n2. Extend root discovery to accept either `<pwd>/kb.toml` or `<ancestor>/kb/kb.toml`. Matches the 'global ~/kb' pattern where kb.toml lives directly in the root.\n\nOption 2 is probably right because ~/kb is documented in the plan at notes/plan.md as one of two supported layouts (global `~/kb` with kb.toml at the root, project `<project>/kb/` with kb.toml under `kb/`).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] `kb init && kb status` in the same dir both succeed\n- [ ] `kb --root <dir-with-kb.toml>` accepts the dir itself as root\n- [ ] `kb --root <project-with-kb-subdir>` still resolves to the `kb/` subdir\n- [ ] Error messages distinguish the two patterns","kind":"bug","title":"root discovery fails when pwd is the KB root"}	blake3:dVlyxybWfMaQ9bmmDlz1Xzy-hnvsViqKqS5FlR6NxF8
1776555380525423	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtkwM		item.update	bn-37j	{"field":"urgency","value":"urgent"}	blake3:5o7BpU_ql14lJ5o7QHUI6CykKmXgwM6NHWmDeysj_8w
1776555380698601	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtlAM		item.create	bn-2hp	{"description":"# Context\n\nFresh `kb init` writes a kb.toml with `[llm.runners.claude] permission_mode = \"ask\"`. But the actual `claude` CLI rejects this value.\n\n# Repro\n\n```\nkb init --root /tmp/test\nkb --root /tmp/test doctor\n```\n\n# Observed\n\n```\n[ERROR] model_access:claude: Runner `claude` health check failed for model `openai/gpt-5.4`.\n  details: command=`claude` error=Other error: Claude CLI exited with 1: error: option '--permission-mode <mode>' argument 'ask' is invalid. Allowed choices are acceptEdits, auto, bypassPermissions, default, dontAsk, plan.\n```\n\nSame thing happens on any actual `kb ask` / `kb compile` that routes through claude.\n\n# Root cause\n\n`crates/kb-cli/src/config.rs` LlmConfig::default() sets `permission_mode: Some(\"ask\".to_string())` for the claude runner. `crates/kb-llm/src/claude.rs` ClaudeCliConfig::default() does the same. Both were written against a stale Claude CLI spec.\n\n# Fix\n\nDefault to one of the valid values. `\"default\"` matches what interactive `claude` uses; `\"bypassPermissions\"` matches chief's runner setup. Pick `\"default\"` for the kb.toml default since it preserves whatever the user has configured in their claude setup.\n\nAlso: `kb doctor` should call out \"default permission_mode is invalid; fix it\" more actionably than \"Verify the harness can authenticate\".\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] Fresh `kb init` + `kb doctor` shows ClaudeCode health check passing (given claude is authenticated)\n- [ ] kb.toml default uses a permission_mode from {acceptEdits, auto, bypassPermissions, default, dontAsk, plan}\n- [ ] Config migration note if we ever ship a `kb admin migrate-config`","kind":"bug","title":"default claude permission_mode \"ask\" is invalid — doctor + compile fail out of the box"}	blake3:yFFgORtiiDTz-UB5Q2G0f8DY1Ok4RpRbsbLT4KIfHII
1776555394214871	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtlQM		item.update	bn-2hp	{"field":"urgency","value":"urgent"}	blake3:PY_W40qtYjQWc1Y46v027-Sic7AhzLtJM9192vQlNHg
1776555394380193	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtlgM		item.create	bn-2pk	{"description":"# Context\n\nDefault `[lock] timeout_ms = 5000`. But a single `opencode run` call can take 10-60+ seconds for a model response. So any two kb invocations that overlap in time will fail the second one immediately.\n\n# Repro\n\n```\nkb --root /tmp/test compile &   # LLM call in flight\nkb --root /tmp/test status      # wait, this should just read state — but it also errors if a lock is held. Fine, try a mutating op:\nkb --root /tmp/test ask \"q\"     # error: timed out waiting for KB root lock after 5000ms\n```\n\n# Why 5s is wrong\n\n- A `kb ask` run with opencode measured ~10s in this session (kb ask was in-flight while the lock was held).\n- A `kb compile` over 100 sources would hold the lock for minutes.\n- Users will hit this constantly.\n\n# Fix\n\nRaise the default `[lock] timeout_ms` to something like 600_000 (10 minutes), matching the per-command LLM timeout of 900s. Alternatively:\n\n- Print periodic 'still waiting on lock (held by <command> since <time>)' messages instead of timing out\n- Make read-only commands (status, search, inspect) never contend for the lock (they already don't take it; verify)\n\nAlso: the 5s is set in `LockConfig::default().timeout_ms`, and the only env override is `KB_LOCK_TIMEOUT_MS`. Users don't know to tweak this.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] `kb init` default timeout is long enough for a realistic compile\n- [ ] Waiting on the lock prints at least one status line before giving up\n- [ ] Doc note explaining what the timeout is for","kind":"bug","title":"lock timeout (5s) is shorter than a single LLM round-trip"}	blake3:065Uo3rjKKEvB-G_i0_d4DxMfmDUvpn7uR0qaUAl234
1776555394411310	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtlwM		item.update	bn-2hp	{"field":"urgency","value":"urgent"}	blake3:Z9z8_kEjdkuBi9pOLoU1w45hj98AXdR8Pue21V0TCXI
1776555405706151	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmAM		item.create	bn-2wj	{"description":"# Context\n\nAfter `kb ingest <4-files>` succeeds, `kb status` reports:\n\n```\nsources: 0 total\nwiki pages: 0\nconcepts: 0\n```\n\n# Root cause\n\n`gather_status` counts `wiki/sources/*.md` for the sources line, not the actual ingested source documents. So the label \"sources\" means \"wiki source pages\" but a user who just ran `kb ingest` expects a different meaning.\n\n# Fix\n\nEither:\n\n1. Rename \"sources\" → \"wiki source pages\" and add a separate \"ingested sources\" counter that walks `normalized/` (or the canonical source record dir, once F-ingest-schema is fixed).\n2. Count both: wiki pages + normalized count.\n\nOption 2 is more informative:\n\n```\nsources ingested: 4\n  wiki pages generated: 0 (run `kb compile`)\nconcepts: 0\n```\n\n# Related\n\nBlocked by bn-l9a (ingest-NormalizedDocument-mismatch) in the sense that once ingest properly populates normalized/, status should be able to count from there.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] status shows ingested source count\n- [ ] status distinguishes ingested vs wiki-generated\n- [ ] --json schema adds a field for the new counter","kind":"bug","title":"kb status counts the wrong things — \"sources: 0\" after ingesting 4 sources"}	blake3:Exd6sUy2YuYgx4d7ZxwRP5YgOVuI8UCOxd9mfndb4Pw
1776555416429319	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmQM		item.create	bn-1ab	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb ingest https://raw.githubusercontent.com/.../README.md` fetches a plain markdown file, but url.rs runs the response through HTML-to-markdown readability regardless of Content-Type.\n\n# Repro\n\n```\nkb ingest https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rust-lang/rust-by-example/master/README.md\ncat normalized/src-xxxx/source.md\n```\n\n# Observed\n\nThe markdown source comes out mangled:\n\n- '# Rust By Example' becomes '\\# Rust By Example'\n- '*' becomes '\\*'\n- Newlines collapsed into single lines because the readability pipeline treated the markdown as HTML\n\n# Fix\n\nCheck response Content-Type. If text/markdown or text/plain, store the fetched bytes directly as source.md without running readability/html2md. If text/html, do the current extraction.\n\nProbably also: sniff the first bytes for `<html` or `<!DOCTYPE` to catch mis-served markdown.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] Ingesting a raw .md URL preserves original markdown structure\n- [ ] Ingesting an HTML page still runs readability\n- [ ] Content-Type is recorded in raw/web/<src>/page.headers.json","kind":"bug","title":"URL ingest double-processes raw markdown URLs through HTML extraction"}	blake3:1rHYT0ECI9dYXOB3gyTYYKWna2fb7OTtZdcxyfMmCSE
1776555429199814	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmgM		item.create	bn-2qu	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb ingest /bin/ls` (or any binary file) succeeds with `new_source`, creating `raw/inbox/<id>/<rev>/ls` plus sidecars. No file-type check.\n\n# Repro\n\n```\nkb ingest /bin/ls\n# status new_source file /bin/ls src-xxxx rev-yyyy raw/inbox/src-xxxx/rev-yyyy/ls\n```\n\n# Why bad\n\nMVP scope is 'local markdown/text files and readable web articles'. A binary ELF file will break downstream:\n- canonical_text can't be extracted safely as UTF-8\n- heading_ids extraction will produce garbage\n- source_summary LLM prompt will contain binary bytes\n- blake3 hashing works but the downstream artifacts are useless\n\n# Fix\n\nReject files whose content isn't valid UTF-8, or whose first KB doesn't look like text. Common approach: check the first 8KB for NUL bytes and very-high non-printable ratio.\n\nAlternative: require a whitelist of extensions (.md, .txt, .rst, .org, maybe .html) and warn/skip otherwise.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] `kb ingest /bin/ls` fails with a clear 'file does not appear to be text' error\n- [ ] `kb ingest <text-file-with-no-extension>` still works if contents are UTF-8 text\n- [ ] `kb ingest <dir>` walks in and silently skips binaries instead of erroring","kind":"bug","title":"kb ingest accepts binary files"}	blake3:GUs9LFlA7fS-nn-wpsViY-wdc43W-C9MSfmMipy5uug
1776555441990734	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmwM		item.create	bn-13k	{"description":"# Context\n\nAfter `kb ask --promote` and `kb review approve <id>`, the promoted wiki page's frontmatter contains:\n\n```\nsource_document_ids:\n  - question-xxxx\n  - artifact-xxxx\n```\n\nBut those aren't source documents — they're Question and Artifact IDs. Running `kb lint` correctly catches this:\n\n```\n[ERROR] orphans: referenced source document 'question-xxxx' is missing\n[ERROR] orphans: referenced source document 'artifact-xxxx' is missing\n```\n\n# Root cause\n\n`crates/kb-compile/src/promotion.rs::build_frontmatter` copies `review_item.metadata.dependencies` into `source_document_ids`. Dependencies include the Question and Artifact IDs, which is semantically wrong for this field.\n\n# Fix\n\nThe promoted page's `source_document_ids` should be the actual source-document IDs from the retrieval plan that produced the answer. Either:\n\n1. Thread the original retrieval plan into the promotion path (revive from `outputs/questions/<qid>/retrieval_plan.json`)\n2. Write a separate frontmatter field like `derived_from` for question/artifact IDs and leave `source_document_ids` for true sources\n\nOption 1 is the right semantic — a promoted answer is grounded in the same sources that grounded the answer.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] Promoted page's `source_document_ids` lists the retrieval candidates, not question/artifact IDs\n- [ ] `kb lint` on a freshly promoted page has zero orphan findings\n- [ ] Either add a `derived_from: { question_id, artifact_id }` frontmatter section OR lose the linkage","kind":"bug","title":"promoted wiki pages list question/artifact IDs as source_document_ids (lint false-positives)"}	blake3:iJKi4xILCW4a3VGYqFUpeJDDCm_SUaSwGm-MxoLX978
1776555453945215	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtnAM		item.create	bn-3ny	{"description":"# Context\n\n`state/jobs/<id>.log` is supposed to help debug long-running or hung jobs. In practice it contains a single line: \"job started\". No per-pass events, no subprocess stdout/stderr, nothing.\n\n# Repro\n\n```\nkb compile    # assuming LLM integration is working\ncat state/jobs/<latest>.log\n# → job started\n```\n\n# Why bad\n\n- A compile that hangs on `opencode run` gives the user zero visibility.\n- `kb status` shows the JobRun as still \"running\" but the log doesn't say what step.\n- `kb doctor` warns about interrupted jobs but there's nothing to inspect.\n\n# Fix\n\nAt minimum, pipeline.rs should append structured events to the JobRun log via `append_log_line`:\n\n```\n[pass] backlinks: start\n[pass] backlinks: done (0 affected)\n[pass] source_summary: doc-xxxx\n[pass] source_summary: doc-xxxx: opencode run started, timeout=900s\n[pass] source_summary: doc-xxxx: done (0.9s)\n[pass] concept_merge: 2 groups, 0 uncertain\n```\n\nBetter: capture subprocess stdout/stderr from run_shell_command and append to the log on completion (success or failure).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] JobRun log for a typical compile has at least one line per pass\n- [ ] LLM call logs include model, pass name, and duration\n- [ ] Failures (exit != 0, timeouts) capture stderr tail into the log","kind":"bug","title":"JobRun log captures only \"job started\"; no per-pass or subprocess output"}	blake3:HY4BxvKdNPOlb8sE-J7ZleFtrEm7dL51qwvJpPWUrGQ
1776555465558157	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtnQM		item.create	bn-2gm	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb compile` runs for minutes with zero output while per-document LLM passes hit opencode/claude. Users can't tell if it's working or hung.\n\n# Observed session\n\n- Started kb compile with a single normalized doc\n- Nothing printed for 10+ minutes\n- Had to `ps` to discover opencode was running, timed out eventually\n\n# Fix\n\nPrint one line per pass start + end with a running indicator in between. Example:\n\n```\ncompile: 3 source(s), 3 stale\n  [run] source_summary: doc-a...\n  [ok]  source_summary: doc-a (9.4s)\n  [run] source_summary: doc-b...\n  [ok]  source_summary: doc-b (8.7s)\n  [run] concept_extraction: doc-a...\n  ...\n```\n\nBetter yet: progress bar (via `indicatif`) when stdout is a tty, plain lines when piped/JSON mode.\n\nAlso: `--verbose` flag could stream the opencode stderr live for deeper debugging.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- [ ] kb compile prints at least one line per LLM call before + after\n- [ ] Latency reported per pass\n- [ ] `--json` output is unchanged (structured events, not progress bars)\n- [ ] SIGINT during a pass cleanly cancels and marks the JobRun interrupted","kind":"task","title":"compile should print progress per pass + LLM call (no more silent hangs)"}	blake3:n_orgHAnlSnMZLNEioEQViOS9g5NA93J84k3SyaoPZ4
1776555494494370	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtngM		item.create	bn-1n8	{"description":"# Context\n\nRunning kb with the root flag pointed at a dir that has kb.toml directly (not under a kb subdir) fails with:\n\n  error: Provided root X does not contain kb/kb.toml. Run kb init to initialize a KB root.\n\nBut the user DID run kb init in that dir and there IS a kb.toml there. The error misleads them into thinking kb init did not work.\n\n# Root cause\n\nSame as bn-37j (root discovery only knows the project-scoped layout). The error message cites the specific thing root.rs was looking for (kb/kb.toml) instead of explaining the two valid patterns.\n\n# Fix (depends on bn-37j resolution)\n\nOnce discovery accepts pwd/kb.toml as valid, the error message should say something like:\n\n  error: /path is not a KB root.\n    Expected either /path/kb.toml (KB root) or /path/kb/kb.toml (project-scoped KB).\n    Run kb init to initialize one.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n* Error message names both supported layouts\n* Error suggests the exact kb init command to fix","kind":"bug","title":"root flag error message assumes project layout; misleads when pointed at KB root"}	blake3:wAFTX_fa9RoH2210RBVBwZDAfMvhwSfdHC38Ra7M0U0
1776555509344966	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtnwM		item.create	bn-1h7	{"description":"# Context\n\nA kb compile that crashes or is SIGKILLed leaves a stale state/locks/root.lock.json file with pid/command/timestamp. Next invocation prints:\n\n  error: timed out waiting for KB root lock after 5000ms (command=compile pid=57429 started_at_millis=1776554551797)\n\nBut pid 57429 is dead. The OS-level advisory file lock was correctly released when the process died; only the sidecar metadata persists.\n\n# Why bad\n\nThe error message shows a ghost pid, and if the user then runs kb doctor it correctly detects the orphaned JobRun, but the root.lock.json itself stays. Subsequent invocations still print the stale pid until the user manually deletes the file.\n\n# Fix\n\nWhen try_lock_exclusive succeeds, the acquire path should overwrite the metadata (it already does). The issue is the PRE-acquire diagnostic: format_lock_holder prints metadata without checking if the pid is alive. Before printing, check is_pid_alive(metadata.pid). If not alive, clear the metadata and retry acquire immediately.\n\nAlso: KbLock::acquire should delete stale root.lock.json on successful acquisition to prevent accumulation.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n* After SIGKILLing a compile, the next mutating command either succeeds immediately (stale lock recovered) or prints a clearer \"holder pid is dead, cleaning up\" message.\n* No manual rm needed.\n* kb doctor notes the cleaned-up lock as an informational event.","kind":"bug","title":"stale lock metadata persists after SIGKILL; errors show ghost pid"}	blake3:D0cX01gOQDZt37DxElEa14YQZwJlofCWNz0fOiRV-Yw
1776555521802851	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtoAM		item.create	bn-1ve	{"description":"# Context\n\nkb doctor calls LlmAdapter::run_health_check which invokes the harness with \"respond with OK\" and a 10-second timeout. In practice a cold opencode invocation takes 10-15s on first call, so the health check errors out even though the harness is fine.\n\n# Observed session\n\n  [OK] harness:opencode: Found harness binary opencode\n  [ERROR] model_access:opencode: Runner opencode health check failed... Timeout: opencode health check exceeded timeout of 10s\n\nMeanwhile the same opencode binary answered a real kb ask call 9.8s later. So it works — it just doesn't fit in 10s.\n\n# Fix\n\nBump the health-check timeout default to something like 30-60s, or respect the runner's own timeout_seconds config (currently 900s).\n\nAlso consider warm-vs-cold distinction: the first invocation of opencode in a shell is slow because of mise/TS bootup; subsequent ones are fast. kb doctor could issue a short \"warmup\" call and retry once.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n* Fresh kb doctor against a valid opencode setup reports OK, not Timeout\n* The 10s magic number is either removed or documented in config\n* Error still fires quickly if the harness binary is genuinely missing","kind":"bug","title":"opencode health check timeout of 10s is too aggressive for cold start"}	blake3:twghkCVkfVo-WkphpmNGlYxPovlQv7qMG7h_zi6Mtrg
1776555534265587	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtoQM		item.create	bn-262	{"description":"# Context\n\nDefault kb ingest output is a plain-text table with no header:\n\n  status new_source file /tmp/kb-source/rust-ownership.md src-5b2835ac rev-b7c691ca raw/inbox/src-5b2835ac/rev-b7c691ca/rust-ownership.md\n  Summary: 1 total | 1 new sources | 0 new revisions | 0 skipped\n\nThe columns (status/outcome/kind/path/src-id/rev-id/output-path) are parseable but not labeled. The one-line-per-source format is good, but users can't tell which column is which.\n\n# Fix\n\nEither:\n\n1. Add a header line: \"status kind source_path source_id rev_id output_path\"\n2. Render as a pretty table (use a table lib) with column names\n3. Multi-line output per source, with labels:\n     new_source /tmp/kb-source/rust-ownership.md\n       source_id: src-5b2835ac\n       revision: rev-b7c691ca\n       content: raw/inbox/.../rust-ownership.md\n\nThe --json output is already good (see schema). This only affects the default/human-readable mode.\n\nAlso: \"status new_source\" reads weirdly — drop the literal word \"status\" and just use the outcome:\n\n  [new] file /tmp/kb-source/... src-xxxx rev-yyyy -> raw/inbox/...\n\n# Acceptance\n\n* Human mode has clearly identified columns or fields\n* Existing --json schema unchanged\n* Summary line still present at the end","kind":"task","title":"kb ingest human output has no column labels"}	blake3:VwWkFq23-k1TnNdWFD3vZZnLLZ4acczcz-REu6k7svw
1776555544663856	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtogM		item.create	bn-25h	{"description":"# Context\n\nRunning kb init prints only:\n\n  Initialized empty knowledge base at /tmp/kb-hands-on\n\nNo hint about what to do next. A first-time user has no idea what kb ingest looks like, where prompts live, or that they should look at kb.toml.\n\n# Fix\n\nAfter init, print a short \"What next?\" block:\n\n  Initialized empty knowledge base at /tmp/kb-hands-on\n\n  Next:\n    kb ingest <path-or-url>    add a document\n    kb compile                 build source/concept pages from stale sources\n    kb ask \"your question\"     generate an answer grounded in your corpus\n    kb doctor                  verify your LLM backend is reachable\n\n  Config: /tmp/kb-hands-on/kb.toml\n\nKeep it under ~6 lines. Gated by a --quiet flag if scripts rely on silent init.\n\nAlso consider: if opencode/claude isn't on PATH at init time, note it.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n* Fresh kb init output helpful to a first-time user\n* --quiet suppresses the next-steps block\n* --json output unchanged","kind":"task","title":"kb init prints no next-step guidance for first-time users"}	blake3:Rr5Z7zljObqvX5iqbhiJ14Ba2DdgqMsjjmviBAaoG5E
1776555556184745	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtowM		item.create	bn-1n7	{"description":"# Context\n\nkb compile --dry-run only shows the batch passes:\n\n  compile: 1 source(s), 1 stale\n    [dry-run] backlinks - would process 1 node(s) - wiki/concepts/*\n    [dry-run] lexical_index - would process 1 node(s)\n    [dry-run] index_pages - would process 3 node(s)\n\nBut a live compile with 1 stale normalized doc would ALSO run source_summary, source_page, concept_extraction, and concept_merge. The dry-run output doesn't mention them, so users think compile will just index.\n\n# Fix\n\nIf an adapter is (or would be) available, include per-doc passes in the dry-run output:\n\n  [dry-run] source_summary - would process 1 stale doc(s)\n    - normalized/src-manual\n  [dry-run] concept_extraction - would process 1 stale doc(s)\n  [dry-run] concept_merge - would process <N> candidates globally\n\nIf no adapter is configured, print a note:\n\n  [skipped-dry] source_summary - no LLM adapter configured\n\n# Acceptance\n\n* dry-run output mirrors what live compile would run\n* Stale doc IDs listed as would_process entries\n* Matches the existing test pipeline::tests::dry_run_matches_live_run_stale_count (that one counts stale sources, not passes)","kind":"task","title":"compile --dry-run omits per-doc LLM passes from its preview"}	blake3:WlxkbVsXzMb6MAfNzcrpLgy5sWuHL5XyRc-OUl_nvpc
1776555569639775	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtpAM		item.create	bn-cpg	{"description":"# Context\n\nkb inspect can resolve by path, by graph node ID, by build record ID, or by job ID — but NOT by frontmatter id: field.\n\n# Repro\n\nA wiki page has:\n\n  ---\n  id: wiki-source-manual\n  ...\n\nRunning kb inspect wiki-source-manual errors:\n\n  error: wiki-source-manual was not found. Try an exact ID, a unique graph suffix, a build record ID, a job ID, or a path under the KB root.\n\nBut kb inspect wiki/sources/manual.md works.\n\n# Why bad\n\nFrontmatter ids are the kb entity IDs called out in the plan (SourceDocument, WikiPage, Concept, Question, Artifact). They're the natural thing a user would type to inspect \"the wiki page called X\" — especially for artifact ids (artifact-question-xxxx) that aren't obviously paths.\n\n# Fix\n\nExtend inspect resolution: scan wiki/ and outputs/ for files whose frontmatter id matches the target. Cache this resolution after kb compile (add a lookup index to state/indexes/).\n\nCheaper path for v1: when inspect fails, scan the trees (O(#wiki-pages)) looking for matching frontmatter id and suggest \"did you mean kb inspect wiki/sources/manual.md?\".\n\n# Acceptance\n\n* kb inspect <frontmatter-id> resolves when unique\n* When ambiguous (two pages with same id — shouldn't happen but defensive), print both options\n* Helpful \"did you mean\" suggestion on failure","kind":"task","title":"kb inspect does not resolve targets by frontmatter id"}	blake3:MeMK-4dtJn-7FdI4kvExNGiwX3u0FzUWvQGKLUgg99s
1776555578337364	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtpQM		item.update	bn-l9a	{"field":"labels","value":{"action":"add","label":"hands-on-sweep"}}	blake3:-Q2Eflc_88XrwBNH4wzfGM74GYVNkN3TW7jLED1g0ms
