1776561636787689	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_QM		item.create	bn-1pw	{"description":"# Context\n\nAfter `kb compile`, `kb status` and `kb inspect` fail:\n\n  error: deserialize hashes /tmp/kb2/state/hashes.json\n\nThe file exists (compile writes it) but status/inspect can't parse it.\n\n# Root cause\n\nTwo Rust structs both claim ownership of `state/hashes.json` with incompatible schemas:\n\n- `kb_core::Hashes { inputs: BTreeMap<PathBuf, Hash> }` -- written by `kb init`, consumed by `kb status` (main.rs:2240) and `kb inspect` (main.rs:1589).\n- `kb_compile::HashState { hashes: BTreeMap<String, String> }` -- written by `run_compile_with_llm`, consumed internally for stale detection.\n\nOn disk after `kb init`:  `{\"inputs\": {}}`. After `kb compile`: `{\"hashes\": {...}}`. `Hashes::load` then fails because `inputs` is missing and serde does not have `#[serde(default)]` on the struct.\n\n# Fix\n\nCollapse to one schema. Either:\n- Drop `kb_core::Hashes` entirely, make status/inspect consume `HashState` directly via `kb_compile::HashState::load_from_root`.\n- Or merge both into one struct (pick `HashState` since it is the one compile actually uses for stale detection).\n\nBest: remove `Hashes` (dead init artifact) and update the two main.rs call sites to use HashState.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb init && kb compile && kb status && kb inspect wiki/sources/X.md` all succeed end-to-end\n- Remove one of the two redundant structs\n- Add integration test: round-trip through `init -> compile -> status` without error","kind":"bug","title":"state/hashes.json schema conflict: Hashes vs HashState (status+inspect break after compile)"}	blake3:KsoxwCt5eQ77nxzz-5AKbhVyH0UdUnMT0XyKrspjq8k
1776561636823915	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_gM		item.update	bn-1pw	{"field":"urgency","value":"urgent"}	blake3:qPl6zMa9vaNmTOqcz8lq5oXqvQQ8xhLYIYSiCTmf7XU
1776561652566917	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_wM		item.create	bn-3lo	{"description":"# Context\n\nConcept pages produced by `run_concept_merge_pass` use hand-rolled writeln! macros to build YAML frontmatter:\n\n```rust\nfor alias in &group.aliases {\n    writeln!(content, \"  - {alias}\").expect(\"infallible write to String\");\n}\n```\n\nAny alias containing YAML-sensitive characters produces invalid YAML. Example: a Rust \"Named lifetime parameter\" concept gets alias `'a` (a lifetime), written as:\n\n```yaml\naliases:\n  - 'a\n```\n\nYAML parser sees an unterminated single-quoted string. `kb lint` then fails:\n\n  error: read frontmatter for /tmp/kb2/wiki/concepts/named-lifetime-parameter.md\n\n# Observed impact\n\nOn a 4-source Rust+Python corpus, 2 of 42 concept pages had broken YAML (`'a` alias, `'static` alias). The entire lint run bails on the first bad page.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-compile/src/concept_merge.rs::render_concept_page`, replace hand-rolled serialization with `serde_yaml`:\n\n```rust\nlet mut fm = serde_yaml::Mapping::new();\nfm.insert(\"id\", concept_id);\nfm.insert(\"name\", canonical_name);\nif !aliases.is_empty() { fm.insert(\"aliases\", aliases); }\nif !source_anchors.is_empty() { fm.insert(\"sources\", source_anchors); }\nlet yaml = serde_yaml::to_string(&fm)?;\n```\n\nserde_yaml handles quoting, escapes, and line continuation correctly.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Concept pages with aliases containing apostrophes, quotes, colons, hashes, etc. produce valid YAML\n- `serde_yaml::from_str` can round-trip every generated concept page\n- Add a test with alias list `[\"'a\", \"'static\", \"foo: bar\", \"hash#tag\"]` asserting round-trip","kind":"bug","title":"concept_merge writes unescaped YAML; Rust lifetime aliases break lint"}	blake3:Snwx-m9Bi8uaUbXZUULXSe4JVrTd1pX1APR71rnb9xc
1776561652607258	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgAQ		item.update	bn-3lo	{"field":"urgency","value":"urgent"}	blake3:PILuMP0ZU_xGkr-27_nVi8Emb8p0YVn0_ZWuhOMLJgQ
1776561669197642	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgQQ		item.create	bn-1op	{"description":"# Context\n\nSecond `kb compile` on an unchanged corpus reports:\n\n```\ncompile: 4 source(s), 0 stale\n  [run] concept_merge: 43 candidate(s)...\n  [ok]  concept_merge (84.6s)\n```\n\nZero stale sources, so per-doc passes (source_summary, concept_extraction) correctly skip. But concept_merge runs unconditionally, sending all 43 candidates through the LLM again. 84+ seconds wasted per no-op compile.\n\nViolates the plan's headline incremental guarantee (notes/plan.md, \"Incremental compilation design\": \"rerun only affected passes\", \"second compile with no changes is a no-op\").\n\n# Root cause\n\n`pipeline.rs::run_concept_merge_from_state` loads every candidate JSON from `state/concept_candidates/` and calls the adapter every time, without checking if the candidates changed since the last successful merge.\n\n# Fix\n\nCompute a merge fingerprint from:\n- sorted list of candidate file hashes (blake3 of JSON contents)\n- merge prompt template hash\n- model identifier\n\nCompare against the fingerprint recorded in the last merge's BuildRecord (manifest_hash already exists but isn't consulted for skip). If unchanged, skip the merge.\n\nStorage option A: add an entry to `state/hashes.json` keyed on \"concept_merge:global\" with the fingerprint.\nStorage option B: consult the latest `build:merge-concept-candidates` record's manifest_hash directly.\n\nEither way, short-circuit in run_concept_merge_from_state.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Two successive `kb compile` runs on unchanged corpus: second run shows `[skip] concept_merge (no candidate changes)` and exits under 5s (no LLM calls)\n- Adding one new source triggers the merge again\n- Changing the merge prompt template triggers the merge again\n- Changing the default model triggers the merge again","kind":"bug","title":"concept_merge runs every compile even when no candidates changed"}	blake3:8ojcnghEFEl0CUoflV6WX1l7FjVttiKi3raD0KHdeIM
1776561669234971	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtggQ		item.update	bn-1op	{"field":"urgency","value":"urgent"}	blake3:_6c6Rnfm2SJ_vn-uu9u9Zy8pz5DmRh6J1i4HrlTebFE
1776561683606991	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgwQ		item.create	bn-3qd	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb lint` on a corpus with one unparseable frontmatter bails with a single error and skips every other check. Example: one concept page has invalid YAML -> lint exits after broken-links runs but before (or during) the next check, masking any other issues.\n\n# Observed\n\nActual run with two pages having broken YAML:\n\n```\n[fail] broken-links: 4 issue(s)\n...\n[fail] orphans: 8 issue(s)\n...\nerror: read frontmatter for /tmp/kb2/wiki/concepts/static-lifetime.md\n```\n\nThe `error:` terminates the process; subsequent checks (stale, missing-citations) never run. And the broken page itself is not reported as a lint finding.\n\n# Fix\n\n`read_frontmatter` failures inside any lint pass should be caught, reported as a LintIssue with `kind: invalid_frontmatter` severity=error, and processing continues with the next file. The current `with_context` bubbles the anyhow error up; swap for `match read_frontmatter(...)` inside the lint scan loops.\n\nAlso: add `IssueKind::InvalidFrontmatter` to the enum and emit it with line 0 target=<path>.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Lint with a broken frontmatter page reports `invalid_frontmatter` finding and continues running the remaining checks\n- Every other file in the wiki still gets its frontmatter parsed\n- Exit code reflects severity (warn/error) as before","kind":"bug","title":"lint bails on first unparseable page instead of reporting and continuing"}	blake3:mxo4FWuA2-u0qaE3XDuJB7UWPnU6-XquYjY8Ouo1tjc
1776561701568304	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthAQ		item.create	bn-3aw	{"description":"# Context\n\nAfter `kb ask --promote` and `kb review approve`, the promoted wiki page frontmatter contains wiki page paths where source-document IDs should be:\n\n```yaml\nsource_document_ids:\n  - wiki/concepts/c-extensions-that-release-the-gil.md\n  - wiki/sources/src-04aca3d1.md\n```\n\n`kb lint orphans` flags every entry as missing because they are not SourceDocument IDs.\n\n# Root cause\n\n`kb_query::write_artifact` pulls `source_document_ids` from the retrieval plan's `candidates[].id` field. But `RetrievalCandidate.id` is a wiki page path (e.g. `wiki/concepts/ownership.md`), not a source-document ID (`src-xxxx`).\n\nbn-13k plumbed this through from the artifact frontmatter into promotion, which perpetuates the mistake.\n\n# Fix options\n\n1. **Resolve at retrieval time**: when building the retrieval plan, also record the underlying source_document_id for each candidate (read frontmatter, find `source_document_id` field). Candidates for concept pages (which aggregate multiple sources) record all contributing source docs.\n2. **Resolve at promotion**: promotion walks each candidate path, reads its frontmatter, extracts `source_document_id` or `source_document_ids`, and writes those.\n3. **Teach lint to understand paths**: orphans check also accepts path-style values and verifies the file exists.\n\nOption 2 is simplest: contained change in promotion.rs. Option 1 is cleanest.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Approved promotion's `source_document_ids` contains only src-xxxx-style IDs from the corpus\n- `kb lint orphans` on a freshly-promoted page has zero findings\n- Retrieval plan candidates still work for retrieval (unchanged API)","kind":"bug","title":"promoted pages source_document_ids contain wiki page paths, not source IDs"}	blake3:bW6YR8SzYvYtzJ14W3WWfIZOVCYeotfyZfRea-0f4B8
1776561713336037	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthQQ		item.create	bn-1xf	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb compile --dry-run` skips LLM adapter construction (correct, no LLM calls). But the dry-run output misleadingly reports:\n\n```\n[skip] source_summary — no LLM adapter configured\n[skip] concept_extraction — no LLM adapter configured\n[skip] concept_merge — no LLM adapter configured\n```\n\nUser reads \"no LLM adapter configured\" and thinks their kb.toml is broken, when really the dry-run deliberately chose not to construct one.\n\n# Fix\n\nEither:\n1. Distinguish the two states in `PassStatus`: `Skipped { reason: \"dry-run (would run)\" }` vs `Skipped { reason: \"no LLM adapter configured\" }`. CLI dispatch (main.rs compile handler) already knows which case applies (if dry_run: ..., else: ...).\n2. Construct the adapter even for dry-run so the would-process list is populated correctly, but never invoke it.\n\nOption 1 is probably simplest. Pass a `skip_reason` enum into the pipeline from the CLI:\n- `SkipReason::DryRun` -> `\"dry-run (would process <N> node(s))\"` with the doc IDs listed\n- `SkipReason::NoAdapter` -> current text\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb compile --dry-run` on a real configured KB says `[dry-run] source_summary: doc-a` (not `[skip] no LLM adapter`)\n- `kb compile --dry-run` on a KB with broken opencode still says `[skip] no LLM adapter configured` when the adapter fails to build","kind":"task","title":"dry-run compile says \"no LLM adapter configured\" instead of \"dry-run\""}	blake3:e-3hqpj0duI5-HzsKTb5N4e9xXaXY9P3VbfbHY-EApk
1776561726701094	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthgQ		item.create	bn-2nk	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb ask` prints an \"uncertainty banner\" when source coverage looks low. On a real corpus (4 Rust+Python sources, 40+ concepts), the ask \"what are rust's three ownership rules?\" produced:\n\n- 8 retrieval candidates pulled\n- 5 valid citations in the final answer\n- 0 unresolved citations\n- Strong, grounded response citing the rules correctly\n\nBut the output still said:\n\n```\nNote: low source coverage — uncertainty banner added.\n```\n\nAnd the same banner appeared at the top of the answer markdown. For a question answered well with strong grounding, this is noise.\n\n# Root cause\n\n`kb_query::postprocess_answer` decides `has_uncertainty_banner` using some threshold that triggered despite 5/5 valid citations. Likely compares `estimated_tokens vs token_budget` or `candidates.len()` alone without weighting by citations-used.\n\n# Fix\n\nCompute uncertainty only when actually uncertain:\n\n- `valid_citations.is_empty()` → uncertainty banner (truly ungrounded)\n- `invalid_citations > valid_citations` → uncertainty banner (mostly hallucinated)\n- Otherwise no banner\n\nRemove any pure `candidates.len() < N` or `estimated_tokens < token_budget * X` heuristic.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Ask with 5+ valid citations, 0 unresolved: no banner\n- Ask with 0 valid citations, 0 candidates: banner\n- Ask with mix (e.g. 3 valid, 5 unresolved): banner\n- New unit tests in `kb_query::artifact::tests` for each case","kind":"task","title":"uncertainty banner fires even with strong grounding"}	blake3:EzWTU7SXF0S9Zs6IxEGKaOTGHLwOKPfUOUSDslpqJnA
1776561736652246	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthwQ		item.create	bn-1pm	{"description":"# Context\n\nkb lint broken-links output duplicates the target:\n\n```\n- [Error] wiki/concepts/index.md:44 unresolved wiki page target `wiki/concepts/named-lifetime-parameter` (wiki/concepts/named-lifetime-parameter)\n  suggested fix: wiki/concepts/lifetime-annotation\n```\n\nThe target appears twice - once in backticks after \"target\", once in parentheses at the end.\n\n# Fix\n\nDrop the parenthesized duplicate in the format! call inside kb-lint (find_broken_links output formatting). Keep the backticks version.\n\n# Acceptance\n\nOnly one copy of the target per line; format looks like:\n```\n- [Error] referring/page.md:LINE unresolved wiki page target `target/path`\n  suggested fix: closest-match/path\n```","kind":"task","title":"lint broken-links output duplicates the target string"}	blake3:mW1N8tWXO4Po1Ws6Upwf8D-cgfUTBzqnPgumvEy9m9M
