1776622719549450	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt5wQ		item.create	bn-nnd	{"description":"# Context\n\nTwo separate normalization gaps in URL ingest produce duplicate or unrecognized sources:\n\n## J4: uppercase scheme rejected entirely\n\n    kb ingest HTTPS://example.com/foo\n    error: source path does not exist or is not a regular file/directory: HTTPS://...\n\nThe ingest dispatcher (in `crates/kb-ingest/src/lib.rs`) decides URL vs file by prefix-matching `https://` / `http://` in lowercase. Mixed-case schemes like `HTTPS://` or `Http://` fail prefix match and fall through to the file-path branch, which then errors.\n\nPer RFC 3986 URL schemes are case-insensitive.\n\n## J5: trailing slash produces distinct source_document IDs\n\n    kb ingest https://foo.com/bar/\n    kb ingest https://foo.com/bar\n\nThese semantically equivalent URLs get different `src-xxxx` IDs. Standard practice: collapse trailing slashes on non-root paths during URL normalization for identity hashing.\n\n# Fix\n\n`source_document_id_for_url(url)` in `crates/kb-core/src/source_identity.rs`:\n\n- Lowercase the scheme before hashing\n- Strip a trailing slash from the path (unless path is just `/`)\n- Keep case on host (already handled) and query params (already sorted)\n\nAlso update the URL-vs-file dispatch in kb-ingest to recognize mixed-case `https://` / `http://` prefixes.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb ingest HTTPS://example.com/` and `kb ingest https://example.com/` produce the same src-id\n- `kb ingest https://foo.com/bar/` and `kb ingest https://foo.com/bar` produce the same src-id\n- Root path `https://foo.com/` stays distinct from empty path (unchanged)\n- Unit tests for both in source_identity.rs","kind":"bug","title":"URL normalization: mixed-case scheme rejected, trailing slash not collapsed"}	blake3:6Qia9Ftc7STpSjepBnI9z8XNiSdIPb2bKfrFd2TqwQM
1776622737516428	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6AQ		item.create	bn-2ey	{"description":"# Context\n\nSeveral global flags appear in `kb --help` but are either unwired or partially wired:\n\n- `--since <SINCE>`: advertised as \"Filter results since a given time\" but no command acts on it. `kb --since 2025-01-01 status` produces identical output to `kb status`.\n- `--review`: no command reads it.\n- `--format <FORMAT>` with choices `md, marp, json, png`:\n  - `kb --format json status` does NOT produce JSON (only `--json` does)\n  - `kb --format png status` is silently accepted; png is meaningless for status\n  - `kb --format marp` only meaningful for `kb ask`\n\n# Fix (one or the other)\n\n**Option A — implement them:**\n- `--since`: plumb into `gather_status` to filter recent_jobs + changed_inputs, and into `kb review list` to filter by created_at\n- `--format json` → alias for `--json`\n- `--review` → shorthand for `kb review` (tricky clap structure)\n- Error when a command receives `--format` with a value it doesn't support\n\n**Option B — remove unimplemented flags:**\n- Drop `--since` from global until there's a consumer\n- Drop `--review` from global\n- Scope `--format` to the specific subcommands that consume it (ask, publish) — not as a global flag\n\nOption B is cleaner for v1: fewer promises, no confusing dead flags.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Every flag in `kb --help` either has at least one consumer OR is removed\n- `kb --format X Y` errors when Y does not support format X\n- `--json` and `--format json` behave consistently","kind":"bug","title":"global flags --since, --review, --format partially unwired; some silently ignored"}	blake3:1mAslH0rVgdh2iRzISFBhkVBRgrSoabRvSSX1otv6xU
1776622754830983	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6QQ		item.create	bn-2s6	{"description":"# Context\n\nTwo commands accept empty required arguments silently and then do useless work:\n\n## J1: kb ask with empty question\n\n    kb ask \"\"\n    Artifact written: outputs/questions/question-xxxx/answer.md\n    Citations: 0 valid, 0 unresolved\n    Note: low source coverage — uncertainty banner added.\n\nCalls the LLM with an empty query, burns tokens/latency, writes a placeholder artifact. Should validate the question isn't empty/whitespace-only.\n\n## J2: kb inspect with empty target\n\n    kb inspect \"\"\n    target:\n\n    resolved_id:\n\n    kind: file\n    ...\n\nSucceeds and reports on `\"\"` as if it were a valid target. Should refuse empty string.\n\n# Fix\n\nAt the start of `run_ask` and `run_inspect` in `crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs`:\n\n```rust\nif query.trim().is_empty() {\n    bail!(\"ask: question cannot be empty\");\n}\n```\n\nSame for inspect target. Match the existing error messages — e.g. \"no question provided\" in `resolve_query`.\n\n`resolve_query` already handles the `Some(q) if q != \"-\"` branch by accepting `q`, then reads stdin for `None | Some(\"-\")`. The issue: when q = `\"\"`, it's treated as a valid question (the empty string). Add `q.trim().is_empty()` check to the guard.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask \"\"` errors without calling the LLM\n- `kb ask \"   \"` errors\n- `kb ask -` with empty stdin errors (this already works per `resolve_query`)\n- `kb inspect \"\"` errors\n- `kb inspect \"   \"` errors","kind":"bug","title":"kb ask and kb inspect accept empty required arguments"}	blake3:RSdt59tdTZMQa4tOGWPRZPjwDmkf0Cz9VCd8JDTXEYE
1776622772723155	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6gQ		item.create	bn-24t	{"description":"# Context\n\n`heading_ids` in normalized documents has no deduplication. A file with repeated headings produces duplicates:\n\n    # In a file with 200,000 identical `## section` lines:\n    heading_ids: [\"section\", \"section\", \"section\", ... 200k times]\n\nEven a realistic corpus with 5 `## Overview` in a long doc ends up with:\n\n    heading_ids: [\"overview\", \"overview\", \"overview\", \"overview\", \"overview\"]\n\n## Consequences\n\n- metadata.json bloats — 200k entries × ~9 bytes each = 1.8MB of duplicates\n- Citations referencing `heading_anchor: overview` can't pick a specific instance\n- Concept extraction prompt sees many identical anchor names, gets confused about which source section to cite\n- Semantic searches via the lexical index may double-count\n\n# Fix\n\nSuffix duplicates with a counter (Markdown's own rendering convention):\n\n    [\"overview\", \"overview-2\", \"overview-3\", \"overview-4\", \"overview-5\"]\n\nImplement in `crates/kb-ingest/src/headings.rs::extract_h1_h2_h3_headings`. After computing each slug, check a local `HashMap<&str, u32>` counter:\n- Slug not seen → emit as-is, count = 1\n- Slug seen N times → emit `slug-{N+1}`, bump counter\n\nMatches GitHub Flavored Markdown and most static site generators.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Unique headings unchanged: `[\"intro\", \"setup\", \"conclusion\"]`\n- Duplicate headings suffixed: input `[\"overview\", \"overview\", \"overview\"]` → output `[\"overview\", \"overview-2\", \"overview-3\"]`\n- Case-insensitive matching (Overview vs overview)\n- Unit tests in headings.rs covering dedup\n- Existing extract tests still pass","kind":"bug","title":"heading_ids has no dedup; repeated headings produce duplicates"}	blake3:CKNLMCsnmJ9v3EeUFJbzoUqiiG_v_crCrE0QOQNlhPQ
1776622792761402	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6wQ		item.create	bn-2sv	{"description":"# Context\n\nIf kb.toml is present but syntactically broken, read-only commands silently ignore the error and run anyway:\n\n    echo \"invalid toml ===\" > /tmp/kb5/kb.toml\n    kb status\n    # succeeds, prints status, no warning\n\nOnly commands that explicitly load config (ask, compile, publish) error. But the user may not realize their config is broken until they hit a command that cares.\n\nDoctor *does* correctly flag an unparseable kb.toml, which is good — but users don't always run doctor first.\n\n# Fix\n\nEither:\n\n1. **Validate once at the top of every command** (including read-only): try `Config::load_from_root(root, None)` and print a warning (not error) if it fails, then continue with defaults. Warning on stderr.\n\n2. **Make unparseable kb.toml a hard error for every command**. More strict; matches \"fail fast\" philosophy. A broken kb.toml is always a bug.\n\nOption 2 is cleaner — users should fix a broken config before running ANY kb command. Status/search/inspect can still run if they catch and explain the specific parse error and tell the user to fix kb.toml or run `kb init --force`.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Any command on a KB with broken kb.toml produces a clear error message naming the line/column of the problem\n- Errors happen before the command body runs (so no partial state writes)\n- Exit code 1; error text suggests `kb init --force` or manual fix","kind":"bug","title":"broken kb.toml silently ignored by read-only commands (status, search, inspect)"}	blake3:C2fDupA0OqrFNpVu8VT4hlWRBduyGQz2DuEJZFP1kRQ
