1776640870959395	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthQU		item.create	bn-yqz	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb compile` generates spurious cross-document backlinks whenever two unrelated source documents happen to share a heading name.\n\nRepro in `/tmp/kb-pass6/kb`:\n\n- `sqlite-wal.md` (src-0f41ad8b) has a `## Pitfalls` heading. Concept `checkpoint` extracted from it gets `sources: [{ heading_anchor: pitfalls, quote: \"Checkpoint contention with many concurrent writers\" }]`.\n- `rust-async.md` (src-302b46ff) also has a `## Pitfalls` heading.\n- After compile, `wiki/concepts/checkpoint.md` lists a backlink to `wiki/sources/src-302b46ff` (rust-async), and `wiki/sources/src-302b46ff.md` lists `[[wiki/concepts/checkpoint]]` under \"Referenced by concepts\".\n\nSame symptom for `nfs-incompatibility-of-wal`, `checkpoint-contention`, `long-running-reader-checkpoint-starvation`, etc. — all SQLite concepts incorrectly backlinked to rust-async just because `pitfalls` appears in both doc heading_ids.\n\nAffected user pages include `wiki/sources/src-302b46ff.md::Referenced by concepts` which lists ~7 SQLite concepts that rust-async has nothing to do with.\n\n# Root cause\n\n`crates/kb-compile/src/backlinks.rs::collect_frontmatter_source_backlinks` builds `anchor_to_source_docs: BTreeMap<String, Vec<String>>` from every normalized/src-.../metadata.json heading_ids. For each concept's `sources[].heading_anchor`, it unions ALL source docs that happen to share that anchor name (line 268-281):\n\n```rust\nlet Some(candidate_docs) = anchor_to_source_docs.get(anchor) else { continue };\nfor doc_id in candidate_docs {\n    let Some(source_page_id) = source_doc_to_page.get(doc_id) else { continue };\n    // credit the relation — but doc_id might be a completely unrelated doc!\n```\n\nThe concept's own `source_document_ids: [...]` frontmatter field is the authoritative list of contributing sources. Anchor matching should be gated by that set.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `collect_frontmatter_source_backlinks`, compute the concept's `source_document_ids` set once and intersect the anchor-resolution candidate list with that set:\n\n```rust\nlet concept_source_docs: BTreeSet<String> = parsed\n    .get(\"source_document_ids\")\n    .and_then(|v| v.as_sequence())\n    .map(|seq| seq.iter().filter_map(|v| v.as_str().map(str::to_string)).collect())\n    .unwrap_or_default();\n\n// ...\nfor doc_id in candidate_docs {\n    if !concept_source_docs.is_empty() && !concept_source_docs.contains(doc_id) {\n        continue;\n    }\n    // credit as before\n}\n```\n\n(The `is_empty()` guard preserves current behavior for older concept pages missing the field. New extractions always emit it.)\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After compile on the /tmp/kb-pass6 corpus, `wiki/concepts/checkpoint.md` lists only `src-0f41ad8b` as backlink, not `src-302b46ff`.\n- `wiki/sources/src-302b46ff.md::Referenced by concepts` does NOT list SQLite-only concepts.\n- Existing `heading_anchor_and_source_document_ids_paths_combine_without_duplicates` test still passes.\n- New test: two sources share a heading \"summary\"; a concept sourced only from src-A must not backlink to src-B.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): backlinks must respect source_document_ids — heading-anchor collisions create false cross-links"}	blake3:0kxSW2xS9hQH8vUUBhyZ5unFFD1lmzREJix8pf1Jjrs
1776640874121578	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthgU		item.create	bn-2gn	{"description":"# Context\n\nModifying a source file and re-ingesting produces a new revision, but `kb status` does not flag the source as needing recompile.\n\nRepro:\n\n    kb ingest /path/to/foo.md           # rev-A\n    kb compile                          # wiki/sources/src-NNN.md generated with source_revision_id rev-A\n    echo \"change\" >> /path/to/foo.md\n    kb ingest /path/to/foo.md           # rev-B\n    kb status\n    # \"changed inputs not yet compiled\" does NOT list src-NNN\n\nBut `normalized/src-NNN/metadata.json` now carries source_revision_id rev-B, while `wiki/sources/src-NNN.md` frontmatter still shows rev-A. The wiki page is stale and the user has no signal it needs recompile.\n\nRunning `kb compile` correctly detects the change via content hashing and re-runs source_summary (the in-compile stale detection works). The bug is only that `kb status` misreports the between-runs state.\n\n# Root cause\n\nLikely in `crates/kb-cli/src/status.rs` (or wherever `changed_inputs_not_compiled` is computed). The check is probably \"source exists in normalized/ but no corresponding wiki/sources/<src>.md\" — which is true only for never-compiled sources, not for sources whose revision has changed since last compile.\n\nThe correct check: compare `normalized/<src>/metadata.json::source_revision_id` against `wiki/sources/<src>.md` frontmatter `source_revision_id`. If different → stale.\n\n# Fix\n\nLoad each wiki source page's frontmatter (small, cheap); compute the set of (src_id, revision_id) pairs generated; diff against normalized/.\n\nTests should cover:\n- fresh ingest, no compile → reported as changed (current behavior)\n- compiled, then re-ingested with new content → reported as changed (currently missed)\n- compiled, no change → not reported (current behavior)\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After `kb ingest` of a modified file, `kb status` lists the source's normalized path under \"changed inputs not yet compiled\".\n- After `kb compile`, the list clears.\n- Unit + integration test in kb-cli covers the re-ingest path.","kind":"task","title":"fix(status): detect when re-ingested sources need recompile (revision-id mismatch)"}	blake3:wg-CnPQBkNDnK_lYvi4_dA1rTslzn6tyLBFtfSRxPNk
1776640877227139	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthwU		item.create	bn-2so	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb init --force` overwrites kb.toml even when a user-customized file exists. This destroys publish targets, custom runner configuration, custom lint rules, etc.\n\nThe error message for a corrupted manifest.json explicitly suggests this as a remedy:\n\n    error: deserialize manifest ...: missing field `artifacts` ...\n    # user follows the hint to fix manifest, runs:\n    kb init --force\n    # → silently wipes [publish.targets.*], runner overrides, etc.\n\nRepro in /tmp/kb-pass6/kb:\n\n    # kb.toml has custom [publish.targets.my-obsidian]\n    kb init --force\n    # kb.toml no longer has it\n\n# Fix\n\nOption 1 (safer, recommended): `kb init --force` regenerates the *directory scaffold* and `state/manifest.json` but leaves kb.toml alone unless the file is literally absent or unparseable. If kb.toml is present and valid, preserve it; print \"kb.toml preserved\".\n\nOption 2: `kb init --force` creates `kb.toml.new` alongside the existing and tells the user to diff + merge manually. Still a hazard.\n\nOption 3: `kb init --force` makes a `kb.toml.bak.<timestamp>` before overwriting, prints where the backup went.\n\nRecommended: Option 1 + add explicit flag `--reset-config` for the rare case where a user really does want to wipe config.\n\nAlso consider: any command that suggests `kb init --force` in its error message should not suggest it as a fix for state file corruption. For a broken manifest.json, the tool should offer `kb doctor --repair` or write fresh manifest.json directly.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb init --force` on an existing KB with a customized kb.toml leaves kb.toml untouched and prints an acknowledgement.\n- Adding `--reset-config` (or a confirmation prompt without --force) is the only way to wipe kb.toml.\n- The error-message hint for manifest corruption changes to something that won't wipe config.\n- Integration test: seed kb.toml with `[publish.targets.test] path = \"/x\"`, run `kb init --force`, assert the section is still present.","kind":"task","title":"fix(init): --force preserves kb.toml; destructive config reset requires explicit flag"}	blake3:yYvSyPzaMYyVoTJ0UMRQ_Wjv7n5VzL__B-ewswGUX5s
1776640880955609	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtiAU		item.create	bn-40r	{"description":"# Context\n\nEmpty files are ingested silently, then run full LLM pipeline in compile (source_summary + concept_extraction), burning tokens and seconds per empty source, and producing useless artifacts.\n\nRepro:\n\n    touch empty.md\n    kb ingest empty.md\n    # [new-source]  empty.md        (no warning about empty content)\n    kb compile\n    #   [ok] source_summary: src-fb6d570e (6.7s)      ← LLM called on empty content\n    #   [ok] concept_extraction: src-fb6d570e (7.2s)   ← LLM called again\n    kb lint\n    # 3 synthetic-region missing-citations warnings for that source page\n\n`kb ask` will also list the empty source in its `source_document_ids` frontmatter, suggesting the empty file contributed evidence when it contributed nothing.\n\n# Fix\n\nAt the bottom of `run_ingest_path`, after normalization:\n\n- If the normalized source.md is zero bytes (or only whitespace/frontmatter, nothing semantic), refuse the ingest with `warning: skipping empty source <path>`.\n- Accept a `--allow-empty` flag for rare cases (placeholder files).\n- Alternative: allow the ingest but mark the source `kind: empty` in metadata.json and skip it in compile + ask.\n\nOption A (simpler, more users expected): warn and skip. An accidentally empty file is almost always a mistake.\n\nSame check applies to files containing only YAML frontmatter with no body.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb ingest empty.md` prints a warning and does NOT create normalized/ entries (or creates them with `empty: true` metadata that compile + ask skip).\n- `kb compile` does not invoke the LLM for empty sources.\n- `kb lint` does not warn about synthetic-region citations for empty sources.\n- Non-empty files unaffected.","kind":"task","title":"fix(ingest): skip empty files with a warning instead of running LLM on zero bytes"}	blake3:lEisf5CziAhUBk_VnZaQIC1iusz-pIRlLW3lM0kB3ms
1776640884513862	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtiQU		item.create	bn-1yq	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb inspect` has several rough edges:\n\n## I1: src-xxxx identifiers don't resolve\n\nAfter ingest AND compile:\n\n    kb inspect src-302b46ff\n    # error: 'src-302b46ff' was not found. Try an exact ID, ..., a frontmatter id, or a path under the KB root.\n\nBut `src-302b46ff` *is* the source_document_id, it exists in normalized/, and there's a wiki/sources/src-302b46ff.md page with that id in frontmatter. The resolver is looking in the dependency graph but source documents aren't nodes. At minimum, inspect should resolve bare src-xxxx IDs to their normalized/ dir OR their wiki/sources/<id>.md page.\n\n## I2: resolved paths outside the KB root succeed\n\n    kb inspect /tmp/kb-pass6/raw/rust-async.md   # OUTSIDE kb root\n    # kind: entity\n    # (happily reads the external file, scrapes citations)\n\nArbitrary file paths outside the KB root should be refused — or at minimum, `kind: external` and no attempt to treat them as KB entities.\n\n## I3: freshness always reports \"unknown\"\n\nEvery inspect output shows `freshness: unknown`, even for a concept page that was just regenerated. If the dependency graph knows the last-built revision and the source hash, freshness should be resolvable to `fresh` / `stale`.\n\n## I4: build_records and generating_jobs are always (none)\n\nEven after compile has produced build records naming these pages (wiki pages list `build_record_id:` in frontmatter), `kb inspect <page>` reports empty for these sections. The resolver isn't looking them up.\n\n## I5: \"citations\" shows backlink markdown literally\n\n    citations:\n      - - [[wiki/sources/src-302b46ff]]\n\nThe list item prefix `- ` is part of the emitted markdown and gets prefixed again by the inspect renderer → `- - [[...]]`. Not a correctness bug, just ugly. Parse the citations list and render cleanly, or surround in code fence.\n\n# Fix\n\nI1 is the biggest — make `src-<hex>` a first-class resolver type that maps to `wiki/sources/<src>.md` when available or normalized/<src>/ otherwise.\n\nI2 — require absolute resolved path to be under root OR a known schema (concept:, src-, etc.); otherwise error.\n\nI3 — compute freshness from source_revision_id comparison with normalized/.\n\nI4 — scan state/build_records/ and state/jobs/ for records naming the resolved file in output_paths / affected_outputs.\n\nI5 — pre-parse then render.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb inspect src-302b46ff` resolves to the source page and prints its key metadata.\n- `kb inspect /etc/hosts` errors with a clear \"outside KB root\" message.\n- `kb inspect concept:tokio` on a fresh compile shows `freshness: fresh`, and lists the build_record and generating_job.\n- Inspect citations section renders each citation on its own line without the double-bullet artifact.","kind":"task","title":"fix(inspect): resolve src-xxxx ids, reject out-of-root paths, populate freshness and build_records"}	blake3:juL9XL4t8J7j401rggPlMGTM7a399_6jo7KYrPWNh1g
1776640887733101	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtigU		item.create	bn-2ho	{"description":"# Context\n\nTwo small UX issues in `kb search`:\n\n## S1: empty query accepted silently\n\n    kb search \"\"\n    # No results for ''\n    # Tip: run 'kb compile' to build the search index.\n\nMatches the empty-arg class of bug fixed for `kb ask` and `kb inspect` in the prior sweep (see recent commits `2b01f9d fix(cli): ask and inspect reject empty or whitespace-only arguments`). Search was missed.\n\nSame for `kb search \"   \"`.\n\n## S2: misleading \"run kb compile\" tip after compile\n\nAfter a successful compile, `kb search foo` with no matches still prints:\n\n    No results for 'foo'\n    Tip: run 'kb compile' to build the search index.\n\nThe index exists — confirmed by any matching query returning scored results. The tip fires unconditionally on zero-result queries. Should only fire if `state/indexes/<search-index>.json` (or wherever) is missing.\n\n# Fix\n\nS1: add `if query.trim().is_empty() { bail!(\"search: query cannot be empty\"); }` at the start of `run_search` in crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs, matching the pattern used for ask/inspect.\n\nS2: before printing the tip, check whether the lexical index file actually exists. If present, replace the tip with something like \"Try a broader query or `kb search --json` for ranking details.\"\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb search \"\"` errors.\n- `kb search \"   \"` errors.\n- `kb search unlikelyqueryvalue` on a compiled KB shows no tip or a different tip.\n- `kb search unlikelyqueryvalue` on an un-compiled KB still shows the compile tip.\n- Integration test for each.","kind":"task","title":"fix(search): reject empty query; don't show 'run kb compile' tip after index exists"}	blake3:f_DXM5BHGfemmRPg8KmeBm4_sHr7-TjMyfQVvB-ln70
1776640891379158	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtiwU		item.create	bn-1vz	{"description":"# Context\n\nConcept extraction is far too fine-grained. A 10-file test corpus (~1kB each) produced 106 concept pages. Many are sub-concepts, re-phrasings, or lifted literally from bullet points:\n\nExamples from a real compile:\n- `edit.md`, `drop.md`, `pick.md`, `fixup.md`, `squash.md`, `reword.md` — each is a git rebase action; they are members of ONE concept (rebase todo actions), which was also extracted.\n- `5-second-busy-timeout-default.md` — specific to \"PRAGMA busy_timeout = 5000\". Sub-concept of a concept.\n- `empty-directory-removal.md`, `idempotent-directory-creation.md` — these are just fact-level observations about mkdir/rmdir, not reusable concepts.\n- `cross-language-explanation-of-rust-async.md` — a *topic* mentioned once in one doc, not a concept.\n- `already-pushed-branch.md`, `long-running-reader-checkpoint-starvation.md`, `nfs-incompatibility-of-wal.md` — paraphrases of single sentences.\n- `ingest-handling-of-frontmatter.md` — speaking-to-the-ingester; shouldn't be extracted as the corpus's topical concept.\n\nReview queue partially compensates with duplicate-detection (the rebase actions were flagged as dups of \"rebase-todo-actions\"), but:\n\n- Duplicates are caught only at the end; the concept pages already exist on disk\n- Sub-concepts (`5-second-busy-timeout-default`) aren't flagged as duplicates of parents\n- Users staring at 100+ concept pages from 10 notes will lose trust in the tool\n\n# Observations\n\nThe extract_concepts.md prompt (see prompts/extract_concepts.md in kb.toml data dir) asks the LLM to extract concepts. The model is currently erring heavily on the side of \"anything nameable.\" It needs:\n\n- Concrete rejection criteria: \"don't extract specific magic numbers, don't extract parentheticals, don't extract single-sentence paraphrases\"\n- A minimum evidence threshold: at least N words of corpus support, or at least 2 distinct mentions across the doc\n- Examples of what to skip (a handful in the prompt is worth 1000 words of rules)\n\nSeparately, the merge prompt could also consider sub-concept hierarchy (not just similarity-based merging).\n\n# Fix\n\nThis is a prompt-engineering bone, not a code one.\n\n1. Revise `prompts/extract_concepts.md` to:\n   - Add \"do not extract\" examples (specific numeric defaults, sub-items of lists, code fragments, single-sentence rephrasings)\n   - Require a minimum reusability test: \"would this concept reasonably be cited from a different document?\"\n   - Cap concept-per-source at ~3-5 for a sub-1k-word note (the model is emitting ~10)\n\n2. Revise `prompts/merge_concept_candidates.md` to:\n   - Detect parent/child relations, not just near-duplicates (\"X is a member of Y\" → fold X into Y)\n\n3. After prompt changes, re-run on a golden corpus and compare concept counts.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Golden-corpus compile produces concept counts in the same order-of-magnitude as the number of source docs (± 3x, not 10x).\n- Examples of over-extraction from this finding no longer appear.\n- Existing grounding / citation coverage doesn't regress.","kind":"task","title":"tune(prompts): concept extraction overreaches — 10 notes → 106 concepts; tighten selection criteria"}	blake3:7Y-Uqi5zti3C4Fs-zKMVyouB84CyLaHfCuziYQHHH_w
1776640894642386	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjAU		item.create	bn-1e9	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb review approve <id>` marks a review item approved but does not apply the change. The final line tells users to do the edit by hand:\n\n    $ kb review approve merge:sqlite-wal-mode\n    Approved: merge:sqlite-wal-mode (concept_merge)\n      note: the proposed change is not applied automatically — perform the edit manually, then run 'kb compile'.\n\nFor a proposed concept merge, this means the user has to:\n1. Open the proposal JSON in reviews/merges/\n2. Read which concept pages to fold\n3. Manually edit the canonical concept to absorb aliases/members\n4. Delete the other concept files\n5. Run compile to regenerate backlinks\n\nThat's five steps of manual work for something the tool already has structured data about. Most users won't do it.\n\nThe `kb review show` output doesn't mention this manual-apply expectation either — users expect approve to ... apply.\n\n# Fix\n\nEither\n\n1. Make `approve` apply the change:\n   - For concept_merge reviews: write the proposed canonical concept page (merged aliases/members), delete the subsumed concept files, queue a targeted recompile.\n   - For alias/promotion/canonicalization: similar structured application.\n   - Keep `--dry-run` to preview.\n\n2. Or, keep the decision-only design and rename:\n   - `kb review decide approve/reject` — just records decision\n   - `kb review apply [--only-approved]` — applies all approved decisions\n\nOption 1 is simpler and matches user expectations. Option 2 is fine as long as the UX is obvious.\n\n`kb review show` output should mention up front whether approval auto-applies.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb review approve merge:<id>` produces either (a) the applied merge and a reminder to compile, or (b) a clear note that the decision is recorded and `kb review apply` will execute it.\n- `kb review show` tells the user what happens on approve.\n- Post-apply, `wiki/concepts/<subsumed>.md` is gone and the canonical page carries the aliases.","kind":"task","title":"fix(review): approve should apply merges automatically, or rename to 'decide'"}	blake3:6lYyaJc6xQ8fJwWNIfcBNgSbT3hfsHo5oZY_aIttsrw
1776640898046611	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjQU		item.create	bn-90d	{"description":"# Context\n\nWhen a second kb command waits on the KB root lock, the wait message says:\n\n    waiting for KB root lock (held by unknown, 0s elapsed)\n\nThe lock metadata *is* being written (KbLock stamps pid + command into state/locks/), so \"held by\" should be able to say e.g. \"pid 12345 (compile)\". Something in the wait-message formatting is reading a null or empty holder field.\n\nRepro in /tmp/kb-pass6/kb (two shells):\n\n    # shell A\n    kb ingest /tmp/foo.md\n\n    # shell B (while A is running)\n    kb ingest /tmp/bar.md\n    # → waiting for KB root lock (held by unknown, 0s elapsed)\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-cli/src/jobs.rs::KbLock::acquire`, the waiting message is constructed when the current lockfile is read. Parse the metadata file (pid, command) and include both. Example format:\n\n    waiting for KB root lock (held by pid 12345 running `kb compile`, 3s elapsed)\n\nIf the metadata file is absent or unparseable, report accordingly:\n\n    waiting for KB root lock (holder metadata missing, 0s elapsed)\n\nAlso useful: include which elapsed-time threshold prints the progress line (every 5s was added recently — keep that cadence but make the identity visible on every print).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Hold the lock in one shell; in another shell, `kb status` wait message names the holding pid + command.\n- If the holder's metadata file is missing, wait message says so explicitly (not \"unknown\").\n- Integration test in kb-cli/tests/ that seeds a lock with a specific pid+command and asserts the wait message.","kind":"task","title":"fix(jobs): lock wait message says 'held by unknown' — surface holder pid + command"}	blake3:xjY4SSfgoEUgAp7vw3twoqAOAz5PpOklY0gSdCyc0w8
1776640901123432	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjgU		item.create	bn-2cr	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb status` output has two readability issues:\n\n## ST1: \"changed inputs\" paths are opaque\n\n    changed inputs not yet compiled:\n      - /tmp/kb-pass6/kb/normalized/src-0639ebb0\n      - /tmp/kb-pass6/kb/normalized/src-20b5f90c\n      - /tmp/kb-pass6/kb/normalized/src-2bd76f9c\n\nUsers don't remember which `src-xxxxxxxx` is which file. The information is in `raw/inbox/<src>/<rev>/<filename>` — show the original filename or path alongside:\n\n    changed inputs not yet compiled:\n      - concurrent-a.md          (src-0639ebb0)\n      - big.md                   (src-20b5f90c)\n      - weird/émoji-💀.md        (src-2bd76f9c)\n\n## ST2: wiki source page counts show \"other: 10\"\n\n    wiki source pages: 10\n      other: 10\n\nThe breakdown bucket is literally named \"other\" for every source. This bucket-by-kind display is meaningless when there's only one kind. Either:\n- Hide the breakdown when there's only one bucket\n- Rename the default bucket to something descriptive (e.g. \"source\")\n- If kinds are meaningful (papers, web, repos, etc.), populate them based on the raw/ subdirectory the file came from\n\nThe raw/ scaffold already has `papers/`, `web/`, `repos/`, `datasets/`, `images/` subdirectories (created by `kb init`). If ingest records the original category dir, status could show a useful breakdown.\n\n## ST3: failed job runs accumulate forever\n\nEvery time a user types a wrong path or a binary file, `kb status` records a failed job. The failed list shows as \"failed job runs (2):\" in perpetuity, with no way to clear. Over weeks this will pile up and drown signal.\n\nEither:\n- Only show the most recent N failures (say 5)\n- Add `kb jobs clear --status failed` or `kb status --forget-failures`\n- Distinguish user-error failures (bad args, file not found) from actual tool failures, and auto-expire the former after some TTL\n\n# Fix\n\nST1: In status's \"changed_inputs\" loop, join with `normalized/<src>/metadata.json` to find the original path (stored in source_revision metadata via ingest) and print it.\n\nST2: Remove the breakdown when single-bucket. If populating real buckets, plumb the raw-subdir through ingest → normalized metadata → status rollup.\n\nST3: Cap failed-job display to most recent 10, or add a prune command.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- ST1: changed-inputs list shows the source filename, not a bare src-id.\n- ST2: \"wiki source pages: N\" shows either no breakdown or a useful one.\n- ST3: after 20 failed commands, status shows at most ~10 failures with a \"... and N more (run `kb jobs`)\" hint.","kind":"task","title":"fix(status): map src-ids to filenames, drop 'other' bucket, cap failed-job history"}	blake3:6o9XwKw7wfCYNX6yKZu5NhNex_wwoLvUZnIERBVCRPw
1776640904105224	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjwU		item.create	bn-2c0	{"description":"# Context\n\n`just install` runs `cargo install --path crates/kb-cli` without `--locked`. That causes cargo to dependency-resolve to the latest available versions on the registry, ignoring Cargo.lock.\n\nOn a system with rustc 1.93.0 this breaks because transitive deps (e.g. `constant_time_eq 0.4.3`) now require rustc 1.95+:\n\n    error: failed to compile `kb-cli v0.1.0`\n    Caused by:\n      rustc 1.93.0 is not supported by the following package:\n        constant_time_eq@0.4.3 requires rustc 1.95.0\n\nCargo.lock already pins a compatible `constant_time_eq 0.4.2` — running `cargo install --locked --path crates/kb-cli` works fine.\n\n# Fix\n\nChange `justfile` to pass `--locked`:\n\n```make\ninstall:\n    cargo install --locked --path crates/kb-cli\n```\n\nOptionally add `--locked` to `just check` and `just build` too, so CI and local reproducibility are consistent with what's on main.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `just install` succeeds on a machine with rustc 1.93.0 and no prior cargo cache.\n- Pinned versions in Cargo.lock are honored.\n- CI (if any) uses --locked for the same reason.","kind":"task","title":"fix(build): 'just install' must use --locked to avoid MSRV drift"}	blake3:IjOz4ft1rw5NxModT8WIR3Etd3cmmGJBs9k-WQI2tOY
