1776645675811131	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmwU		item.create	bn-36x	{"description":"# Context\n\nThe bn-40r empty-file skip path produces a stale \"interrupted\" job manifest that pollutes `kb status` and `kb doctor` forever.\n\nRepro in /tmp/kb-pass7/kb (or any KB):\n\n    touch empty.md\n    kb ingest empty.md\n    # warning: skipping empty source ... (use --allow-empty to override)\n    # No sources ingested\n    # exit 0\n\n    kb doctor\n    # [WARN] interrupted_jobs: Detected 1 interrupted job(s).\n    #   details: job_ids=...-ingest\n\n    kb status\n    # ⚠ interrupted job runs (1):\n    #   ...-ingest | Interrupted | ingest [10ms]\n    #   → Inspect the logs and rerun: kb ingest\n\nThe job manifest at `state/jobs/<id>.json` shows:\n\n    \"status\": \"interrupted\",\n    \"exit_code\": 1,\n    \"ended_at_millis\": 1776645010377,\n    ...\n    log: \"interrupted: process no longer running\"\n\nBut the command actually exited cleanly with code 0 (\"No sources ingested\" is the printed result). The job-status updater in the empty-skip path is being missed.\n\n# Root cause\n\n`run_ingest` (or wherever the ingest job is registered) opens a job manifest before checking emptiness. When all sources are empty, `ingest_paths_with_flags` returns an empty Vec and the function exits OK — but the job-completion code path is bypassed, so the manifest stays in its initial state. The stale-job reaper then catches it on subsequent commands and labels it \"interrupted: process no longer running\".\n\nThis is a regression of bn-40r (the empty-skip fix). The fix added the early skip but didn't extend the job-lifecycle handling to mark the job as \"succeeded (no-op)\" or skip writing the manifest when nothing is ingested.\n\n# Fix\n\nEither:\n\nA. Mark the job successful when ingest skips all empty inputs:\n   - In the no-sources path, write `status: \"succeeded\"`, `exit_code: 0`, set `ended_at_millis`, before returning.\n\nB. Don't open a job manifest until at least one source survives the empty check:\n   - Defer `KbLock::acquire`/job-manifest-write until after the emptiness gate.\n\nA is simpler and matches existing structure. B is cleaner but touches more code.\n\nEither way: don't surface a clean exit-0 ingest as an \"interrupted\" job.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After `kb ingest empty.md` (cleanly skipped), neither `kb status` nor `kb doctor` reports interrupted jobs.\n- A truly killed ingest (SIGKILL between job-open and job-close) is still detected as interrupted.\n- Integration test: ingest an empty file, then assert `kb doctor` exits 0 with no warnings.","kind":"task","title":"fix(jobs): empty-file ingest produces stale 'interrupted' job manifest"}	blake3:l9WRLxeEj0qkHyo9dRNg9uSM0GMNcbk6aKfbNOYb_I8
1776645679674371	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtnAU		item.create	bn-1iw	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb status` reports `wiki source pages: 0` while a `kb compile` is mid-flight, even though wiki/sources/*.md files have already been written to disk by the source_summary pass.\n\nRepro:\n\n    kb compile &        # long-running, in another shell\n    sleep 30            # wait for some source pages to be emitted\n    ls wiki/sources/    # 9 files exist\n    kb status           # \"wiki source pages: 0    (run 'kb compile' to generate)\"\n\nThis is misleading mid-compile, but the bigger issue is that `gather_status` reports the count from a state index that's only refreshed at compile end. If anything causes that index update to be skipped (compile killed mid-finalize, partial failure), status will under-report indefinitely until the next successful compile.\n\n# Hypothesis\n\n`gather_status` likely reads counts from `state/manifest.json` or `state/indexes/*.json`. These are written atomically at the end of compile but not incrementally during it.\n\nThe right answer for users: count by walking `wiki/sources/*.md` and `wiki/concepts/*.md` directly. The directory walk is O(few hundred files) for a realistic KB and is fast. It also gives accurate counts even when the index is stale.\n\nAlternative: keep the current index-based count BUT add a comparison against a directory walk and warn if they disagree:\n\n    wiki source pages: 9 (state index says 0; possible stale index — run 'kb compile')\n\n# Fix\n\nReplace the index-based count in `gather_status` with a direct count of `*.md` files under `wiki/sources/` and `wiki/concepts/`. The current `(run 'kb compile' to generate)` tip should fire only when the count is actually 0.\n\nAlso: drop the tip when counts > 0 — it's misleading after the first compile and reads as \"hey, you should run compile\" even when the data is fresh.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Mid-compile, `kb status` reports the actual on-disk wiki page count (which grows as compile progresses).\n- Post-compile, count matches `find wiki/sources -name '*.md' | wc -l`.\n- \"(run 'kb compile' to generate)\" tip fires only when count is exactly 0.\n- Integration test: write 5 wiki/sources/*.md files manually, run `kb status`, assert it reports 5.","kind":"task","title":"fix(status): wiki page counts read from on-disk files, not stale manifest index"}	blake3:jlZIzBxC6of3wyBoLRLWzz6J4GeQVBmMfHFAdsOfvVQ
1776645683976045	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtnQU		item.create	bn-181	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb lint` runs against partial state during a mid-flight `kb compile`, producing false-positive warnings about missing citations in source pages whose synthesis is still in progress.\n\nRepro:\n\n    kb compile &\n    # (some wiki/sources/*.md have been written; others not; concept pages not yet started)\n    kb lint\n\nOutput includes warnings like:\n\n    [warn] missing-citations: 2 issue(s)\n    - [Warning] wiki/sources/src-0e2e3f8b.md:16 synthetic region is missing citations in the page body\n    - [Warning] wiki/sources/src-0e2e3f8b.md:21 synthetic region is missing citations in the page body\n\nThese are real defects in the on-disk file at that moment — but the file is mid-rewrite. After compile completes the issues disappear.\n\n# Why it matters\n\n- CI pipelines that run `lint` after `compile` may catch the file in a half-written state if compile-and-lint are not strictly serialized\n- Users running `lint` while a background compile is in flight get scary warnings that resolve themselves silently\n- `lint --strict` would fail in this window\n\n# Fix\n\nLint should refuse to run, OR print a \"compile in progress, results may be partial\" warning, when the root lock is held. The `KbLock` type already records the holder pid and command (see bn-90d).\n\nSuggested behavior:\n\n    kb lint\n    # warning: kb compile is currently running (pid 12345); lint output may be stale.\n    #          run again after compile finishes for authoritative results.\n    # ... continues with normal lint output\n\nOr with `--strict`:\n\n    kb lint --strict\n    # error: kb compile is currently running (pid 12345); refusing to run --strict\n    #        run again after compile finishes.\n\nAcquiring the lock isn't right (lint is read-only and should be able to run); but a lock-presence check is sufficient.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb lint` while compile is running prints a warning naming the holder.\n- `kb lint --strict` while compile is running exits with a clear error.\n- `kb lint` with no compile running behaves identically to today.\n- Integration test that holds a fake compile lock and asserts the warning appears.","kind":"task","title":"fix(lint): warn (or refuse --strict) when a kb compile is in flight"}	blake3:3C0gnX0aWXyJUzFesAj3Jgeefib05K3YklWnzzimgaM
1776645687259839	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtngU		item.create	bn-127	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb inspect` has two remaining inconsistencies after bn-1yq:\n\n## L1: extension required for wiki-page paths\n\nUsers naturally refer to wiki pages without `.md` (Obsidian/wiki convention). Today:\n\n    kb inspect wiki/sources/src-0e2e3f8b\n    # error: 'wiki/sources/src-0e2e3f8b' was not found. Try an exact ID, ...\n    \n    kb inspect wiki/sources/src-0e2e3f8b.md\n    # works fine\n\nThe resolver should try with-and-without `.md` for paths under `wiki/`. The bn-1yq `is_source_id` check handles bare `src-` ids; this is the analogue for wiki page paths.\n\n## L2: arbitrary KB-internal paths get a confusing `kind`\n\n    kb inspect raw/inbox\n    # kind: source_revision    ← wrong; raw/inbox is a directory, not a revision\n\nThe `inspect_kind` function classifies any path starting with `raw/` as a `source_revision`, but `raw/inbox` itself is just the parent dir. Same logic likely misclassifies `normalized/`, `state/`, `wiki/`.\n\n# Fix\n\nL1: in `run_inspect`, when target starts with `wiki/` and `root.join(target)` doesn't exist but `root.join(format!(\"{target}.md\"))` does, redirect to the `.md` form.\n\nL2: in `inspect_kind`, when the resolved path is a directory, return `kind: directory` (or skip the heuristic prefix-classification entirely and use file-system metadata).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb inspect wiki/sources/src-0e2e3f8b` resolves to the `.md` page and prints normal output.\n- `kb inspect raw/inbox` (a directory) reports `kind: directory`, not `source_revision`.\n- `kb inspect raw/inbox/src-foo/rev-bar/file.md` (a real revision) still reports `kind: source_revision`.\n- Tests for both L1 and L2 cases.","kind":"task","title":"fix(inspect): accept wiki paths without .md; classify directories as kind=directory"}	blake3:CaNg0K3XV-EUiZim1bXaO8PF1EBZ2x0QNiUQm3fOrn0
1776645691645195	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtnwU		item.create	bn-2q6	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb review approve` for a `lint:duplicate-concepts:...` item errors instead of applying the merge:\n\n    kb review approve lint:duplicate-concepts:concept:byzantine-consensus:concept:raft-consensus\n    error: apply concept merge for review 'lint:duplicate-concepts:concept:byzantine-consensus:concept:raft-consensus':\n           canonical concept page missing at reviews/merges/lint-duplicate-concepts-concept-byzantine-consensus-concept-raft-consensus.json;\n           cannot apply merge 'lint:duplicate-concepts:concept:byzantine-consensus:concept:raft-consensus'\n\n`kb review show` shows both `merge:...` and `lint:duplicate-concepts:...` items have `kind: concept_merge`. But the bn-1e9 auto-apply path only knows how to handle the `merge:...` shape — it tries to read the destination JSON path as if it were a concept page.\n\n# Root cause\n\nIn `crates/kb-cli/src/review.rs` the apply branch for `concept_merge` assumes the review's `destination` is `wiki/concepts/<canonical>.md`. For the lint-duplicate-concepts review, `destination` is `reviews/merges/<id>.json` — the proposal sidecar, not a concept page.\n\nThe apply code treats `destination` as a path to absorb members into, then tries to read it as a concept page, which fails.\n\nThe two review subkinds need different apply logic, OR the lint-duplicate-concepts review needs to encode its canonical concept page separately (e.g., via a new field like `canonical_concept_path`).\n\n# Fix\n\nTwo reasonable approaches:\n\nA. **Discriminate by the review's id prefix**: when the review id starts with `lint:duplicate-concepts:`, parse out the canonical concept name from the id (`concept:raft-consensus` is the canonical, `concept:byzantine-consensus` is being merged into it) and apply via the same `apply_concept_merge` helper but with the parsed canonical path.\n\nB. **Normalize the review record**: when `lint:duplicate-concepts:...` items are queued, populate the destination with the canonical concept page path (not the proposal JSON). The id already encodes `<merged>:<canonical>`.\n\nB is cleaner — fix the data shape at the producer, not the consumer. A is a smaller change but adds discriminator logic.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb review approve lint:duplicate-concepts:concept:X:concept:Y` applies the merge: X is folded into Y (or vice versa per the proposal), the subsumed file is deleted, summary is printed.\n- `kb review approve merge:<id>` continues to work as today.\n- Integration test for the lint-duplicate-concepts apply path.\n- Idempotent re-apply still no-ops.","kind":"task","title":"fix(review): approve fails for lint:duplicate-concepts: items — destination is proposal JSON, not concept page"}	blake3:pKfPc72rx8hyO15NM7elePSEtSMqoRPARgPS8-VwD74
1776645695947901	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtoAU		item.create	bn-2xi	{"description":"# Context\n\nThe duplicate-concepts lint produces false positives by matching on partial string similarity rather than concept-level semantics:\n\n    lint:duplicate-concepts:concept:byzantine-consensus:concept:raft-consensus [concept_merge]\n      Near-duplicate of 'concept:raft-consensus' (similarity: 0.88; matched: 'BFT consensus' ≈ 'Raft consensus')\n\n    lint:duplicate-concepts:concept:conflict-free-replicated-data-type:concept:happens-before-relation\n      Near-duplicate of 'concept:happens-before-relation' (similarity: 0.88; matched: 'causal ordering' ≈ 'causal order')\n\nThese are false:\n- Byzantine consensus and Raft consensus are not duplicates — they tolerate fundamentally different fault models. The match is on the substring \"consensus\".\n- CRDTs and happens-before-relation are related but distinct concepts. The match is on the substring \"causal\".\n\nA user who scans the review queue without context would never approve these, but they pollute the queue and erode trust. Worse, with bn-1e9's auto-apply (once the lint-apply path is fixed per `l-review-apply-lint.md`), an unattended approval would silently destroy a real concept.\n\n# Root cause\n\nThe duplicate-detection code (likely in `crates/kb-lint/` or `crates/kb-compile/src/concept_merge.rs`) computes pairwise string similarity over concept names + aliases and flags pairs above a threshold. Substring overlap on common technical words like \"consensus\", \"causal\", \"lock\" produces high false-positive rates.\n\n# Fix\n\nThree improvements that compound:\n\n1. **Stop-word filter**: strip common technical terms (\"consensus\", \"causal\", \"lock\", \"data\", \"store\", \"system\", \"tree\") before similarity scoring. These words are the topic, not the discriminator.\n\n2. **Require both name AND definition similarity**: today's check seems to use name/alias only. Comparing the `definition_hint` or summary text is a much stronger signal.\n\n3. **Raise the threshold or require multiple matches**: 0.88 single-match is too lenient. Either bump to 0.95, or require at least two independent matches (name + alias, or name + definition).\n\nEven just doing #2 (compare definitions) would eliminate the cases observed here — Byzantine vs Raft definitions share basically no n-grams.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- The two false positives above no longer appear in the review queue for the pass-7 corpus.\n- Genuine duplicates (e.g., concept emitting \"Tokio\" alongside concept emitting \"tokio runtime\") still flag.\n- Unit tests in the duplicate detector for the false-positive examples + a true-positive example.","kind":"task","title":"fix(lint): duplicate-concepts false-positives on substring matches (Byzantine vs Raft 'consensus')"}	blake3:YHin2Xxk59mYN1m7eRa1qTar3mxcIdhJexCKwcWbFcw
1776649605316971	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtoQU		item.move	bn-127	{"state":"done"}	blake3:Va9XKi0eGWmZ3z717wuu_9SjVplknreBWAuiscomUIs
1776649658782578	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtogU		item.move	bn-181	{"state":"done"}	blake3:BrecQLjGlesekmiYAHPflGVk2T0nlEFMD1jqcLMN10I
