1776650023205892	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtpgU		item.move	bn-36x	{"state":"done"}	blake3:J0dt-tkIgTcFO2QodSNSnX8VQTn7syGyiry-5liD_bE
1776651172803924	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtpwU		item.create	bn-iiq	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb ask --format=png` is silently accepted. It runs a normal LLM ask and writes `answer.md` (regular markdown) — no PNG is generated, no warning is printed, no error is raised.\n\nRepro:\n\n    kb ask --format=png \"what is dropout\"\n    # Artifact written: outputs/questions/question-.../answer.md\n    # Citations: 4 valid, 0 unresolved\n    # exit 0\n\n    ls outputs/questions/question-.../\n    # answer.md  metadata.json  question.json  retrieval_plan.json\n    # (no .png, no image file of any kind)\n\n    grep requested_format answer.md\n    # requested_format: png    ← recorded as png, but file extension is .md\n\nThe frontmatter lies: `requested_format: png` but the file is markdown.\n\n`kb --help` for `ask` lists png as a supported format:\n\n    --format <FORMAT>  Artifact format for the answer (md, marp, json, png)\n\nBut there's no actual png renderer. Same for `json` likely (`answer.md` is still markdown).\n\n# Fix\n\nEither:\n\nA. Remove `png` and `json` from the clap `possible_values` list until they're implemented. Honesty over aspiration.\n\nB. Implement them:\n   - `png` — render the markdown answer to an image (pandoc+rsvg or imgkit). Probably overkill for v1.\n   - `json` — write the answer as a structured JSON doc (title, sections, citations array) instead of markdown.\n\nC. If the format is declared but not implemented, return a clean error:\n   `error: --format png is not yet supported; supported formats: md, marp`\n\nOption A or C is the correct v1 answer. Option B can wait.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask --format=png \"…\"` either (a) errors with a clear \"not yet supported\" message and exit 1, or (b) actually produces a png file.\n- `kb ask --format=json \"…\"` similarly either errors or produces a valid JSON artifact.\n- `kb ask --format=md` and `--format=marp` continue to work as today.\n- Integration test verifying the error/success path for each declared format.","kind":"task","title":"fix(ask): --format=png|json are declared but silently fall back to md"}	blake3:3WhXE-IFSk4yFz-BddNKCo0clsOcNyvZpVx3FqnN6H0
1776651176643770	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtqAU		item.create	bn-1fq	{"description":"# Context\n\nSources that have been ingested live in the KB forever. There is no way to remove them.\n\nRepro:\n\n    kb ingest /tmp/notes/foo.md\n    kb compile\n    # → wiki/concepts/foo-concept.md and wiki/sources/src-xxxx.md exist\n    rm /tmp/notes/foo.md\n    kb status\n    # ingested sources: 1          ← still 1\n    # wiki source pages: 1         ← page still exists\n    # (no \"removed source\" indicator, no warning)\n    kb compile\n    # no change — the deleted source stays ingested\n\nA user who deletes a source file expects that the wiki page and concepts derived from it either disappear on the next compile, or at least get flagged. Today, both stay forever.\n\nSame issue if the user renames a file:\n\n    mv foo.md foo-v2.md\n    kb ingest foo-v2.md\n    # → new src-id for the same content (distinct from the original)\n    # both pages remain; the corpus now has duplicate content under two src-ids\n\n# Fix\n\nA complete fix spans three features:\n\n**F1: `kb forget <src-id>` or `kb forget <path>`** — explicit removal. Deletes the `normalized/<src>/` dir, marks the source for pruning on next compile, and records a reason in the job log.\n\n**F2: Auto-detect removed sources** — when `kb compile` runs, check that every `normalized/<src>/metadata.json`'s `canonical_path` still exists on disk. If not, flag in status:\n\n    sources with missing origin (run `kb forget` to remove):\n      - foo.md   (src-abc, origin /tmp/notes/foo.md deleted)\n\n**F3: prune on compile** — once marked for forget, compile removes the wiki/sources/<src>.md page and recomputes concept backlinks so concepts whose only source was the forgotten one become orphans (which lint can surface).\n\nStart with F1 + F2. F3 is follow-up.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb forget <src-id>` removes normalized/ dir, next compile prunes wiki/sources/<src>.md and updates backlinks.\n- `kb forget <path>` resolves to src-id via `raw/inbox/<src>/source_document.json::stable_location` and does the same.\n- After deleting a source file on disk, `kb status` surfaces the missing origin.\n- Integration tests for each case.\n- If forgetting would orphan concept pages, list them and ask for confirmation (or offer `--cascade`).","kind":"task","title":"feat(lifecycle): kb forget — remove ingested sources and prune wiki pages"}	blake3:w0XRvvUfSJHk2cEs41kFyGMIHOBqBvChx1z3z0Q8xW8
1776651180636702	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtqQU		item.create	bn-2hz	{"description":"# Context\n\n`wiki/index.md` (the top-level wiki index) generates links that only work when viewed from the KB root, not from inside `wiki/`:\n\n    # wiki/index.md contents:\n    - [Adam optimizer](wiki/sources/src-b5e205f9.md)\n    - [Attention](wiki/sources/src-9e37349d.md)\n\nBut this file is at `wiki/index.md`. The correct relative link from that location is `sources/src-b5e205f9.md`, not `wiki/sources/src-b5e205f9.md`. In Obsidian, VS Code markdown preview, or GitHub's renderer, clicking these links 404s.\n\nTest:\n\n    cd /tmp/kb-pass8/kb/wiki\n    ls wiki/sources/src-b5e205f9.md   # No such file or directory\n    ls sources/src-b5e205f9.md        # works\n\nThe same issue likely affects `wiki/concepts/index.md` and `wiki/sources/index.md` — verify all index pages.\n\n# Root cause\n\nLikely in `crates/kb-compile/src/` wherever `index_pages` are emitted. The emitter is using paths rooted at the KB root, but markdown link resolution is relative to the file containing the link.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn the index-page renderer, compute links relative to each index file's location:\n\n- `wiki/index.md` → `sources/src-xxxx.md` (strip `wiki/` prefix)\n- `wiki/sources/index.md` → `src-xxxx.md` (strip `wiki/sources/` prefix)\n- `wiki/concepts/index.md` → `foo.md` (strip `wiki/concepts/` prefix)\n\nUse `std::path::Path::strip_prefix` on the emitted link path relative to the index file's parent dir.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `wiki/index.md` links resolve correctly when viewed from Obsidian / any relative-link renderer.\n- `wiki/sources/index.md` and `wiki/concepts/index.md` similarly.\n- Integration test: build a KB, open each index page, check every link with `Path::exists()` resolved against the file's parent.\n- Obsidian-style `[[wiki/...]]` backlinks elsewhere in the tree (which are already produced correctly per bn-yqz) are unaffected.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): wiki/index.md links use root-relative paths; broken when viewed from wiki/"}	blake3:CGt-n4vNCStiDfdELzrcxjlXROcL9FESFLE6DwvF8cY
1776651184449476	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtqgU		item.create	bn-2vm	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb compile --dry-run` acquires the root lock and holds it for the duration of the dry-run, blocking any other mutating command and leaving an \"interrupted job\" manifest behind if the caller pipes output through `head` (which closes the pipe early via SIGPIPE).\n\nRepro:\n\n    # In shell A\n    kb compile                # real compile, long-running\n    # In shell B\n    kb compile --dry-run | head -3\n    # hangs waiting for the root lock\n    # kill the head -3, the kb process is left with an open job manifest\n    # next kb status / kb doctor surfaces it as \"interrupted\"\n\nDry-run reads the graph, prints what would happen, and writes nothing. It shouldn't need the exclusive mutating-command lock at all.\n\n# Root cause\n\n`execute_mutating_command_with_handle` (in `crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs`) wraps compile in a lock-acquire regardless of whether `--dry-run` is set. The lock + job-manifest lifecycle is orthogonal to whether any writes happen.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn the dispatch for `Command::Compile`, check `cli.dry_run` and route through a read-only path that:\n\n- Still loads graph / hash state (required to compute the would-process list)\n- Does NOT acquire the root lock\n- Does NOT write a job manifest\n- Prints the dry-run output and exits 0\n\nSimilar treatment for any other mutating command with a meaningful `--dry-run` mode (ingest --dry-run already exists).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb compile --dry-run` while a real `kb compile` is in flight in another shell: returns immediately with the dry-run output, no waiting.\n- `kb compile --dry-run` output is identical before and after the change.\n- Killing a dry-run mid-process leaves no \"interrupted\" job behind (no manifest was ever written).\n- Integration test: seed a held lock, run dry-run, assert it completes without waiting.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): --dry-run should not acquire root lock"}	blake3:d_56g298vFwHYYOMLhixalNDZfWVo1lHaAbrRp8AzYU
1776651195110329	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtqwU		item.create	bn-3qn	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb status` and `kb doctor` surface interrupted job runs from `state/jobs/*.json`. The list grows without bound:\n\n- Every SIGINT during a long compile adds one\n- Every SIGPIPE from a piped command adds one (see m-dryrun-lock.md)\n- Every OS crash / OOM adds one\n\nOver weeks of development the list balloons. Users see:\n\n    ⚠ interrupted job runs (47):\n      1776645010367774625-2481322-ingest | Interrupted | ingest [10ms]\n      1776650818172840134-2662472-compile | Interrupted | compile [57385ms]\n      ...\n\nEach one is flagged on every subsequent `kb status` with \"Inspect the logs and rerun\". There's no way to acknowledge or clear them.\n\nbn-2cr already capped failed jobs at 10 with a \"... N more\" hint. The same treatment is needed for interrupted jobs.\n\n# Fix\n\nTwo parts:\n\n**Part 1 — cap the display** (mirrors bn-2cr):\n- Text output: at most 5 interrupted jobs listed; append `... and N more (run 'kb jobs --interrupted' to inspect)` if exceeded.\n- JSON output: add `interrupted_jobs_total` for the true count; keep `interrupted_jobs` capped to the display limit.\n\n**Part 2 — add a prune command**:\n- `kb jobs prune --interrupted` — deletes interrupted job manifests older than some TTL (default 7d) or accepting a `--force` flag.\n- `kb jobs prune --failed` — same for failed.\n- Don't prune by default; explicit.\n\nDocument in `kb status` help that these lists are advisory and can be pruned.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- With 20 interrupted jobs, status shows at most 5 + a \"... and N more\" hint.\n- `kb jobs prune --interrupted` deletes them (or just old ones with --older-than).\n- `kb --json status` exposes both the truncated list and the total count.\n- Doctor-warning threshold stays the same — it warns on ANY interrupted job; just the rendering is capped.\n- Integration test for both display cap and prune.","kind":"task","title":"fix(status): cap interrupted-job list; add kb jobs prune --interrupted"}	blake3:M9Ox5FdROMOSo9luM__H2elEUKDm23bLQY_Mu2sCOEY
1776651200104928	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtrAU		item.create	bn-1l8	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb ask` writes `source_document_ids: [...]` into the answer's frontmatter listing every ingested source in the KB, not just the ones that actually contributed citations.\n\nExample from pass-8: question \"what is dropout used for?\" produced an answer citing 4 sources, but frontmatter lists all 10 ingested sources including ones about Adam, weight-decay, transformers, attention — concepts not even touched by the answer.\n\n    citations:\n      - wiki/concepts/dropout.md (fulldocument)\n      - wiki/sources/src-150287b4.md (fulldocument)\n      - wiki/sources/src-f278141a.md (fulldocument)\n      - wiki/sources/src-e5ebe14e.md (fulldocument)\n    source_document_ids:\n      - src-0ce55453          ← backprop-impl; not cited\n      - src-150287b4          ← regularization; cited\n      - src-37b86a3d          ← layer-norm; not cited\n      - src-3d37e559          ← transformer; not cited\n      - src-8f4f6d0b          ← SGD; not cited\n      - src-9e37349d          ← attention; not cited\n      - src-b5e205f9          ← Adam; not cited\n      - src-e5ebe14e          ← weight-decay; cited\n      - src-f278141a          ← dropout; cited\n      - src-fbcfed2b          ← learning-rate-schedules; not cited\n\nThe `source_document_ids` list is \"what was in scope during retrieval\" — but a user reading the promoted wiki page will interpret it as \"what grounds this answer\". Inflated.\n\nSame behavior when `--promote` moves the artifact into `wiki/questions/<slug>.md`: the promoted page carries the same inflated list in its frontmatter.\n\n# Fix\n\nDerive `source_document_ids` from the resolved citations, not from retrieval scope:\n\n1. Parse the answer markdown for `[N]` bracket references (or whatever citation format the ask pipeline uses).\n2. Map each [N] to its citation entry (already done — `citations:` is correct).\n3. For each citation, look up the source_document_id (concepts trace back to their sources; sources ARE the src-id).\n4. Dedup and emit only those.\n\nThe retrieval-scope list is still useful for debugging (which candidates were considered). Keep it, but under a different field name:\n\n    source_document_ids: [src-150287b4, src-e5ebe14e, src-f278141a]   # actually cited\n    retrieval_candidates: [src-0ce55453, ..., src-fbcfed2b]           # considered\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After ask, frontmatter `source_document_ids` contains only sources whose concept/source pages are in `citations:`.\n- A user inspecting a promoted wiki question page sees only the sources that support its claims.\n- Existing tests that check the list contents need to update to the new semantics.\n- Integration test: run an ask that resolves to 2 citations out of 10 ingested sources; assert `source_document_ids` has length 2.","kind":"task","title":"fix(ask): source_document_ids should list only cited sources, not retrieval scope"}	blake3:dGQ9v2a6IbG13HGeu5-Ebh6n7iqeRWYOTiNqdsGQKKA
1776651207548083	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtrQU		item.create	bn-3ml	{"description":"# Context\n\nConcept extraction still occasionally emits meta-observation concepts despite the explicit rule in `extract_concepts.md` (from bn-1vz):\n\n> 6. **Meta-observations about the corpus or tooling.** E.g. \"ingest handling of frontmatter\", \"extractor behavior on empty files\".\n\nPass-8 compile on 11 deep-learning docs emitted:\n\n- `regularization-generalization-trade-off.md` — a *trade-off* statement about regularization, not a concept. The source (regularization.md) has a `## Trade-offs` section; the extractor hoisted that trade-off discussion into its own concept page.\n- `batch-size.md` — borderline; \"batch size\" is a hyperparameter knob, not a reusable concept. Discussed in sgd.md as a trade-off.\n- `causal-masking.md` — one-sentence note in attention.md; prompt rule #3 (\"single-sentence paraphrases\") should have filtered.\n- `loss-landscape-smoothing.md` — single-phrase explanation in batch-norm.md.\n- `feature-co-adaptation.md` — one bullet in dropout.md's \"Why it works\" section.\n\nFinal count: 27 concepts from 11 sources. Compare to pass-7: 20 concepts from 12 sources — the tightening from bn-1vz is holding in ratio (~2/source) but rule-violating extractions still slip through.\n\n# Options\n\n**A. Add more worked examples to the prompt** — the current rules are abstract. The prompt would benefit from 3-5 *before/after* examples: \"if the source has `## Trade-offs`, extract the underlying concepts (e.g. overfitting, not 'regularization-generalization-trade-off')\".\n\n**B. Post-process filter** — reject concept names matching regex patterns like `.*-trade-off$`, `.*-implementation$`, `.*-behavior$`, `.*-handling$`. Belt-and-suspenders over the prompt.\n\n**C. Tighten the reusability test to a quantified rule** — \"a concept must have a name ≤ 4 words AND its definition_hint must not begin with 'A ... of X' or 'A ... between X and Y'\".\n\nRecommend A + B together. A handles the 80% case; B catches the remaining patterns that worked examples can't cover.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- On the pass-8 corpus (or a similar golden), concepts matching `.*-trade-off`, `.*-handling`, `.*-behavior` are not emitted.\n- Single-bullet concepts (feature-co-adaptation, loss-landscape-smoothing, causal-masking) are not emitted.\n- Concept count on the golden corpus drops from 27 to ≤ 22 without losing genuine concepts (adam-optimizer, attention, backpropagation, etc.).\n- Golden-corpus test in `crates/kb-compile/` locks in the lower count.","kind":"task","title":"tune(prompts): extract_concepts still emits meta-observations despite bn-1vz rules"}	blake3:7ZqYFzZY2VAY062xZ47IF-lr7hHfquSyOvdI69Hjfpo
1776651679789549	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtrgU		item.move	bn-2vm	{"state":"done"}	blake3:r6yPkc4nwMuh-A2Q5TTqI9GdP3dkC4-z0ISf0Jd0LBA
