1776651880980587	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtsQU		item.move	bn-iiq	{"state":"done"}	blake3:Be9EK0pFsCOw5fXPKLCh4pGvmgX2rBoQyN94JSqLmr0
1776652185620377	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtsgU		item.move	bn-1l8	{"state":"done"}	blake3:dfVtBVqehkxe7UASMXeX6Vsi-HeXI6hMJb-M8SxTiTM
1776652201664995	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtswU		item.move	bn-3qn	{"state":"done"}	blake3:YDBU5CSwxUpwpQTwK0MeO_wmkEgeWCwR01JfZtS2v0E
1776652295208461	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEttAU		item.move	bn-1fq	{"state":"done"}	blake3:Nk6A_ubRiQ37ieWEq6wgrKTeW-fIBKiS6e4Wd7Mq46Y
1776653785575503	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEttQU		item.create	bn-2tw	{"description":"# Context\n\n`wiki/concepts/paxos.md` body reads:\n\n> A Paxos variant that keeps auxiliary nodes out of the steady state and activates them only during failures\n\nThat's **Cheap Paxos**, not Paxos.\n\nSimilarly `wiki/concepts/leader-election.md` body narrowly describes the **bully algorithm**, not leader election in general.\n\nObserved on a pass-9 blind audit with an 11-doc distributed-systems corpus. The underlying problem: when multiple sources contribute to a concept (paxos has 3+ source quotes spanning Basic Paxos / Multi-Paxos / Cheap Paxos), the merge pipeline's \"definition\" for the concept appears to grab the LAST quote rather than synthesizing across them. The result is an authoritative-looking one-liner that is subtly wrong.\n\nHigh-impact defect — the concept page body is the first thing users read. A wrong definition on the top-level concept for a major topic makes the whole KB feel untrustworthy.\n\n# Where\n\n`crates/kb-llm/prompts/merge_concept_candidates.md` (the merge prompt) and/or `crates/kb-compile/src/concept_merge.rs::render_concept_page`. Find where the one-sentence body definition is generated when a concept has multiple sources.\n\n# Fix\n\nTwo-part fix:\n\n**A. Revise the merge prompt** — `merge_concept_candidates.md` should instruct the LLM that when multiple aliases/quotes contribute to a concept:\n- The body definition must cover the **most general** reading, not the most specific variant.\n- If the candidates include both a parent concept (\"Paxos\") and specific variants (\"Cheap Paxos\", \"Multi-Paxos\"), the canonical concept is the parent; variants become aliases or notes.\n- Add a worked example: \"Input: 3 quotes about Basic Paxos, Multi-Paxos, Cheap Paxos. ✓ right: body says 'A family of consensus algorithms for replicated logs'. ❌ wrong: body quotes only the Cheap Paxos specialization.\"\n\n**B. Post-check at merge time** — in concept_merge, after the LLM returns a merged concept, check: if the body text references a concept name that is only an alias (e.g., body says \"Cheap Paxos\" but canonical is \"paxos\"), flag for human review instead of writing the page. This catches LLM regressions the prompt alone can't prevent.\n\nOption A alone is probably enough for the pass-10 bump; B is defense in depth.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- On a corpus with Basic Paxos + Multi-Paxos + Cheap Paxos mentions, `wiki/concepts/paxos.md` body defines the family, not one variant.\n- On a corpus with Raft + bully-algorithm + token-ring mentions, `wiki/concepts/leader-election.md` body defines leader election generally, not the bully algorithm.\n- Golden-corpus test in `crates/kb-compile/` with fixture candidates asserting the merged body's first sentence is the most-general reading.\n- Existing concept-merge tests still pass.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): concept definition scoped to last-quote variant; should synthesize across aliases"}	blake3:fzT42Pt_XKXR5Bfiv52UA_PAAwNij45CwYJOX_ckVZA
1776653785748180	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEttgU		item.create	bn-32u	{"description":"# Context\n\n`wiki/concepts/raft.md` has only one backlink: `wiki/sources/src-950344f8` (the originating raft-overview.md source).\n\nBut \"Raft\" is also discussed in at least 6 other sources on the same corpus:\n- `etcd-raft-impl.md`\n- `raft-read-paths.md`\n- `raft-membership-changes.md`\n- `paxos-deep-dive.md`\n- `paxos-variants.md`\n- `google-spanner.md`\n\nThose sources use `[[raft-overview]]`-style wiki-links or reference Raft by name. None of them appear as backlinks on the Raft concept page.\n\nCascading problem: a user opens `wiki/concepts/raft.md` expecting to find all places Raft is discussed; they see one link. The wiki-graph value proposition collapses.\n\n# Root cause (hypothesis, no code read)\n\nThe backlinks pass (post bn-yqz fix) correctly gates cross-doc links by the concept's `source_document_ids: [...]`. Great for false positives, but the concept's `source_document_ids` field only lists the ONE source the concept was originally extracted from (via source_summary + concept_extraction passes).\n\nWhen `raft-read-paths.md` (which discusses Raft extensively) is processed, it doesn't emit its own `raft` concept candidate (correctly — the concept already exists). But the fact that Raft is mentioned there never propagates into the Raft concept's `source_document_ids`.\n\nTwo things are getting conflated:\n1. **Originating sources** — the source(s) that produced the concept via extraction.\n2. **Mentioning sources** — all sources that reference the concept (via wiki-link OR plain-text name match).\n\nA concept page's \"Backlinks\" section should show #2, not just #1.\n\n# Fix\n\nExtend the backlinks pass (`crates/kb-compile/src/backlinks.rs`) with a \"mentions\" scan:\n\n1. After processing existing source_document_ids-gated links, do a second scan:\n2. For each concept page, collect its name + aliases.\n3. Walk every source page body; for each one, check whether any of the concept's name/aliases appears as a word (case-insensitive, word boundaries) OR as a `[[wiki-link]]`.\n4. Add those source pages to the concept's backlinks.\n\nKeep the existing source_document_ids gating as the PRIMARY path; \"mentions\" is additive. Users visiting the concept page see both \"authoritative sources\" (from frontmatter) and \"mentions\" (additional sources).\n\nOptional display hint: separate the two sections visually:\n    ## Backlinks — authoritative sources\n    - [[wiki/sources/src-950344f8]]\n    \n    ## Backlinks — mentioned in\n    - [[wiki/sources/src-etcd-raft]]\n    - [[wiki/sources/src-raft-read-paths]]\n\nSimpler v1: merge both into one Backlinks block, dedup. (Mentioning already covers originating since originating sources always mention the concept.)\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- On the pass-9 corpus, `wiki/concepts/raft.md` Backlinks lists all 7 sources that discuss Raft.\n- Concepts with unique/singular sourcing (a term mentioned only once) still show one backlink — no false positives from matching the word elsewhere.\n- Word-boundary matching avoids substring false positives (e.g., \"Raft\" doesn't match inside \"craft\").\n- Integration test: seed a concept page with aliases + two unrelated source pages (one mentions the concept, one doesn't); assert the mentioning one appears.","kind":"task","title":"feat(compile): concept backlinks include all mentioning sources, not just originating one"}	blake3:jGhCeIwAZ-VdPTMcZdj-IJJh4G8OV-Ceti5l0cQn4Qc
1776653785912834	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEttwU		item.create	bn-did	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb forget src-xxxx` (from bn-1fq) moves the source's raw/normalized/wiki files to trash and emits a backlinks-refresh. But concepts that derived only from that source become silent orphans:\n\nRepro from pass-9 audit:\n\n    kb forget src-aa540111 --force\n    kb lint\n    # [fail] orphans: 5 issue(s)\n    # - wiki/concepts/zab.md ... refers to source_document_id src-aa540111 which no longer exists\n    # - wiki/concepts/zookeeper.md ...\n    # - wiki/concepts/zookeeper-lock-recipe.md ...\n    # - wiki/concepts/zookeeper-membership.md ...\n    # - wiki/concepts/zookeeper-watch.md ...\n\nThe user has to either manually delete those concept pages or approve separate cleanup actions. `kb lint` surfaces them, but forget should surface them up front or clean them up.\n\nAlso observed: `wiki/questions/<promoted-question>.md` files that cite the forgotten source are NOT rewritten. They still reference `src-aa540111` in frontmatter, which points to a now-trashed normalized dir.\n\nAlso: `state/build_records/build:source-summary:src-aa540111.json` remains — lint catches it as a stale artifact but forget didn't clean it.\n\n# Fix\n\nExtend `kb forget <target>` to:\n\n**F3a: pre-flight cascade analysis** — before doing any disk moves, enumerate:\n- Concept pages whose `source_document_ids` list becomes empty after removing this src.\n- Promoted question pages (`wiki/questions/*.md`) whose `source_document_ids` references this src.\n- Build records under `state/build_records/` that name this src in `output_paths`.\n\nPrint the list and require `--force` (or a `y/N` prompt) before proceeding:\n\n    kb forget src-aa540111\n    would also affect:\n      concept pages orphaned by this forget (will be moved to trash):\n        - wiki/concepts/zab.md\n        - wiki/concepts/zookeeper.md\n        ...\n      promoted questions that cite this source (will NOT be rewritten):\n        - wiki/questions/how-does-zookeeper-x.md\n      stale build records (will be removed):\n        - state/build_records/build:source-summary:src-aa540111.json\n    proceed? [y/N]\n\n**F3b: execute the cascade** — on approval:\n- Move orphaned concept pages to trash alongside the source.\n- Keep promoted question pages as-is but add a frontmatter field `orphaned_sources: [src-aa540111]` so they can be filtered/handled in a later sweep. (Rewriting is too involved for v1; flagging is sufficient.)\n- Remove matching build records (move to trash).\n\n**F3c: `kb forget --no-cascade`** — explicit opt-out for users who know what they're doing. Without it, cascade is default.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb forget src-X --force` with 3 concepts solely sourced from src-X moves all 3 concept pages to trash.\n- `kb lint` after forget reports 0 orphan errors.\n- Promoted question pages citing the removed source gain an `orphaned_sources:` frontmatter marker.\n- Stale build records for the removed source are trashed.\n- `kb forget --no-cascade` preserves legacy bn-1fq behavior.\n- `--dry-run` previews the cascade without moving anything.\n- Integration tests for each path.","kind":"task","title":"feat(forget): cascade to orphaned concepts, flag promoted questions, clean build records"}	blake3:Fez0fllXMVOzjYAHP7AGUhYW5s7H5oK0c6uaIt-mito
1776653792958705	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtuAU		item.create	bn-bup	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb lint broken-links` flags `[[wiki-link]]`-like strings that appear INSIDE YAML `quote:` fields in concept frontmatter:\n\n    # wiki/concepts/leader-election.md:27\n    sources:\n    - heading_anchor: ...\n      quote: \"See also: [[raft-overview]]\"       ← quoted from original source\n\nResult:\n\n    [Error] wiki/concepts/leader-election.md:27 unresolved wiki page target `raft-overview`\n\nBut the `[[raft-overview]]` is inside a string literal (the quote field), not an actual wiki-link meant to be resolved. The link scanner is treating markdown-level wiki-links identically regardless of context.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn the lint pass's wiki-link walker (likely `crates/kb-lint/src/`), when scanning a markdown document:\n- Skip text inside YAML frontmatter entirely.\n- Inside the markdown body, skip text inside fenced code blocks (` ``` `) and inline code spans (`` ` ``).\n\nFor frontmatter specifically: consume the leading `---` block up through the closing `---` and never report on its contents.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb lint` no longer flags `[[foo]]` patterns inside YAML frontmatter string values.\n- `kb lint` still catches real broken `[[foo]]` wiki-links in markdown body.\n- Wiki-links inside fenced code blocks in markdown body are also skipped (a real user pitfall).\n- Unit test with a fixture concept page whose frontmatter contains `[[fake-link]]` strings; assert lint reports 0 issues.\n- Unit test with a fixture whose body has an actual broken `[[missing]]`; assert lint reports 1 issue.","kind":"task","title":"fix(lint): broken-links falsely flags [[...]] inside YAML quote fields and code blocks"}	blake3:e6JXofA_xTOG3-N2oZr09AJeLaA4oJ56mu2PRS81qNU
1776653793118684	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtuQU		item.create	bn-32t	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb forget src-xxxx` (without `--force`) prompts `[y/N]`. Typing `n` returns exit 1 with:\n\n    error: forget aborted by user\n\nDeclining a prompt is a normal, non-error outcome. Treating it as an error:\n- Breaks shell pipelines (`kb forget $x && echo done` never echoes, but the user didn't actually fail at anything)\n- Surfaces in `kb status` / `kb doctor` as a failed job (job manifest exit_code=1)\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-cli/src/forget.rs` (or wherever the prompt lives), when the user types `n` / `N` / blank / anything other than `y`/`Y`:\n\n- Print `forget cancelled` to stdout (not stderr).\n- Exit 0.\n- Job manifest status: `Succeeded` with an informational note (or don't write a manifest at all for aborted-before-action).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `echo 'n' | kb forget src-X` exits 0, prints \"forget cancelled\" or similar.\n- Post-abort `kb status` does not show a failed job for the aborted forget.\n- `echo 'y' | kb forget src-X` proceeds normally (unchanged).\n- `kb forget --force src-X` skips the prompt (unchanged).\n- Integration test for the decline path.","kind":"task","title":"fix(forget): declining the prompt should exit 0 (not error), no failed job"}	blake3:cfLLU55SEhCh70jwLmjhKz9YpMQAs2yuznQ5ag9ACFo
1776653793284705	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtugU		item.create	bn-2m2	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb status` includes a line:\n\n    stale artifacts: 0\n\nBut this doesn't reflect the case where an ingested source has a new revision that hasn't been recompiled — the existing wiki source page's `source_revision_id` is out of date.\n\nPass-9 audit repro:\n1. Compile a KB, observe `stale artifacts: 0`.\n2. Modify `raft-overview.md` and re-ingest: new revision `rev-4253da59` for `src-950344f8`.\n3. Run `kb status`: `changed inputs not yet compiled: - raft-overview.md (src-950344f8)` appears, but `stale artifacts: 0` is unchanged.\n\nThe \"changed inputs\" section DOES surface the staleness (thanks to bn-2gn), but `stale artifacts: 0` in the header is misleading — a user who glances at the summary line will think the KB is up to date.\n\n# Fix\n\nTwo options:\n\n**A. Wire `stale_count` to reflect revision-mismatched sources** — count one \"stale artifact\" per source where `normalized/<src>/metadata.json::source_revision_id` differs from `wiki/sources/<src>.md::source_revision_id`. Also count orphaned concepts, build records pointing at removed sources, etc. This makes the summary line meaningful.\n\n**B. Rename the line** — if `stale_count` was narrowly defined to mean something specific (artifacts that failed validation?), rename to clarify. `stale artifacts` suggests \"things that need recompile\" which is NOT what it currently tracks.\n\nRecommend A — make the summary line match user expectations.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After re-ingesting a modified source without recompile, `kb status` shows `stale artifacts: 1` (or more, depending on what else is stale).\n- After `kb compile`, it drops back to 0.\n- `stale_artifacts` in JSON output matches the text count.\n- Integration test verifies the count changes after re-ingest.","kind":"task","title":"fix(status): stale_artifacts count should reflect revision-mismatched sources and orphans"}	blake3:tVZ5GG2_NDA0y6yYBP17qEOfAOGE4UjX8bGsQI4ska4
1776653793446437	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtuwU		item.create	bn-308	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb lint missing-citations` fires warnings on index pages:\n\n    [Warning] wiki/concepts/index.md: synthetic region is missing citations in the page body\n    [Warning] wiki/sources/index.md: synthetic region is missing citations in the page body\n\nIndex pages are auto-generated listings of concepts / sources. They don't have source material — they're navigational. Requiring citations on them is a category error.\n\n# Fix\n\nThe missing-citations lint should skip any `wiki/*/index.md` file. Simplest: match by filename — if the basename is `index.md`, skip.\n\nAlternative: the index_page pass (bn-2hz) could emit a `type: index` frontmatter marker, and lint skips any page with `type == index`. More explicit but requires two-crate coordination.\n\nGo with the simpler filename skip.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb lint` on a freshly-compiled KB reports 0 missing-citations warnings when only index pages would otherwise flag.\n- Real source-page missing-citations warnings (e.g., on an empty/whitespace-only source) still fire.\n- Unit test asserting `wiki/concepts/index.md` and `wiki/sources/index.md` are skipped.","kind":"task","title":"fix(lint): skip missing-citations on wiki/*/index.md auto-generated pages"}	blake3:RtDz-gNbx1oFRMYsiio_qcDREKOdeIlFdEah82l_gO8
1776654149364965	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvAU		item.move	bn-32t	{"state":"done"}	blake3:D8CvMa6EyiG6_z5NWf9NNVE96KEvQvi2x4lDnYdFKhc
1776654166799903	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvQU		item.move	bn-bup	{"state":"done"}	blake3:aequMRGn7kPl1H4Fdnj_daVt4wPtTu7Kwktut7uHTkQ
1776654192404395	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvgU		item.move	bn-2tw	{"state":"done"}	blake3:IdPkL9r1Uml-eVXCvlvvmlT_z1gsRLx12pjw9omQTdQ
1776654211596984	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvwU		item.move	bn-308	{"state":"done"}	blake3:hZuV-gW7QYtn0JID6UYsD3jbbUMzKGUzz95RavEis7M
1776654232476029	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtwAU		item.move	bn-32u	{"state":"done"}	blake3:1mNGGq3d0xX8cAJyLJC7pBKPpTijGHBwKUggFyqDUT4
1776654257838610	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtwQU		item.move	bn-2m2	{"state":"done"}	blake3:9rWotEmbsxp8QFYICHY9faXwQYYu9WUL1uofFjujyT8
1776654454174661	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtwgU		item.move	bn-did	{"state":"done"}	blake3:z6BJDYqfAQwlxdpVU6Oo4uk0tGmSlRVZUo1Fgwi6IhA
1776655800065784	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtwwU		item.create	bn-i5r	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-did's forget cascade added orphan-concept trashing + promoted-question flagging + build-record cleanup. But several downstream artifacts are still NOT refreshed, leaving the KB in a broken state until the user manually runs `kb compile` again:\n\n1. **Index pages** — `wiki/index.md`, `wiki/concepts/index.md`, `wiki/sources/index.md` still list the trashed source AND the orphaned concepts. `kb lint` produces 7+ broken-links errors pointing into `trash/`.\n\n2. **Surviving concept frontmatter** — when a multi-sourced concept survives cascade (because it has OTHER source_document_ids), its frontmatter `source_document_ids: [src-removed, src-kept]` still lists the removed id. `kb lint orphans` then flags it.\n\n3. **Lexical search index** — the lexical index built at compile-end still references the trashed `wiki/sources/<src>.md` and orphaned `wiki/concepts/<c>.md` pages. Worst consequence: `kb ask` **crashes** with `error: parse retrieval candidate /.../wiki/sources/src-<deleted>.md: No such file or directory (os error 2)` because retrieval pulls candidates from the stale index and fails to read them.\n\nRepro:\n\n    kb ingest /tmp/corpus\n    kb compile\n    kb forget src-<id> --force\n    kb ask \"anything\"\n    # → crash\n\nThis makes `kb ask` broken until `kb compile` runs again — a hard blocker for the core query flow.\n\n# Fix\n\nThe cascade needs three additional steps:\n\n**Step 1 — update index pages in-place.**\nAfter moving concept/source files to trash, call the index-page renderer (`crates/kb-compile/src/index_page.rs`) with the current on-disk state to regenerate `wiki/index.md`, `wiki/concepts/index.md`, `wiki/sources/index.md`. This is cheap — just a disk walk + atomic write.\n\n**Step 2 — scrub forgotten src-ids from surviving concept frontmatter.**\nWalk `wiki/concepts/*.md`. For each page whose frontmatter `source_document_ids` contains the forgotten src-id, remove that id from the list. If the list becomes empty, the page should have been trashed already (cascade caught it). If it still has other ids, just scrub and atomic-rewrite the frontmatter.\n\n**Step 3 — refresh the lexical index.**\nRegenerate the lexical index from current on-disk state. This is the pass that bn-32u's backlinks pass runs in; the same utility probably exists in `crates/kb-query/src/lexical.rs`. Call it after the trash moves.\n\nAll three should run INSIDE `kb forget` post-trash, not left for the next compile.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't re-run the expensive LLM passes (source_summary, concept_extraction, concept_merge). These deal with CONTENT, not layout. We only need to refresh the structural indexes.\n- Don't skip `--dry-run` handling: dry-run should still show the cascade plan without doing any of these updates.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After `kb forget src-X --force` (with 3 orphaned concepts), `kb lint` reports 0 orphan errors and 0 broken-links errors.\n- After same, `kb ask \"...\"` runs cleanly (no \"No such file or directory\" crash).\n- A surviving concept whose source_document_ids was `[src-X, src-Y]` now has `[src-Y]` in its frontmatter after forget.\n- `wiki/index.md` no longer lists the trashed source.\n- `wiki/concepts/index.md` no longer lists trashed concepts.\n- `kb search <term-unique-to-deleted-source>` returns no results (or a clean \"not found\") — not a crash from stale index entries.\n- Integration tests covering each of the three post-cascade refreshes.\n- `--dry-run` shows the cascade plan AND mentions \"will refresh index pages and lexical index\" but doesn't execute.","kind":"task","title":"fix(forget): cascade must refresh index pages, scrub frontmatter, rebuild lexical index (kb ask crashes after forget)"}	blake3:pCx4oSdQWmK0Trb1lqTcDe_aMU82PUhYs38eDX8eUx0
1776655800239839	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtxAU		item.create	bn-2d6	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-2tw's post-check regex (`^A .{1,30}? variant`, `^A specialization/instance/kind of`) catches ONE phrasing pattern. But in a fresh blind audit, the model produced variant-scoped concept bodies with DIFFERENT phrasings that slip past the check:\n\n- `wiki/concepts/raft.md` body: *\"A Raft safety property stating that any entry committed in a term must appear in the logs of all leaders elected in later terms.\"* ← that's Leader Completeness, not Raft.\n- `wiki/concepts/paxos.md` body: describes Basic Paxos single-value agreement, even though aliases include Multi-Paxos, Cheap Paxos, EPaxos, Flexible Paxos.\n- `wiki/concepts/quorum.md` body: describes Byzantine quorums specifically, not majority quorums generally.\n- `wiki/concepts/leader-election.md` body: describes Zab's specific leader-election procedure, not leader election in general.\n\nNone match the existing regex. The bodies are authoritative-sounding but wrong in scope.\n\n# Root cause\n\nThe merge pipeline takes N candidate quotes (one from each contributing source) and asks the LLM to produce a single merged concept page. When quotes describe different variants, the LLM's one-paragraph definition tends to synthesize from the most specific quote rather than lifting to the most general reading.\n\n# Fix\n\nTake a structural approach rather than adding more regex patterns:\n\n**Part A — explicit two-step prompt.**\n\nSplit `merge_concept_candidates.md` into two distinct asks:\n\nStep 1 (canonical selection): given candidate names + aliases, pick the canonical name and list all aliases — same as today.\n\nStep 2 (definition synthesis): given the canonical name and every quote across all aliases, produce a body that:\n- Starts with \"<Canonical> is [category]\" framing, e.g. \"Raft is a consensus algorithm...\"\n- NEVER starts with \"A <alias-specific-phrasing>\"\n- If the aliases span multiple variants/subtypes, the body must explicitly mention that (\"Variants include Basic Paxos, Multi-Paxos, Cheap Paxos, EPaxos.\")\n\nMove to a structured output where the LLM returns `{canonical: str, aliases: [str], category: str, definition: str, variants: [str]}` and the rendering is done template-side. That way we can enforce the framing (\"<canonical> is a <category> ...\") in code rather than relying on the LLM.\n\n**Part B — stronger post-check.**\n\nAfter receiving the merged concept body, check:\n- Does the first sentence begin with the canonical name? If not, flag.\n- Does the first sentence mention a string that appears in the aliases but isn't the canonical? (Signal the body is scoping to a variant rather than the parent.) Flag.\n- When `len(aliases) >= 3`, the body should mention at least one alias explicitly OR the word \"variants\" or \"includes\" to signal multi-variant scope.\n\nFlag via `tracing::warn!` and optionally via a new review-queue item `concept_definition_review` — don't block the page, but surface it for human review.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Prompt template updated to use structured output with enforced canonical-name framing.\n- Post-check catches the 4 specific observed failures (Raft, Paxos, Quorum, leader-election).\n- For a concept with aliases `[Basic Paxos, Multi-Paxos, Cheap Paxos, EPaxos, Flexible Paxos]`, the body mentions \"variants\" or the word \"family\" or names at least one alias.\n- Golden-corpus test with fixture candidates for the 4 observed failures; assert the merged body starts with the canonical name OR flags for review.\n- Existing tests still pass.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't auto-reject concepts that fail the check — a flagged page with an imperfect body is better than no page at all.\n- Don't add >3 regex patterns — the structural approach (enforce canonical framing in code, structured LLM output) is the robust fix.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): concept bodies still variant-scoped despite bn-2tw; needs structural prompt + post-check"}	blake3:Wu0w4BJ2t0riZLy79R0J0SSKOqLaQbNgKPxM7_31q74
1776655800405639	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtxQU		item.create	bn-2nr	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-32u added mention-scanning so concept backlinks include all sources that reference them. But coverage is inconsistent across concepts:\n\n- Raft concept: all 11 source files that mention Raft appear in backlinks. ✓\n- Quorum concept: 6 of 9 source files that substantively mention quorums. Missed: `raft.md`, `paxos.md`, `cap.md`.\n- Byzantine-fault-tolerance concept: 6 of 9 relevant. Missed 3.\n\nHypothesis: the mention-scanner uses `\\bquorum\\b` as a regex, but source files say \"quorums\" (plural), \"majority quorum\", \"quorum writes\". Word-boundary match without inflection/stem handling misses plurals and compound mentions.\n\nSimilarly BFT: files may say \"Byzantine fault tolerance\" or \"BFT\" but not the specific concept name.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn the mention-scanner (`crates/kb-compile/src/backlinks.rs`):\n\n**Part A — plural/singular handling.**\nFor each alias token, also try:\n- token + \"s\" (quorum → quorums)\n- token + \"es\" (box → boxes)\n- token without trailing \"s\" if length ≥ 4 (quorums → quorum)\n\nImplement as a small set of transformation rules, not a full stemmer — a stemmer library is overkill for personal-KB scale.\n\n**Part B — match compound mentions by alias parts.**\nWhen the concept has alias \"Byzantine fault tolerance\", also check for \"Byzantine\" AND \"fault tolerance\" in the same source paragraph (adjacency signal). Or more simply: match any alias substring of length ≥ 8 characters (multi-word aliases are their own signal).\n\n**Part C — lowercase + word-boundary rigor.**\nSanity check: `kb inspect concept:quorum` body likely has aliases `[quorum, quorums, majority quorum, Byzantine quorum]`. Verify the scanner iterates over aliases AND tries each inflected form.\n\n## Caveats\n\n- Don't over-match: \"BFT\" shouldn't pull in sources just because they mention \"byte\" or \"left\" (word-boundary check is load-bearing).\n- Plural-stripping on 3-char aliases (\"SQL\" → \"SQ\"?) would break things. Require min-length for stripping.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Quorum concept backlinks include `raft.md`, `paxos.md`, `cap.md` (sources that say \"quorums\" or \"majority quorum\").\n- Byzantine-fault-tolerance backlinks include all 9 mentioning sources.\n- Raft concept backlinks don't regress (still 11/11).\n- Word-boundary rigor preserved: \"Raft\" still doesn't match inside \"draft\" or \"craft\".\n- Unit tests for the plural/inflection transforms.\n- Integration test: concept with alias \"quorum\" gets backlinks from a fixture source whose body says \"quorums\".\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't pull in a full stemming library (no Porter stemmer).\n- Don't match concept name substrings — that produces pathological false positives.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): backlinks mention-scanner misses plural/inflected forms (quorum vs quorums)"}	blake3:himqft5XUTiTNosWsIzE0BNmrFuo5OEgB4mlowFbKNM
1776655806595631	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtxgU		item.create	bn-2oj	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb search <term>` scoring gives large boosts for matching common English stopwords. Pass-10 blind audit observation:\n\n> \"The JSON artifact shows sources getting +5 from matching the word \"is\" five times in their summaries.\"\n\nA retrieval plan that gives 5 points to every source containing the word \"is\" is essentially noise — every summary has \"is\" at least five times. The ranking signal is drowned.\n\n`kb retrieval plan` JSON for a query like \"Raft safety\" produces candidates with reasons like:\n- `summary matched 'is' 5x (+5)`\n- `summary matched 'raft' 2x (+2)`\n\nThe query-term-matching score is dominated by the stopword term.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn the lexical index scorer (`crates/kb-query/src/lexical.rs` or similar):\n\n1. Define a stopword list: the standard English stopwords (a, an, the, is, are, was, were, be, been, has, have, had, of, in, on, at, by, for, with, to, from, and, or, but, not, it, its, this, that, these, those, as, if, so, such).\n2. Before tokenizing the query, strip stopwords.\n3. Before tokenizing indexed text (summaries, bodies) for matching against a stopword-stripped query, you can keep stopwords in the index but never score matches for stopword query terms. Simpler: strip stopwords in BOTH directions.\n4. If the query is ENTIRELY stopwords after filtering (e.g. \"is a\") return no results.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb search \"is\"` returns no results (query is a stopword).\n- `kb search \"Raft safety\"` ranks by Raft + safety matches; no score from \"is\" or \"a\" if present in the summary.\n- `kb retrieval plan` JSON no longer shows `matched 'is' Nx (+N)` reasons.\n- Unit test: score a query \"the is of raft\" and assert the \"raft\" match dominates; \"the\", \"is\", \"of\" contribute 0.\n- Existing search/retrieval tests still pass.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't exhaustively import every stopword from every corpus — 30-50 words is plenty.\n- Don't remove stopwords from the index itself — they're fine to keep for potential future phrase matching; just don't score against them.","kind":"task","title":"fix(query): lexical search scores stopword matches ('is' +5x drowns real signal)"}	blake3:N_SMCBN3Ja3Oo-7MOxlzVFP7WsEVGGe-H4Qk12rsJbw
1776655806761372	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtxwU		item.create	bn-1jx	{"description":"# Context\n\nWhen a user runs `kb ask --format=png \"...\"` (or similar clear input-validation rejection), the command correctly exits 1 with the informative error. But the job manifest at `state/jobs/<id>.json` records `status: \"failed\"` with `exit_code: 1`, which:\n\n- Shows up in `kb status` \"failed job runs\" list.\n- Pollutes `kb doctor` if the threshold triggers.\n- Requires `kb jobs prune --failed` to clean up.\n\nUser-input validation rejections are a normal, expected outcome — not a system failure. They shouldn't count.\n\nSame class of issue: malformed ingest paths, bad inspect targets, etc. — any exit-1-due-to-clap-or-input-validation.\n\n# Fix\n\nDistinguish two error classes in the job manifest:\n\n**System failure** — something went wrong internally (LLM timeout, file I/O error, compile pass crashed). Records as `status: failed, exit_code: 1`. Shows up in doctor/status.\n\n**Validation rejection** — user-input check returned a clear error before any mutating work ran. Either:\n- Don't write a job manifest at all (cleanest — the user got an error message; nothing to track).\n- Write manifest with `status: rejected, exit_code: 1`, and exclude `status == \"rejected\"` from doctor + status failed-jobs counts.\n\nSimplest implementation: in `execute_mutating_command_with_handle`, detect `ExitCodeError` variants that originated from argument validation and skip the manifest write. Or add a new `Error::Validation` variant that the wrapper treats specially.\n\n## Scope\n\nInventory which `bail!` / `Err(...)` calls are validation vs system failures. Candidates for \"validation\" classification:\n- `kb ask --format=png` rejection\n- `kb ask \"\"` / `kb inspect \"\"` / `kb search \"\"` empty-arg checks\n- `kb ingest <nonexistent-path>` — arguably validation\n- `kb inspect <path-outside-root>` — validation (bn-1yq)\n- `kb review approve <unknown-id>` — validation\n- `kb publish <unknown-target>` — validation\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After `kb ask --format=png \"x\"` (exit 1), `kb status` does NOT show a failed job run for it.\n- `kb doctor` doesn't warn about input-validation rejections.\n- After `kb ask \"<valid question>\"` that failed due to LLM timeout or I/O error, the job IS recorded as failed (system failure).\n- Integration test: run validation-reject commands, assert no manifest or rejected-status manifest; run a simulated LLM failure, assert failed-status manifest.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't silently swallow real errors. The user-facing error message must still be clear and actionable.\n- Don't over-classify — when in doubt, record as failed. Better to clutter status than hide a real failure.","kind":"task","title":"fix(jobs): user-input-validation errors should not appear in failed-jobs list"}	blake3:XGAodAb8p0kqwXlOEY1lhvlL-9SOCExUXvC209M--Pc
1776655806927645	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtyAU		item.create	bn-3gs	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb lint missing-citations` flags promoted question pages (`wiki/questions/<slug>.md`) for missing citations even when their frontmatter carries a valid `citations:` list AND the body has `[N]` bracket references.\n\nObserved on pass-10:\n\n    kb ask --promote \"what is X\"\n    kb review approve <id>\n    # → wiki/questions/what-is-x.md created with citations frontmatter\n    kb lint\n    # [Warning] wiki/questions/what-is-x.md: synthetic region is missing citations in the page body\n\nBut the promoted page HAS citations — they're in frontmatter + referenced as `[1] [2]` inline. The check is looking at the `<!-- kb:begin id=... -->` synthetic regions (from `## Summary` etc.) without recognizing that citations on a question page live in frontmatter + bracket-references, not inline wiki-links.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn the missing-citations lint (`crates/kb-lint/src/`), when scanning a page:\n- If the page frontmatter has `type: question_answer` (or path is `wiki/questions/*.md`), use a DIFFERENT check: verify that every `[N]` bracket reference in the body has a corresponding entry in the frontmatter `citations:` list.\n- Don't require inline wiki-links; the bracket→frontmatter pairing IS the citation structure for questions.\n\nAlternative simplest fix: skip `wiki/questions/*.md` entirely in missing-citations (like bn-308 skipped index pages).\n\nGo with the simpler skip — question pages have their own structural citation format that doesn't map to the source-page model the check was designed for.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb lint` on a KB with promoted question pages reports 0 missing-citations warnings against `wiki/questions/*.md`.\n- Real missing-citations on source pages still fire.\n- Unit test asserting the skip.\n- `kb lint --strict` on a well-formed KB with promotions passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't weaken the check for source pages.\n- Don't silently accept promoted pages with ZERO citations at all — if a future bone wants to add citation-structure validation specific to questions, fine.","kind":"task","title":"fix(lint): skip missing-citations on promoted wiki/questions/*.md pages"}	blake3:JLc6uKQRRSnxSgKyeAxanalnSk8zfHOoaDwtJ4FaxbM
1776656172264282	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtyQU		item.move	bn-3gs	{"state":"done"}	blake3:O4aMFOCFG34Ta1tiobxwYG5_pFupuHX4n38-leCzw98
1776656245295602	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtygU		item.move	bn-2oj	{"state":"done"}	blake3:gDAe1UKDWwg5Hv0IvSVz7qQ0U0o6DbfwMGFzaE6-JGY
1776656258494724	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtywU		item.move	bn-2nr	{"state":"done"}	blake3:ASMYlK0ks6TSoKAeexrPMSouXXba4QhlwRPPC0JLyhY
1776656404667437	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtzAU		item.move	bn-2d6	{"state":"done"}	blake3:i3TrqW4krlXuQg4ChVZcIcadKZtjqr4jxApIfkh8R8w
1776656450037351	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtzQU		item.move	bn-i5r	{"state":"done"}	blake3:CTxHXF5suMvc_DYz6-2r_2OaYo4Kv-P7rdsVGHQlsqE
1776656507649874	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtzgU		item.move	bn-1jx	{"state":"done"}	blake3:GSfoNBtg0IPGjupgcnI43Rzef3HlwbblfUTWJBoPgPg
1776657768464726	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtzwU		item.create	bn-gdd	{"description":"# Context\n\nThe mention-based backlinks added by bn-32u (with plural handling from bn-2nr) still miss obvious mentions at corpus scale:\n\nPass-11 audit:\n- `wiki/concepts/mutex.md` has 1 backlink; 5 of 10 raw files contain \"mutex\"/\"mutexes\"\n- `wiki/concepts/context-switch.md` has 2 backlinks; 5 files mention it\n- `wiki/concepts/virtual-memory.md` has 1 backlink; 2 files say \"virtual memory\"\n\n**Hypothesis: the mention-scanner is walking wiki source PAGES (summaries), not the full normalized source text.** A source's summary is a 100-word compression that omits most of the specific terms appearing in the original. If the summary doesn't say \"mutex\" but the original does, the scanner misses it.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-compile/src/backlinks.rs::collect_mention_backlinks` (or whatever bn-32u named the mention-scanning function):\n\nChange the source iterator from \"walk wiki/sources/*.md bodies\" to \"walk normalized/*/source.md (the full original text after frontmatter strip)\".\n\nSpecifically:\n- For each `normalized/<src>/`, read `source.md` — that's the authoritative full content.\n- Scan that text (minus frontmatter, minus fenced code blocks per bn-bup's rules) against each concept's name + alias + plural inflections.\n- The src-to-wiki-page mapping is already established: `normalized/<src>/` → `wiki/sources/<src>.md`.\n\nKeep bn-32u's word-boundary + min-length guards and bn-2nr's plural handling.\n\n## Secondary fix: exclude auto-generated index pages from backlink candidates\n\n`wiki/concepts/interrupt.md` has `wiki/sources/index` as a backlink because that index's title list contains \"Interrupts\". Exclude `wiki/*/index.md` from the scan.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- On a fresh compile of the pass-11 corpus, `wiki/concepts/mutex.md` Backlinks includes ALL 5 source files whose raw text mentions \"mutex\" or \"mutexes\".\n- `wiki/concepts/context-switch.md` includes all 5 mentioning sources.\n- `wiki/concepts/virtual-memory.md` includes both mentioning sources.\n- `wiki/concepts/interrupt.md` does NOT list `wiki/sources/index` as a backlink.\n- Existing Raft-concept coverage (all 11/11 on prior audit) doesn't regress.\n- Word-boundary discipline preserved: \"Raft\" in \"craft\" still doesn't match.\n- Integration test with a fixture corpus where the summary doesn't mention a term but the full source does — assert backlink is emitted.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't go back to scanning source summaries — that's the bug.\n- Don't drop the source_document_ids-gated primary backlinks (bn-yqz) — those are authoritative and must still fire.\n- Don't include wiki/*/index.md in any backlink set.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): backlinks mention-scanner must walk full source text, not summaries; exclude index pages"}	blake3:A11p4ZdyR_rKFGl6RvDYdxiNCFfpXQDkpG9qqTCHu6M
1776657768632820	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt0AU		item.create	bn-1jl	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-2oj added a 44-word stopword list to the lexical scorer. But common question-stem words are missing:\n\nPass-11 audit: query \"What is a mutex and how does it differ from a semaphore?\" had:\n- \"what\", \"is\", \"a\" filtered (bn-2oj working) ✓\n- \"how\" NOT filtered — scored `process-scheduling` source +1 for matching \"how\" in its summary ✗\n\nMissing from STOPWORDS:\n- **how**, **why**, **when**, **where**, **does**, **do**, **did** — question-stem verbs + adverbs\n- **also**, **then**, **than**, **some**, **any**, **most**, **many** — mild intensifiers/quantifiers\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-query/src/lexical.rs` STOPWORDS const, add:\n\n- how, why, when, where (interrogatives)\n- does, do, did (auxiliary verbs)\n- also, then, than, some, any, most, many (non-content-bearing)\n\nFinal list should be roughly 55-60 words. Don't exhaustively import every English stopword; these are the ones observed to cause actual scoring issues.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb search \"how does X work\"` scores only X and \"work\" (not \"how\" or \"does\").\n- Retrieval plans from `kb ask \"How does X differ from Y?\"` no longer contain `reason: ... matched 'how' Nx`.\n- `kb search \"when was X introduced\"` scores only X and \"introduced\".\n- Existing stopword tests pass; new tests cover the added words.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't remove stopwords from the index (keep current bn-2oj strategy of filtering at query-tokenize).\n- Don't filter technical terms (how, why, when could appear in a title like \"How X Works\" — they stay in indexed text; just not in query-scoring tokens).","kind":"task","title":"fix(query): stopword list missing how/why/does/when (retrieval scoring still leaks 'how')"}	blake3:rzZ0swIpnYYSYJbhZfHouvox_1KdfSPt6wSricC95q4
1776657768800838	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt0QU		item.create	bn-3f6	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-i5r's forget cascade cleans up most downstream state, but the pass-11 audit found:\n\n1. `state/build_records/build:extract-concepts:src-X.json` is NOT listed in the cascade plan and remains on disk. Only `build:source-summary:src-X.json` was surfaced/removed.\n2. `state/graph.json` still references the forgotten source after forget. It gets rebuilt on next compile, but leaves stale state in the interim.\n3. `wiki/questions/<slug>.md` has `retrieval_candidates` including the forgotten src-id. Arguably intentional (the retrieval-plan is a historical log), but the cascade plan doesn't call this out either way.\n\n# Fix\n\n**Part A — include ALL build records matching the src-id.**\n\nIn `crates/kb-cli/src/forget.rs::analyze_cascade::scan_stale_build_records`, extend the match:\n- Today: looks for `build:source-summary:<src>`\n- Required: match ANY build record whose `metadata.output_paths` names `normalized/<src>/*` or `wiki/sources/<src>.md`, OR whose id contains `:<src>` as a component. This covers source_summary, extract_concepts, concept_merge (where applicable), promotion, etc.\n\n**Part B — refresh `state/graph.json` post-cascade.**\n\nSame pattern as the other three refreshes (index pages, frontmatter scrub, lexical index). Rebuild graph.json from current on-disk state. If a full graph rebuild is too expensive, at minimum remove nodes whose paths no longer exist.\n\n**Part C — document `retrieval_candidates` behavior in forget help text.**\n\nAcceptable v1: forget leaves `retrieval_candidates` in wiki/questions/*.md untouched (historical log), but the cascade plan explicitly notes \"promoted questions retain retrieval_candidates as historical record — citations field already scrubbed by bn-did\". Add this one line to the cascade output so users know what to expect.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb forget src-X --force` removes ALL `state/build_records/*:<src>*.json` files (move to trash).\n- After forget, `grep -l src-X state/` finds no matches (except in trash).\n- Cascade plan output lists both source-summary AND extract-concepts build records (and any others).\n- `state/graph.json` after forget does not contain any node whose id references the forgotten src.\n- Integration test asserting grep returns empty after forget.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't rewrite `retrieval_candidates` in promoted questions (too invasive for historical logs).\n- Don't do a full compile to rebuild graph.json — surgically remove the src's nodes.","kind":"task","title":"fix(forget): cleanup misses extract-concepts build records; state/graph.json left stale"}	blake3:01xqkOZJBUIuS2cvdJMzAREv6AZ_vj6iZITHLHjRR28
1776657768960993	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt0gU		item.create	bn-2tq	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb lint --strict` on a KB with a re-ingested-but-not-recompiled source fails with:\n\n    [fail] orphans: 1 issue(s)\n    - [Error] wiki/sources/src-X.md page references stale source revision(s): rev-Y\n\nThis is misleading. The page isn't orphaned — it has its source. It just references a stale revision id. The \"orphans\" class is for pages whose source is entirely gone.\n\n# Fix\n\nSplit into a new lint class `stale_revision`:\n\nIn `crates/kb-lint/src/`:\n- Rename the specific check that catches \"page source_revision_id doesn't match current normalized revision\" to fire under a new `stale_revision` (or similar) lint class.\n- `orphans` retains its original semantics: page references a src-id whose normalized/ is gone.\n- Wiring: update `LintRule::parse` and the iteration order in the runner.\n\nSeverity: `warn` (default) — stale revision is a \"run compile\" prompt, not a hard error. Or keep as `error` if the user has been depending on strict-mode catching it.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Re-ingesting a modified source without recompile now triggers `stale_revision`, not `orphans`.\n- A truly orphaned page (references deleted src) still fires under `orphans`.\n- `kb lint --strict` still fails in both cases.\n- `kb lint --check stale_revision` and `kb lint --check orphans` filter correctly.\n- Existing tests updated to the new class name.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't silently demote stale_revision to warn if users have CI pipelines relying on strict failing the build — keep severity behavior stable.\n- Don't fold the two lint classes back together.","kind":"task","title":"fix(lint): rename stale-revision check from 'orphans' to its own class"}	blake3:O7MM9TmIdBW0gIeE9CEBIU9ZY8XHJUVbO5-RAvZbJqk
1776657769125774	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt0wU		item.create	bn-k79	{"description":"# Context\n\n`wiki/index.md` (top-level) lists Sources and Concepts but omits the Questions section even when `wiki/questions/*.md` files exist (from `kb ask --promote` + `review approve`):\n\n    # Knowledge Base\n    \n    ## Sources\n    ...\n    \n    ## Concepts\n    ...\n    \n    (no Questions section)\n\nUsers who promote question answers can't navigate to them from the index page.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-compile/src/index_page.rs`:\n\n1. Scan `wiki/questions/*.md` (like the existing scans of `wiki/sources/` and `wiki/concepts/`).\n2. Add a `## Questions` section to `wiki/index.md` if any questions exist.\n3. Create `wiki/questions/index.md` the same way as the other index pages — list all promoted questions with file-relative links (matching bn-2hz's convention).\n4. Entries sorted alphabetically by title (extract from frontmatter).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After a promote+approve, `wiki/index.md` has a Questions section with a link to the promoted page.\n- `wiki/questions/index.md` exists and lists all promoted questions.\n- Links resolve when clicked from the index file (bn-2hz relative-path convention).\n- Count correctly reflected in `wiki/index.md` header (\"N question(s)\").\n- Forget cascade (bn-i5r) updates the Questions listing too if a promoted question's source is trashed and the question is flagged or removed.\n- Integration test.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't auto-promote or change promotion semantics.\n- Don't add Questions section if there are zero questions (keep output tidy).","kind":"task","title":"feat(compile): wiki/index.md add Questions section; create wiki/questions/index.md"}	blake3:O0_du7Mr9jb15GucKvY9BpcDk_BbxOnO4B4LywzgV1I
1776657963601887	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt1AU		item.move	bn-1jl	{"state":"done"}	blake3:tLt9Kg33dUWv-gVsI1TY_buKThYDLg2GLcbWrHFW0-w
1776658203728903	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt1QU		item.move	bn-gdd	{"state":"done"}	blake3:G8feP74Eyx1VQNXIAUb7jco_ubFf9Vol6UqJLMw3Rl8
1776658224128647	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt1gU		item.move	bn-2tq	{"state":"done"}	blake3:P8LQ3U1oobRJQUg4LAAXVieJLz-E2CM7wZO9cHrjkL4
