1776658404338569	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt2AU		item.move	bn-3f6	{"state":"done"}	blake3:TQeMaO1SIPmQVt9YfujwfcYDSd-KA7AOE1llQTZIwQw
1776659784391825	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt2QU		item.create	bn-1w5	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-2tw + bn-2d6 combined added worked prompt examples, canonical-prefix check, variant-scoping check, and alias-in-first-sentence check. Despite all that, pass-12 still surfaced:\n\n- `wiki/concepts/cache-eviction-policy.md` body is a **2Q-specific description**, not general eviction-policy. Aliases include LRU, LFU, ARC, 2Q, Clock, CAR.\n- `wiki/concepts/replication.md` body is the **GlusterFS AFR-specific description**, not general replication. Aliases span primary-backup, quorum, AFR.\n- `wiki/concepts/metadata-server.md` body is **lease-based cache-coherence-specific**, not general MDS description.\n\nThe structural approach (post-check + worked examples) catches some cases but not when the model's \"most specific quote\" has a strong LLM signal pulling it into the one-line body regardless.\n\n# Fix — restructure the generation\n\nInstead of prompting for a single merged concept and post-checking, split the body generation from the canonical selection:\n\n**Two-step LLM call:**\n\n1. **Canonical + aliases** (same as today): given candidates, pick canonical name and aliases list. Return structured JSON.\n\n2. **General definition (new separate call)**: given `{canonical: \"Cache eviction policy\", aliases: [LRU, LFU, ARC, 2Q, Clock, CAR]}` AND the pool of candidate source-quotes, generate a definition with these explicit constraints:\n   - First sentence MUST start with `{canonical} is ...`\n   - Body MUST NOT describe any specific variant — it describes what they have in COMMON.\n   - If the aliases represent variants of a common pattern, the body describes that pattern.\n   - Mention \"variants include\" followed by a list of 3-5 aliases.\n   - Maximum 3 sentences total.\n\nThis structural separation forces the model to answer \"what's common across these?\" rather than \"merge these quotes into one paragraph\", which is where the narrowing happens.\n\n## Alternative (if two calls too expensive)\n\nTemplate-based rendering. After Step 1 picks canonical + aliases:\n\n- Body = `\"{canonical} is a {category}. Variants include {alias_1}, {alias_2}, {alias_3}{, and {alias_4}}.\"`\n- `{category}` comes from a single LLM call that maps canonical → category (3-word phrase like \"consensus algorithm\", \"cache replacement strategy\").\n\nThis gets a predictable 2-sentence body that's always correctly scoped. No more variant-narrowing possible. Trade-off: less natural prose.\n\nRecommend trying the two-step LLM approach first; fall back to template-based if still unreliable.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't re-add more post-check patterns — we've seen they don't catch structural narrowing.\n- Don't change the canonical-name selection logic (that's working).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- For cache-eviction-policy with aliases [LRU, LFU, ARC, 2Q, Clock, CAR], body starts \"Cache eviction policy is...\" and mentions variants by name.\n- For replication with aliases [primary-backup, quorum, AFR, chain-replication], body is a general replication definition, not AFR-specific.\n- For concepts with a single alias (no variant spread), body is whatever the LLM naturally produces — no regression.\n- Golden-corpus test with stubbed LLM adapter covering cache-eviction-policy + 2Q-biased candidates.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.","kind":"task","title":"fix(compile): concept body synthesis still variant-narrowed; restructure to two-step LLM or template"}	blake3:u0E7JS__K6pPa_e6J6FzT5PB081Ridn4G8iue_M_bo0
1776659784555010	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt2gU		item.create	bn-2om	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-1l8 was supposed to narrow `source_document_ids` in ask/promote artifacts to only sources whose pages appear in the citations list. Pass-12 audit found it's NOT working on real ask runs:\n\nRepro:\n- `kb ask \"How does Ceph's CRUSH algorithm differ from HDFS's NameNode approach for placement?\"`\n- Answer body cites [2], [3], [4], [5], [6], [7], [8], [9], [11] → 9 citations\n- Frontmatter:\n  - `source_document_ids: [11 items]` — all sources in retrieval scope\n  - `retrieval_candidates: [11 items]` — byte-identical to source_document_ids\n\nThe two fields should differ: source_document_ids = cited-only (9 or fewer), retrieval_candidates = all 11.\n\nSame pattern on promoted question frontmatter.\n\n# Hypothesis\n\nbn-1l8 added `cited_source_paths: &[String]` to `WriteArtifactInput`. The CLI path calling `write_artifact` may be passing an empty slice OR passing all retrieval candidates as \"cited\" instead of computing the subset from `valid_citations`.\n\nCheck `crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs::run_ask` — where does it construct the paths for `cited_source_paths`? It should be derived from `artifact_result.valid_citations` (the indices into retrieval_plan.candidates that the LLM actually cited).\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `run_ask` (`crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs`):\n\n1. After the LLM produces the answer, iterate `valid_citations: &[u32]`.\n2. For each valid citation index `i`, look up `retrieval_plan.candidates[i-1].id` — that's the wiki path (e.g. `wiki/concepts/foo.md` or `wiki/sources/src-abc.md`).\n3. Build `cited_source_paths: Vec<String>` with those path strings.\n4. Pass to `write_artifact(&WriteArtifactInput { ..., cited_source_paths: &cited_paths })`.\n\nPromotion path (`kb review approve` for a promotion review item) mirror the same — extract from the original `ArtifactSidecar::valid_citations` and filter `source_document_ids` accordingly.\n\n## Also\n\nWhen building the `retrieval_candidates` field, use all 11. When building `source_document_ids`, use the filter.\n\nThe `WriteArtifactInput` already has `retrieval_plan: &RetrievalPlan`; you have everything needed.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask \"<multi-source question>\"` that cites 3 of 10 candidates produces an answer with `source_document_ids` length 3, `retrieval_candidates` length 10.\n- `kb ask --promote` followed by `kb review approve` creates a `wiki/questions/<slug>.md` with the same narrowed `source_document_ids`.\n- `source_document_ids != retrieval_candidates` (distinct fields, both present).\n- Integration test asserting the filter.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't remove `retrieval_candidates` — debugging info is load-bearing.\n- Don't change the JSON format (bn-iiq schema).","kind":"task","title":"fix(ask): source_document_ids still lists all retrieval candidates, not cited-only (bn-1l8 regression)"}	blake3:8Rf6LyKAcW8h_b4zZ5b8rMb_Wgsy2PAJ049DbzuML-E
1776659784718884	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt2wU		item.create	bn-2zy	{"description":"# Context\n\n`kb review approve <promotion-id>` moves an ask artifact into `wiki/questions/<slug>.md`. But neither `wiki/index.md` nor `wiki/questions/index.md` is refreshed until the user runs `kb compile` again. If the user never re-compiles (common — they just wanted the promotion), the promoted question is invisible from the wiki's entry point.\n\nAlso observed: the title rendered in `wiki/index.md`'s Questions section is the slug (\"how does arc cache compare to lru\") rather than the properly-capitalized question title from the page's frontmatter (\"How does ARC cache compare to LRU?\").\n\n# Fix\n\n**Part A — refresh indexes on approve.**\n\nIn `crates/kb-cli/src/review.rs::apply_promotion` (or wherever the review-approve handler lives), after writing `wiki/questions/<slug>.md`, call the same index-page refresh helpers used by bn-i5r's forget cascade:\n\n- `kb_compile::index_page::generate_indexes(root)` + `persist_index_artifacts`\n\nThis regenerates `wiki/index.md`, `wiki/sources/index.md`, `wiki/concepts/index.md`, `wiki/questions/index.md` from current on-disk state.\n\nKeep it cheap — no LLM calls, just file walks + atomic writes.\n\n**Part B — render question title correctly.**\n\nIn `crates/kb-compile/src/index_page.rs`, the question-listing render should read `title:` or `question:` from the question page's frontmatter (bn-k79 noted the fallback chain `title > question > name`). Verify it's picking the proper value — the observed output suggests the slug is being used. Debug by grepping the promoted page's frontmatter and tracing what `index_page.rs` reads.\n\nThe fix may be as simple as swapping `slug` for `frontmatter.get(\"title\")` in the question render.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- After `kb review approve <promotion-id>`, immediately running `cat wiki/index.md` shows a Questions section with the new promotion linked — no intervening `kb compile` needed.\n- The link shows the proper question-cased title: `[How does ARC cache compare to LRU?](questions/how-does-arc-cache-compare-to-lru.md)`.\n- `wiki/questions/index.md` similarly renders proper titles.\n- Integration test: promote + approve + check index contents immediately.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't make approve run the full LLM passes. Layout refresh only.\n- Don't change the slug-generation logic.","kind":"task","title":"fix(review): approve should refresh indexes inline; question titles in index use proper title not slug"}	blake3:cQdFW1dffDJEcxsUAx6ITMIhKfm19evjb2dJOgDR490
1776659784879981	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt3AU		item.create	bn-1yvn	{"description":"# Context\n\nbn-did's forget cascade was designed to \"flag but not rewrite\" promoted question pages when their source is forgotten — adding an `orphaned_sources: [src-X]` marker to frontmatter. The pass-12 auditor found that this design is consistent but incomplete: `kb lint` still fires an orphan error on those flagged pages:\n\n    [fail] orphans: 1 issue(s)\n    - [Error] wiki/questions/how-does-arc-cache-compare-to-lru.md referenced source document 'src-df3e2e79' is missing\n\nFlagged means \"user acknowledged this is orphaned\"; the lint should recognize the marker and suppress or downgrade the severity.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-lint/src/` where the `orphans` check scans wiki pages:\n\nWhen a page's frontmatter contains a non-empty `orphaned_sources: [...]` list, and the missing src-id is IN that list:\n- Suppress the `orphans` error for that specific src-id on that page, OR\n- Downgrade it to `warn` severity (still visible, but doesn't fail `--strict`)\n\nPick suppression for v1 — if the user explicitly chose not to rewrite the page, lint should trust that choice. The `orphaned_sources` field is the contract.\n\nIf the missing src-id is NOT in `orphaned_sources`, still fire the error (a genuinely orphaned reference that wasn't acknowledged).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- A promoted question with `orphaned_sources: [src-X]` in frontmatter, referencing src-X which is gone, does NOT fire `kb lint orphans`.\n- A promoted question with NO `orphaned_sources` marker, referencing a missing src, DOES fire.\n- A promoted question flagged for src-X but ALSO referencing src-Y which is missing (not flagged) fires only for src-Y.\n- `kb lint --strict` passes cleanly after `kb forget` with promoted-question flagging.\n- Integration test covering each case.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't change bn-did's \"flag don't rewrite\" design.\n- Don't silently treat all orphaned references as acknowledged — the marker is the signal.","kind":"task","title":"fix(lint): orphans check should respect orphaned_sources frontmatter marker"}	blake3:Ql1ELaPgavrN3-f_Xmzj9ItPrjJJ1bbzRgrLodJpdEQ
1776660157202898	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt3QU		item.move	bn-1yvn	{"state":"done"}	blake3:YaA5PzBryjQ_0pC0zWxMuzEPHEbp6OtY6LYI93yTQ98
