1776700856337999	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt4QU		item.create	bn-2gwa	{"description":"Replace `mint_source_document_id` and `mint_source_revision_id` in crates/kb-core/src/source_identity.rs with terseid. Add `terseid = \"0.1\"` to kb-core Cargo.toml. Source ids: use IdGenerator with prefix \"src\", seed = `<kind>\\n<stable_location>`, exists closure walks normalized/ dir to check. Revision ids: content-addressable, use `terseid::hash(content_bytes, N)` with prefix \"rev\" so identical content → identical id (NO IdGenerator for rev — bypass collision retry to preserve content-addressability). Pick terseid default config (3-char start, grows adaptively) for src-. For rev-, fixed 6 chars via terseid::hash to keep content-addressable determinism. Expected output: src-a7x (3-char for small KBs, grows naturally), rev-a7x3q9 (always 6-char of content hash). Update all affected tests and fixtures. No backwards compatibility needed — test KBs on /tmp/kb-pass*/ will be regenerated. Acceptance: ingest + compile on a fresh corpus produces short ids; existing kb-ingest tests pass after fixture updates; terseid dep added; BLAKE3 usage in other parts untouched; `just check` passes.","kind":"task","title":"refactor(core): convert src- and rev- ids to terseid (adaptive base-36)"}	blake3:17jREcBH-vTjVkCs4X1FPQyQKuINuGgDCRh2PPKp20A
1776700868769700	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt4gU		item.create	bn-3v4a	{"description":"Replace the timestamp-hash question id and 'artifact-' + question_id artifact id with terseid. Find callsites: crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs run_ask (question id generation, around line 1503 with unique_question_suffix) and crates/kb-query/src/writer.rs (artifact id around line 518 format!(\"artifact-{question_id}\")). Use terseid::IdGenerator with prefix \"q\" for questions and \"art\" for artifacts. Seed with query text + timestamp. Exists check walks outputs/questions/ dir. Expected: q-a7x (3-char for small KBs), art-a7x (artifact id independently short). Update references in frontmatter, metadata.json, build record ids (build:ask:<q-id>), promotion code (crates/kb-compile/src/promotion.rs which checks for 'question-' and 'artifact-' prefixes — update those to 'q-' and 'art-'). Kb-compile and kb-query already have terseid via kb-core dep transitively. Acceptance: kb ask produces short-id files under outputs/questions/q-XXX/, promotion flow still works end-to-end, integration tests pass. No backwards compat.","kind":"task","title":"refactor(ask): convert question- and artifact- ids to terseid"}	blake3:XICAtJYuWAW09uze5DUpFU4OQXUGsrzkUo2xHSNrY4E
1776700884980682	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt4wU		item.create	bn-221i	{"description":"Replace next_job_id in crates/kb-cli/src/jobs.rs (line 105: `{now}-{pid}-{command_part}`) with terseid. Use prefix based on command (\"ing\" for ingest, \"comp\" for compile, \"ask\" for ask, \"lint\" for lint, \"pub\" for publish, \"rev\" for review, \"for\" for forget — wait avoid clash with rev- which is revision ids). Use \"j-ing\", \"j-comp\" etc. with \"j\" as namespace? Actually simpler: keep one prefix \"job\" and include the command in the seed. Use terseid::IdGenerator with prefix \"job\", seed = `{timestamp_ns}|{pid}|{command}`, exists closure walks state/jobs/ dir. Result: job-a7x instead of 1776649999145057068-2628666-ingest. Drastic shortening. Update manifest_path_for if needed. Update all tests that seed fake job ids. Also update kb-cli status rendering that shows job ids. Acceptance: kb status shows short job ids; kb jobs list / prune still works; stale job reaper still works; integration tests pass.","kind":"task","title":"refactor(jobs): convert job ids to terseid"}	blake3:0wYF90QYjbmYiR0WqNTkOXnQ0LakVgg5KDhIzu73O0s
1776700899375649	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt5AU		item.create	bn-1525	{"description":"Now that ids are shorter via terseid, wire its IdResolver for prefix matching so users can type 'src-a7' to match 'src-a7x3q9'. Per terseid README: use IdResolver::resolve(partial, known_check, find_substrings). In run_inspect (crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs around line 1601): when the bare id check (resolve_source_id) fails, try IdResolver against all known src ids (walk normalized/ dir). Similarly for concept ids and question ids. In run_forget (crates/kb-cli/src/forget.rs) similarly: user types 'kb forget src-a7' → resolve to the unique full id, error if ambiguous with a clear list of candidates. Use terseid's AmbiguousId error type. Acceptance: kb inspect src-a7 works when there's only one src-a7X; errors with candidates listed when >1 match; exact full-id matches still work as before. kb forget same. Integration tests covering unique-prefix, ambiguous-prefix, and no-match cases. No backwards compat concerns.","kind":"task","title":"feat(inspect+forget): use terseid IdResolver for prefix matching"}	blake3:5xIjfDUaUPgY2oZIv62cNRpiQbD3nvyajTPOkyVsPa0
1776701328006635	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt5QU		item.move	bn-221i	{"state":"done"}	blake3:F5tBNQzEyGqoqRI1baoXQ3WVgUQCacJAFDD_poXAEAw
1776701606972272	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt5gU		item.move	bn-3v4a	{"state":"done"}	blake3:wwyQ3B5whzC24Ki8rMqX1zJ4-cDW6noppfqokgYAKHo
1776701764587563	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt5wU		item.move	bn-2gwa	{"state":"done"}	blake3:j4RLv6i0E3tfKZRjboiCuBgWRR35bYvXh8rHTB92CnY
1776701924660430	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6AU		item.move	bn-1525	{"state":"done"}	blake3:vMjTeDXm72vqJvetsB0mNdHIL2qt3cmt6eC-PlFtqkY
1776704978852973	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6QU		item.create	bn-1zxb	{"description":"\nAdd `kb chat` — interactive multi-turn session about the KB via opencode's TUI with a KB-specific custom agent injected at command time.\n\n## Pattern (from ~/src/chief/ws/default/src/runner/opencode.rs + coo.rs)\n\nchief's COO does this by:\n1. Write a system prompt to a file (e.g. state/chat/system_prompt.md).\n2. Generate a `.kb/opencode.json` that defines a primary agent named 'kb-chat' with:\n   - model (from kb.toml llm.default_model or --model override)\n   - prompt: `{file:<path-to-system-prompt>}`\n   - tools: read=true, bash=true (for grep), write=false, edit=false — the agent should read the KB but not mutate files\n3. Spawn `opencode --agent kb-chat` with `OPENCODE_CONFIG=.kb/opencode.json`, current_dir set to KB root, stdio inherited (TUI takeover).\n\nSee the full impl at `~/src/chief/ws/default/src/runner/opencode.rs::generate_opencode_config` (~40 lines) and `::spawn_interactive` (~20 lines). Copy that pattern into a new `crates/kb-cli/src/runner/opencode.rs` module (or re-use any existing runner code in kb-llm).\n\n## System prompt content\n\nThe system prompt (written to disk at launch, torn down on exit — use tempfile) tells the agent:\n\n```\nYou are a read-only assistant for a personal knowledge base at {root}.\n\nThe KB has:\n- wiki/concepts/<name>.md — extracted concepts with backlinks\n- wiki/sources/src-<id>.md — summaries of ingested sources\n- wiki/questions/<slug>.md — promoted past Q&As\n- wiki/index.md, wiki/concepts/index.md, wiki/sources/index.md — navigation\n- normalized/src-<id>/source.md — full original text\n- outputs/questions/q-<id>/ — prior ask artifacts\n\nUse grep and read tools to answer. Cite sources inline with the path,\ne.g. 'per wiki/sources/src-abc.md'.\n\nWhen asked for a topic overview, start with wiki/concepts/<topic>.md, then\ndrill into mentioned source pages.\n\nThe user can run slash-commands inside this session — opencode handles them.\n```\n\n## New command\n\nAdd `Command::Chat { model: Option<String> }` to the Cli enum.\n\nHandler `run_chat(root, cli_model)`:\n1. Load kb.toml, pick runner + model (opencode only for v1; claude requires separate TUI integration).\n2. Error cleanly if opencode isn't configured: \"kb chat requires an [llm.runners.opencode] block\".\n3. Write system prompt to `state/chat/system-prompt-<terseid>.md`.\n4. Generate `.kb/opencode.json` agent config.\n5. `Command::new(\"opencode\").arg(\"--agent\").arg(\"kb-chat\").env(\"OPENCODE_CONFIG\", config_path).current_dir(root).status()`.\n6. On exit: keep the transcript? opencode handles its own sessions; don't double-manage. Clean up the temp system-prompt file.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb chat` in a compiled KB launches opencode's TUI, user can chat, opencode can grep/read the wiki tree, exit via opencode's exit command.\n- `kb chat --model claude-sonnet-4-6` overrides the default model (if the runner supports it).\n- Opencode not configured → clean error, no crash.\n- No tests required for the TUI-inherited-stdio path (not testable without a PTY). Unit tests for: the system prompt generator, the opencode.json generator, the model/runner picker.\n- No backwards compat concerns (new command).\n\n## Future (out of scope for this bone)\n\n- Post-chat promote: parse opencode transcript, queue interesting turns as review items.\n- Slash-commands for kb-native operations (/promote, /search, /inspect) via opencode plugin or pass-through.\n- Claude-Code TUI variant (claude runs interactively too; requires separate wiring).\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(chat): kb chat interactive mode via injected opencode agent (chief-COO pattern)"}	blake3:71GW1UiFEt8L5wVsE-DOIxPLV4KOxMznQs7fMJRyZpU
1776705003304531	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6gU		item.create	bn-3iq4	{"description":"\nWhen `kb ask` is invoked with no query argument and stdin is a TTY, open an interactive editor for multi-line question entry. Submit with Ctrl-D. On EOF of empty input, exit cleanly with no ask.\n\n## Current behavior\n\n`resolve_query` treats `None` and `Some(\"-\")` identically — both pipe-read stdin. If stdin is a TTY, users get no prompt, no feedback — the terminal hangs silently waiting for input, then they have to Ctrl-D to finish. No multi-line editor, no line-editing keys.\n\n## Desired behavior\n\nIn `resolve_query` (or wherever `run_ask` gets its query):\n\n1. Detect if stdin is a TTY: `atty::is(Stream::Stdin)` or `std::io::stdin().is_terminal()` (stable from Rust 1.70).\n2. If query arg is None AND stdin is TTY:\n   - Print a prompt:\n     ```\n     Enter your question (multi-line; Ctrl-D to submit, Ctrl-C to abort):\n     > \n     ```\n   - Use rustyline's `rl.readline_with_initial` in a loop, OR collect lines from stdin until EOF. Rustyline gives proper line editing (arrows, home/end, history within the session). Plain stdin is simpler but no line editing.\n   - Pick rustyline for the UX win — add it to kb-cli/Cargo.toml.\n   - Submit the joined string as the query.\n3. If query arg is None AND stdin is NOT TTY (piped):\n   - Fall through to today's behavior (read stdin to EOF).\n4. If query arg is Some(\"-\"):\n   - Current behavior (read stdin), regardless of TTY. Explicit `-` means \"I know what I'm doing\".\n5. If query arg is Some(q) and q is non-empty:\n   - Use it directly (today's fast path).\n\n## Rustyline usage\n\n```rust\nuse rustyline::{Editor, error::ReadlineError};\nlet mut rl = Editor::<()>::new()?;\nlet mut lines = Vec::new();\nloop {\n    let prompt = if lines.is_empty() { \"> \" } else { \"... \" };\n    match rl.readline(prompt) {\n        Ok(line) => lines.push(line),\n        Err(ReadlineError::Eof) => break,  // Ctrl-D\n        Err(ReadlineError::Interrupted) => return Err(...),  // Ctrl-C\n        Err(e) => return Err(e.into()),\n    }\n}\nlet query = lines.join(\"\\n\");\nif query.trim().is_empty() { bail!(\"ask: question cannot be empty\"); }\n```\n\nThe existing empty-query check (from bn-2s6) still applies — Ctrl-D with nothing typed → clean error.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask` with no arg, running in a terminal: prompts, accepts multi-line input, Ctrl-D submits, runs the ask.\n- `kb ask` with no arg, stdin piped: reads stdin (no TTY prompt).\n- `echo \"X\" | kb ask -` works as today.\n- `kb ask \"X\"` works as today.\n- `kb ask` with Ctrl-D on empty input: exits cleanly (or errors with \"question cannot be empty\" — either is fine, be consistent).\n- Ctrl-C during input: aborts cleanly, exit 1.\n- Integration test for the TTY path is not strictly required (hard to simulate a PTY in cargo test). Test the non-TTY path and the query-building logic separately.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't change the semantics of explicit `-` or explicit query arg.\n- Don't add dependencies on terminal escape codes beyond what rustyline provides.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ask): no-arg kb ask opens interactive multi-line readline editor (Ctrl-D to submit)"}	blake3:1-1AL8SGPNGdiA2TTp3s2fIwyflzPMrAtQAY-j88rrs
1776705507418547	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt6wU		item.move	bn-3iq4	{"state":"done"}	blake3:ETMVkBFKQYm45Z9zdk4w5-oIkofCqu_fUWgAT19Emp4
1776705619897202	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt7AU		item.move	bn-1zxb	{"state":"done"}	blake3:eB97I3xiscqQADj4N6YRH83AtSGiqq6EQOT2JB01De0
1776705985271208	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt7QU		item.create	bn-1dar	{"description":"\nbn-3iq4 added rustyline multi-line input for no-arg `kb ask` on a TTY — but you can only edit within the line you're currently typing. Once Enter is pressed, that line is committed. Arrow-up gives readline history, not prior lines of the current question.\n\nAdd two paths to $EDITOR:\n\n## 1. `kb ask -e` / `kb ask --editor`\n\nExplicit: open $EDITOR (env var fallback chain: `$VISUAL` → `$EDITOR` → `vi`) on an empty tempfile at `/tmp/kb-ask-<terseid>.md` (or platform temp). User writes their question, saves, closes. kb reads the content back, strips comment lines starting with `#` (like git commit does), validates non-empty, runs the ask.\n\nPre-populate the tempfile with a comment header:\n\n```\n# Write your question below. Lines starting with # are ignored.\n# Save and close to submit; close with empty content to cancel.\n```\n\n## 2. Ctrl-X Ctrl-E during readline multi-line entry\n\nRustyline supports a `Cmd::EditFile` or external-editor binding. Bind Ctrl-X Ctrl-E to it. When the user hits Ctrl-X Ctrl-E during their readline session, rustyline opens $EDITOR on the current buffer; after save+close, the edited content replaces the buffer and readline continues.\n\nThis is standard bash/readline behavior — many users already reach for Ctrl-X Ctrl-E reflexively.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask -e` opens $EDITOR on a tempfile with the comment header, user writes, saves, ask runs.\n- `kb ask --editor` same as -e.\n- `kb ask` in a TTY keeps today's readline behavior as the default quick-path; Ctrl-X Ctrl-E at any prompt opens $EDITOR on the current buffer.\n- Empty content (or only comment lines) after editor closes → bail with \"ask: question cannot be empty\" (ValidationError, no failed-job manifest).\n- `$VISUAL` preferred over `$EDITOR`; `vi` fallback if neither set.\n- Integration test for the --editor flag path using a test $EDITOR that writes a fixture (e.g. `sh -c 'echo hello > $1'`). TTY+Ctrl-X path can't be automated.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't block the readline fast-path behind a flag. Ctrl-X Ctrl-E is additive.\n- Don't delete the tempfile if the user saved an empty file — they might want to recover. Trust tmpfs cleanup OR unlink after successful read.\n- Don't force an editor choice; respect env.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ask): multi-line editing via nvim (--editor flag + Ctrl-X Ctrl-E escape hatch)"}	blake3:qsjqbvgZD9ayVPfExqRJOyU_l5KhlTAfY9qSXWwXqg0
1776706103556931	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt7gU		item.create	bn-ozj5	{"description":"\nbn-3iq4 used rustyline for no-arg `kb ask` on a TTY. Rustyline's multi-line mode is a stack of single-line prompts — once Enter is pressed on a line, it's committed; arrow-up gives history, not prior lines of the current question.\n\nReplace with `reedline` (nushell's line editor) which has native multi-line editing: arrow-up navigates BACK INTO the current buffer's earlier lines, arrow-down forward, full block editing as if in a small editor.\n\n## Scope\n\nOnly the no-arg TTY path inside `run_ask`. Everything else stays:\n- `kb ask \"X\"` — unchanged\n- `kb ask --editor` (bn-1dar) — unchanged, still launches $EDITOR\n- `kb ask -` — still reads stdin\n- piped stdin (no TTY) — still reads to EOF\n\n## Implementation\n\nIn `crates/kb-cli/Cargo.toml`: drop `rustyline` if only used for ask (check other callsites first — other commands might use it). Add `reedline = \"0.38\"` (or latest stable).\n\nIn `crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs` `read_interactive_multiline`:\n\n```rust\nuse reedline::{Reedline, Signal, Prompt, PromptHistorySearch, PromptEditMode, PromptHistorySearchStatus};\n// Configure reedline for multi-line mode. Default Reedline treats Enter as\n// \"submit\". We want Enter = newline, Ctrl-D = submit, Ctrl-C = abort.\n//\n// Reedline supports this via edit-mode key bindings. Specifically, use\n// Reedline::create_default_emacs_keybindings() and re-bind Enter to\n// ReedlineEvent::Newline (inserts newline instead of submit). Bind Ctrl-D\n// to ReedlineEvent::Submit. Ctrl-C stays Interrupt.\n//\n// Research the exact binding names in reedline 0.38+; the README has examples.\n\nlet mut line_editor = Reedline::create()\n    .with_edit_mode(/* custom emacs keybindings as above */);\nlet prompt = /* a simple Prompt impl */;\n\neprintln!(\"Enter your question (multi-line; Ctrl-D to submit, Ctrl-C to abort):\");\nmatch line_editor.read_line(&prompt) {\n    Ok(Signal::Success(text)) => {\n        // This path when the user hits our rebound submit (Ctrl-D).\n        if text.trim().is_empty() { bail ValidationError }\n        Ok(text)\n    }\n    Ok(Signal::CtrlD) => bail ValidationError(empty),  // Ctrl-D on empty buffer\n    Ok(Signal::CtrlC) => bail ValidationError(aborted),\n    Err(e) => Err(e),\n}\n```\n\nLook at reedline's docs.rs and README examples for the exact keybinding API. The upstream nushell config shows this pattern.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask` in a TTY: prompt appears, user can enter multiple lines, arrow-up navigates to previous lines of the CURRENT input, editing works, Ctrl-D submits, Ctrl-C aborts.\n- The ValidationError path (bn-1jx) continues to prevent failed-job manifests on empty/aborted input.\n- Existing tests pass (the piped-stdin path is unaffected).\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't touch --editor (bn-1dar) or the piped-stdin paths.\n- Don't add a new flag; this is a straight replacement of rustyline in the TTY-no-arg path.\n- Don't remove rustyline if other commands depend on it. Check `grep -rn rustyline crates/` first.\n\n## Note on testing\n\nLike bn-3iq4, the TTY interactive path can't be unit-tested without a PTY. Manual verification only. Tests cover the dispatch (is_terminal check), the empty-input bail, and the piped-stdin path.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ask): switch no-arg TTY input from rustyline to reedline for native multi-line editing"}	blake3:2RyW9eaq_ymLLNet3AgqGY4Ei_xAIP1UjfZ36UtLKg4
1776706486729561	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt7wU		item.move	bn-1dar	{"state":"done"}	blake3:E8annt8xPkbFfoAZ5HRxLTb_-97j-gfEvbsXqNSLktw
1776706979924294	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt8AU		item.move	bn-ozj5	{"state":"done"}	blake3:Mg2lbG9TsmlNL-cHWtUiRCXtG6AeVDXDBvztXH_UcBg
1776707995643318	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt8QU		item.create	bn-23ym	{"description":"User-requested UX tweak. Replace DefaultPrompt's 'ask〉' with '>>> '.","kind":"task","title":"chore(ask): use >>> as prompt indicator instead of 'ask〉'"}	blake3:7wbMvxt6xiQ8SNDSR60FIsIWRH8UGgTevrTIs5SDi74
1776708128867510	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt8gU		item.move	bn-23ym	{"state":"done"}	blake3:zh37STdgo0QVdmnishjVoB1wXddNxO89K9oZg61623Y
1776708395864721	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt8wU		item.create	bn-1yvv	{"description":"\nAudit repro: `kb ask` with \"what is this wiki about?\" on a compiled KB returned '0 valid, 0 unresolved' citations and a 'low source coverage' banner. The answer was effectively useless.\n\nThe retrieval scorer finds nothing because the query terms ('wiki', 'about') don't map to any indexed summary. High-level overview queries are systematically underserved.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdd a **low-coverage fallback** in `crates/kb-query/src/lexical.rs` (or retrieval planner):\n\n1. Run normal retrieval.\n2. If the resulting plan has < MIN_CANDIDATES (say 3), OR the top score is < MIN_SCORE (say 2), expand:\n   a. Always include `wiki/index.md`, `wiki/concepts/index.md`, `wiki/sources/index.md` as baseline candidates (they name every concept + source, giving the LLM a table of contents to reason from).\n   b. Optionally include the top N source summaries by length/recency so the LLM has something concrete to cite.\n3. Mark these as `fallback: true` in the retrieval plan's reason strings so users can see what happened.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask \"what is this wiki about?\"` on a compiled KB returns an answer citing index pages + sample sources — not an empty-citations 'uncertainty banner' case.\n- `kb ask \"X\"` for a specific topic where retrieval finds 5+ strong candidates is UNCHANGED (fallback doesn't fire).\n- Retrieval plan JSON shows the expansion when it happens: `{\"fallback\": \"low-coverage\", \"reason\": \"top score was 0; adding index pages\"}`.\n- Integration test: seed a KB where no source matches the query; assert retrieval plan contains the three index pages + at least one source page.\n- Existing tests where retrieval works normally must still pass.\n","kind":"task","title":"fix(ask): retrieval returns 0 candidates for high-level meta queries ('what is this wiki about?')"}	blake3:E1ZZeKRARI-ppe7Oqlf6cPDfN2lcc73EffLWk-TUraY
1776708414911432	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt9AU		item.create	bn-1m02	{"description":"\nToday `kb ask` writes the answer to `outputs/questions/q-<id>/answer.md` and only prints the path. User has to copy+open the file to read it. Annoying.\n\n## Fix\n\nAfter `kb ask` writes the artifact, also render the answer body to stdout with markdown-aware terminal formatting.\n\nOptions:\n- **termimad** (pure Rust, handles headings/bold/italic/code/lists/tables — terminal colors, no external deps). This is the recommended pick.\n- **mdcat** (separate binary) — no.\n- **bat --language md** (subprocess) — portability issue.\n- Plain markdown passthrough — ugly.\n\nGo with **termimad** (`termimad = \"0.31\"` or latest).\n\n## Behavior\n\n- If stdout is a TTY: print the body with termimad's color rendering (headings in bold/color, code fenced blocks highlighted, list bullets styled).\n- If stdout is piped: print the raw markdown as-is so downstream tools see clean markdown.\n- Still print the existing \"Artifact written: ...\" footer so users know the path.\n- `kb ask --json`: suppress the stdout rendering; only JSON goes out (unchanged).\n- `kb ask --quiet`: suppress the rendering; only the path line stays (add this if not already covered by --quiet).\n\nAdd a `--no-render` flag for users who want the current path-only behavior.\n\n## Code blocks syntax highlighting\n\ntermimad renders code-fenced blocks but doesn't syntax-highlight them (yet). If the rendering feels flat, consider piping through `syntect` for fenced blocks before handing to termimad — but for v1, termimad's default rendering is sufficient. File a follow-up bone if needed.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask \"X\"` in a TTY: shows the formatted answer body, then the artifact path footer.\n- `kb ask \"X\" | cat`: raw markdown to stdout, path footer on stderr (or after).\n- `kb ask --json`: JSON only (unchanged).\n- `kb ask --no-render`: old path-only behavior.\n- Integration tests: --no-render, --json, and the piped (non-TTY) case.\n- Rendering the TTY case itself is manually verified (no PTY testing).\n- termimad added to kb-cli/Cargo.toml.\n- `just check` passes.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ask): print the answer to stdout with markdown rendering after generation"}	blake3:SydBy-hY1mOm3Hrnmrop6qH44oye-THJhww5d7HI7WM
1776709059395483	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt9QU		item.move	bn-1m02	{"state":"done"}	blake3:WLBXYuWGybzM5DZ39CjBVRJr_9-pzl9QrAUMQZovdZ4
1776709253198994	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt9gU		item.move	bn-1yvv	{"state":"done"}	blake3:KnV2svAhJZqzxIFRwzW-SZi4nQKj9feiWtVwIfnZ5U4
1776710343978741	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt9wU		item.create	bn-3vky	{"description":"\nToday `kb ingest` uses `ignore::WalkBuilder::standard_filters(true)` which honors `.gitignore`, `.ignore`, and `.git/info/exclude`. Add `.kbignore` as a kb-native exclude file so users can hide files from kb without touching git state.\n\n## Fix\n\nIn `crates/kb-ingest/src/lib.rs` where the WalkBuilder is constructed, add:\n\n```rust\nbuilder.add_custom_ignore_filename(\".kbignore\");\n```\n\nSame syntax as .gitignore. Respects nested .kbignore files in subdirs per ignore crate semantics.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- A directory containing a `.kbignore` file with `secrets.md` excludes that file from `kb ingest <dir>`.\n- Nested `.kbignore` in subdirs also respected.\n- `.gitignore` behavior unchanged; both are honored cumulatively.\n- Integration test in kb-ingest mirroring the existing `directory_ingest_honors_gitignore` test.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- just check` passes.\n\n## Documentation\n\nBriefly mention `.kbignore` support in the README or docs/ if there's a relevant section.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ingest): honor .kbignore files (kb-specific excludes, doesn't pollute .gitignore)"}	blake3:ifYG8_H4r5vPjiZq1niz2jtTtUnEPc8sWdG94vF6OO4
1776710525504864	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt-AU		item.move	bn-3vky	{"state":"done"}	blake3:LvYuZPxedzqKNYDnYrlBH0ue6q9eoYa619MK-7Te5wE
1776711258953202	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt-QU		item.create	bn-1geb	{"description":"\nMarkdown files with image references (e.g. `![alt](./pic.png)`) work as plain text today but the referenced PNGs are never copied anywhere. `wiki/sources/src-xxx.md` ends up with broken image paths, `kb publish` leaves images behind, and the PNG is not preserved even in the KB's own tree.\n\nThe `normalized_assets: Vec&lt;PathBuf&gt;` field on `NormalizedDocument` + the `copy_and_validate_assets` helper in `kb-core/src/normalized.rs` are already scaffolded. Ingest just doesn't populate them.\n\n## Scope\n\nThree tightly-coupled parts, best done as one bone:\n\n### Part A — scan + copy on ingest (crates/kb-ingest/src/lib.rs)\n\nWhen ingesting a markdown file:\n\n1. Parse the markdown to extract image references. Two forms:\n   - `![alt](path)` — markdown image\n   - `&lt;img src=\\\"path\\\"&gt;` — raw HTML image (optional; markdown-only is fine for v1)\n2. For each reference whose path:\n   - is relative (not `http://`, `https://`, `data:`)\n   - resolves to a file that exists on disk (relative to the source markdown file's dir, or relative to cwd if absolute)\n   - passes the existing binary-safe check OR has an allow-listed extension (`.png`, `.jpg`, `.jpeg`, `.gif`, `.svg`, `.webp`)\n3. Copy the file to `normalized/src-xxx/assets/&lt;basename&gt;`. On basename collision (e.g. `./a/pic.png` + `./b/pic.png`), hash-suffix: `pic-a7x.png`.\n4. Rewrite the markdown's image path to `assets/&lt;new-basename&gt;`.\n5. Populate `normalized_assets` with the resolved paths.\n6. Existing `copy_and_validate_assets` handles the actual write (it's already there; currently a no-op because Vec is empty).\n\nURLs (http://, https://) stay untouched — we don't fetch remote images. Broken references (relative paths that don't resolve) stay untouched with a warning logged.\n\n### Part B — compile preserves image paths correctly\n\n`wiki/sources/src-xxx.md` is generated from the normalized source. After Part A, normalized source.md references `assets/foo.png` (relative to `normalized/src-xxx/`). The wiki source page is at `wiki/sources/src-xxx.md`, which is a different depth.\n\nFor the wiki page to work when viewed from its own location (Obsidian, GitHub, VSCode preview), the image references in the WIKI page should point to `../../normalized/src-xxx/assets/foo.png` (file-relative from the wiki page). Matches bn-2hz's pattern.\n\nIf the LLM doesn't naturally preserve image references in the summary (it might drop them), that's acceptable for v1 — summaries are text-focused. The critical case is that when images ARE mentioned in the summary, the path resolves correctly.\n\nEven better: after the LLM writes the summary, post-process to rewrite any image references in the summary or any extracted concept body to the correct relative path. This is belt-and-suspenders.\n\n### Part C — publish copies assets\n\n`kb publish &lt;target&gt;` filter is `wiki/**` today. Extend the publish walker to ALSO copy `normalized/*/assets/*` into the target's matching location.\n\nSimplest: if target filter is the default `wiki/**`, also copy `normalized/*/assets/` under the target's `normalized/assets/` or similar. The path scheme matters: wiki pages need to RESOLVE these after publish.\n\nCleanest path scheme: rewrite wiki pages during publish so image references point to an `assets/` subdir under the target, and copy assets into `&lt;target&gt;/assets/&lt;src-xxx&gt;-&lt;basename&gt;`. This flattens the per-source dirs so Obsidian vaults don't see a `normalized/` tree.\n\nIf that rewrite is too invasive for v1, alternate: just mirror the tree — copy `normalized/*/assets/*` to `&lt;target&gt;/normalized/*/assets/*` and rely on wiki pages' existing `../../normalized/...` references (from Part B). Less elegant but simpler.\n\nPick whichever is simpler. Document the choice in the commit.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- Ingest a markdown file with `![fig](./figures/diagram.png)` where the PNG exists: normalized/src-xxx/assets/diagram.png is created; normalized/src-xxx/source.md references `assets/diagram.png`; normalized_assets list includes the path.\n- Multiple images with same basename get hash-suffixed.\n- Missing/broken relative paths: warn, leave the reference in place, continue.\n- URLs are untouched.\n- Compile: wiki/sources/src-xxx.md (if it references the image in its summary) has a working relative path that resolves via filesystem `join`.\n- Publish: target directory has the image file in an accessible location; rewritten wiki pages' image refs resolve inside the published tree.\n- Integration tests for each part:\n  - ingest-with-png: seed md + png, ingest, assert assets copied + markdown rewritten\n  - ingest-basename-collision: two pngs with same name, different dirs\n  - ingest-missing-png: md references a non-existent path, warn but don't fail\n  - publish-with-assets: ingest + compile + publish, assert published tree has images at expected paths\n- `maw exec &lt;ws&gt; -- just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't fetch remote images. http/https URLs stay literal.\n- Don't implement multimodal ask (separate bone — the LLM still treats images as text references).\n- Don't copy large binary files indiscriminately. Cap at e.g. 10MB per asset; skip with warning above that.\n- Don't alter the `binary content detected` rejection for the top-level markdown file itself; that check is about whether the FILE is text, unrelated to its referenced images.\n- Don't strip image references from summaries if the LLM preserves them — let the model decide.\n\n## Stretch (future, not this bone)\n\n- SVGs embedded as inline XML could be passed to the LLM as text for OCR-lite.\n- Multimodal backends (gpt-4o, claude opus) could receive images in retrieval-plan candidates.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(assets): copy referenced images on ingest, rewrite paths through compile, publish assets too"}	blake3:eGVhtAsiuotGdyir41nDqdFOgSK3FBZTTooK_nNAC9U
1776711680916612	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt-gU		item.create	bn-327j	{"description":"\n`kb compile` currently emits line-by-line progress like:\n\n```\n  [run] source_summary: src-c78151f0...\n  [ok]  source_summary: src-c78151f0 (8.4s)\n  [run] concept_extraction: src-c78151f0...\n  [ok]  concept_extraction: src-c78151f0 (22.2s)\n  [run] concept_merge: 54 candidate(s)...\n```\n\nIt's readable but doesn't give a good at-a-glance sense of completion. Replace with indicatif progress bars on a TTY, fall back to today's format for non-TTY / --json / piped stdout.\n\n## Design\n\nUse `indicatif = \"0.17\"` (or latest).\n\nShow a `MultiProgress` display with one bar per active pass. Possible layout:\n\n```\n  source_summary       [##########------------] 7/11  (tokio-tasks.md)\n  concept_extraction   [######----------------] 4/11  (rust-async.md)\n```\n\nOr, simpler: one overall bar for the current pass, one below for sub-operation count:\n\n```\n  Pass 2/6: concept_extraction\n  [#############-----------] 7/11  rust-async.md (22s)\n```\n\n## Where\n\n`crates/kb-compile/src/pipeline.rs` has the `CompileOptions.progress` flag and `emit_event`. Current line-by-line is piped through that.\n\nRefactor into a `ProgressReporter` trait with two impls:\n- `IndicatifReporter` — multi-progress bars, only used when stdout is a TTY and --json is off\n- `LineLogReporter` — today's `[run]`/`[ok]` lines to stderr; used for non-TTY, --quiet, --json\n\nThe existing `CompileOptions.log_sink` stays — it gets the same lines regardless, so compile logs in `state/jobs/*.log` don't change format.\n\n## Behavior matrix\n\n| stdout state | flags                  | output                                |\n|--------------|------------------------|---------------------------------------|\n| TTY          | (default)              | indicatif multi-bar                   |\n| piped        | (any)                  | line-by-line [run]/[ok]               |\n| TTY          | --json                 | JSON only, no bars/lines              |\n| TTY          | --quiet                | minimal: one-line \"compiling...\" + done |\n\n## indicatif details\n\n- Use `MultiProgress` to own multiple concurrent bars.\n- Per pass: `ProgressBar::new(total)`, `set_style` with a template like `\"  {prefix:20.cyan} [{bar:30}] {pos}/{len}  {msg}\"`.\n- On pass start: pb.set_prefix(pass_name).\n- On per-doc progress: pb.inc(1), pb.set_message(current doc).\n- On pass end: pb.finish_with_message(elapsed).\n- concept_merge is one long opaque blob — use a spinner variant (ProgressStyle::with_template + .spinner()) since there's no per-doc granularity. Show elapsed time.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- TTY: bars render, update smoothly, clean up on completion.\n- Piped: line-by-line output unchanged (grep/sed-friendly).\n- --json: no bars, no log lines on stdout; only the final JSON.\n- --quiet: minimal output.\n- state/jobs/*.log has the same line-based log as today (no bar escape sequences in the log).\n- Existing CompileOptions.log_sink unchanged.\n- Integration test for the piped fallback path (can't test TTY in cargo test).\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't add bars to non-compile commands (ingest, ask, lint are fast enough — not worth the complication).\n- Don't break JSON output — bars must not leak to stdout when --json is set.\n- Don't change the log format in state/jobs/*.log files.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(compile): replace line-by-line progress with indicatif progress bars (TTY only)"}	blake3:m0rhshpBLEP1n7th4weTFI1Aqi2nB7yg_t6uekGyctM
1776712284115830	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt-wU		item.move	bn-1geb	{"state":"done"}	blake3:KfenWoxKChLxz-MVk7bmpH9clYFKUOxFO83oFXay_Ek
1776712529673804	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_AU		item.move	bn-327j	{"state":"done"}	blake3:JaOdHkLzyzGr_IuqChnQv_6yFHMFc_kVyGajpsEC7yc
1776713208545950	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_QU		item.create	bn-1sl5	{"description":"\nKarpathy's diagram lists Repos as a first-class source type. Today `kb ingest <git-url>` falls through to URL fetching (probably rendering as empty or garbage).\n\n## Fix\n\nWhen the ingest path matches a git URL pattern (`https://github.com/*`, `git@*:*/*`, `.git` suffix, or explicit `git+` prefix):\n\n1. Shallow-clone (`git clone --depth 1`) into `raw/repos/<src-id>/`\n2. Walk the repo selectively — ingest only:\n   - `README*` at root and subdirs (any case/ext combo)\n   - `CHANGELOG*`, `CONTRIBUTING*`, `ROADMAP*`, etc.\n   - `docs/**/*.md`, `doc/**/*.md`\n   - `*.md` at top-level\n   - Optional: `-i <glob>` / `-e <glob>` flags to include/exclude\n3. Each discovered file becomes its own source_document under a shared `src-<repo-hash>-<subpath>` naming scheme so they're grouped but individually addressable.\n\nStore the git remote URL + revision (commit SHA) in metadata.json for provenance. On re-ingest, skip files whose commit hasn't changed — full git-level incremental support can be a follow-up.\n\n## Flags\n\n- `--include <glob>` / `--exclude <glob>` — override the default walk filter\n- `--branch <name>` — checkout specific branch (default: default branch)\n- `--commit <sha>` — pin to a commit (for reproducibility)\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ingest https://github.com/microsoft/markitdown` clones, finds README + docs, creates source_documents for each.\n- Re-ingest of the same URL with no changes: all files skipped.\n- Re-ingest after upstream push: new revisions for changed files.\n- Metadata records remote URL + commit SHA.\n- `--include '*.rs'` pulls Rust files (for code-heavy repos where the LLM should see the source).\n- Respects `.gitignore` within the cloned repo.\n- Integration test with a seeded git repo via `tempfile` + `git init`.\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't ingest arbitrary binary files (respect the existing is-text check).\n- Don't fetch submodules by default.\n- Don't check out large binary-heavy history; always shallow clone.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ingest): repo ingestion via kb ingest <git-url>"}	blake3:AuyX3XdJaVwUDFUQ2jPOosNKFrwWd2z22Hwvynpwz8I
1776713234350120	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_gU		item.create	bn-23am	{"description":"\nThe user has Microsoft's `markitdown` installed (https://github.com/microsoft/markitdown). It converts:\n\n- PDF, Word (.docx), PowerPoint (.pptx), Excel (.xlsx)\n- Images (with OCR via Azure Document Intelligence or local OCR)\n- Audio (with transcription)\n- HTML, CSV, JSON, XML, ZIP\n- EPub, Outlook .msg\n\n...all to markdown.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdd a preprocessing step in `kb ingest`:\n\n1. Detect non-markdown file types via extension (initial cut — use MIME or magic bytes later):\n   - `.pdf, .docx, .pptx, .xlsx, .xls, .doc, .ppt`\n   - `.html, .htm, .xml`\n   - `.csv, .json` (optional — they're technically text but markitdown's output is more structured)\n   - `.epub, .msg`\n   - `.mp3, .wav, .m4a` (if audio transcription desired)\n   - `.png, .jpg, .jpeg` only if user opts in (OCR is slower)\n2. When detected, invoke `markitdown <input>` as a subprocess, capture stdout as markdown.\n3. Cache converted markdown in `raw/inbox/<src>/<rev>/original.<ext>` + `raw/inbox/<src>/<rev>/source.md` (the converted form). The .md is what enters the normalize pipeline.\n4. Source ID is based on the ORIGINAL file's stable location (path), so re-ingest after file changes still dedupes correctly.\n\n## Config\n\n`kb.toml`:\n\n```toml\n[ingest.markitdown]\nenabled = true              # default: true if markitdown is on PATH\ncommand = \"markitdown\"     # override if needed\n# Per-extension controls\nextensions = [\"pdf\", \"docx\", \"pptx\", \"xlsx\", \"html\", \"epub\"]\n# Opt-in extensions (slower or require cloud API)\noptional_extensions = [\"png\", \"jpg\", \"mp3\"]\n```\n\n## Failure handling\n\n- markitdown not on PATH: warn once, skip all non-md inputs. Or bail cleanly if user explicitly ingests a PDF.\n- markitdown conversion fails: log error, skip the file, move on.\n- markitdown produces empty output: skip with warning (same as the existing empty-file handling from bn-40r).\n\n## Where\n\nNew module `crates/kb-ingest/src/preprocess.rs` or similar. Called from `ingest_file` before the text/binary check. The binary check would reject a PDF today — so the preprocess step runs BEFORE binary detection.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ingest paper.pdf` with markitdown installed: converts, ingests the resulting markdown.\n- `kb ingest paper.pdf` WITHOUT markitdown: error \"markitdown not found; install from https://github.com/microsoft/markitdown or set ingest.markitdown.enabled = false\".\n- `kb ingest folder/` with mixed .md + .pdf files: processes both.\n- Re-ingest of the same PDF with same content: idempotent (src-id stable, content hash matches).\n- Integration test with a fake `markitdown` shell script that echoes a known markdown output.\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't vendor markitdown or its deps.\n- Don't convert files whose extension is already `.md` / `.txt` / etc.\n- Don't call markitdown on every extension by default (some conversions are slow or cost money).\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ingest): preprocess non-markdown files through markitdown (PDF/Word/Excel/images/audio)"}	blake3:hvM06G1u0BsiuyCtMVfV1yW8QEB73MnnSjPW4r764Fk
1776713260101700	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_wU		item.create	bn-31lt	{"description":"\nKarpathy's diagram calls out 'Suggest new articles' as a lint output. kb today only lints for broken structure; it doesn't suggest missing content.\n\n## Fix\n\nNew lint check `missing_concepts`:\n\n1. Walk all normalized source bodies, extract noun phrases (or just capitalized multi-word terms + common technical tokens).\n2. For each, count occurrences across the corpus.\n3. For each term that:\n   - Appears in ≥ 3 different sources (threshold configurable)\n   - Is NOT the name/alias of any existing concept page\n   - Is not a stopword\n4. Emit a lint suggestion: \"concept candidate 'X' mentioned in N sources but no concept page exists; consider creating one\".\n5. Queue these as review items with `kind: concept_candidate`, `suggested_name: \"X\"`, `source_hits: [src-ids]`, so users can `kb review approve` to auto-create a concept page from the mentions.\n\n## Implementation sketch\n\nExtractors (pick one, keep simple):\n- Regex for capitalized multi-word spans (`\\b[A-Z][a-z]+(?:\\s+[A-Z][a-z]+){1,3}\\b`) — catches proper nouns and CamelCase\n- Backtick-quoted identifiers in markdown (`\\`)\n- Most-frequent bigrams/trigrams after stopword removal (more sophisticated; TF-IDF-lite)\n\nStart with the regex approach. It's noisy but catches the common case.\n\n## Approve workflow\n\n`kb review approve concept-candidate:<name>` triggers a compile pass that:\n1. Calls the LLM with the term + the source snippets where it appears\n2. Has the LLM produce a concept page (name, aliases, definition, source_document_ids)\n3. Writes `wiki/concepts/<slug>.md`\n4. Runs backlinks refresh\n\nSimilar to how the existing concept_merge apply flow works (bn-1e9).\n\n## Config\n\n```toml\n[lint.missing_concepts]\nenabled = true\nmin_sources = 3     # term must appear in N distinct sources\nmin_mentions = 5    # total mentions across corpus\n```\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb lint --check missing_concepts` scans corpus, emits review items for high-frequency uncovered terms.\n- Review items are approvable; approval triggers concept creation via the LLM.\n- Terms matching an existing concept alias are not flagged.\n- Integration test: seed a corpus with term 'FooBar' in 3 source bodies; assert review item emitted.\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't auto-create concept pages without human approval.\n- Don't flag acronyms that are too short or too common.\n- Don't rescan the entire corpus every lint run if expensive; hash state could mark this as a slow check.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(lint): suggest missing-concept candidates (terms mentioned heavily but no concept page)"}	blake3:WQjXt3No8ZCeRV_29ngLxWlr_J1OBmndQzc7UwAdRH4
1776713280812635	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgAY		item.create	bn-3axp	{"description":"\nKarpathy's diagram lists 'Find inconsistencies' as a lint. When two source documents make contradictory claims about the same concept, the wiki is unreliable. Add an LLM-powered check that surfaces these.\n\n## Fix\n\nNew lint check `contradictions`:\n\n1. For each concept, gather all source quotes in its frontmatter `sources[].quote`.\n2. If the concept has quotes from ≥ 2 different sources, hand them to the LLM with a prompt like: 'Do these quotes make contradictory claims about X? Reply with JSON {contradiction: bool, explanation: str, conflicting_quotes: [int indices]}'.\n3. If contradiction detected, queue a review item with kind `contradiction` listing the conflicting quotes + explanation.\n\n## Cost control\n\nThis is O(concepts) LLM calls. Gate behind a config flag since it's expensive:\n\n```toml\n[lint.contradictions]\nenabled = false     # off by default\nmin_sources = 2\n```\n\nOr invoke only on-demand: `kb lint --check contradictions`.\n\n## Review UX\n\n`kb review show contradiction:<id>` displays the concept + quotes + LLM explanation. Approve = mark acknowledged (doesn't auto-fix); reject = dismiss (flagged as 'intended nuance' so it doesn't re-fire).\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb lint --check contradictions` runs the LLM pass, emits review items for actual contradictions.\n- False-positive rate is reasonable on a small corpus (manual verification).\n- Review items include the LLM's explanation.\n- Acknowledgement persists across runs (same pair doesn't re-fire until sources change).\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't run by default in `kb lint` — it's expensive.\n- Don't auto-resolve contradictions.\n- Don't scan concept pairs across different concepts.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(lint): cross-source contradiction detection"}	blake3:mAhH8HETyh1gvyOJBWHkYYvBD2Lr9071d2EnIuVMmag
1776713301797367	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgQY		item.create	bn-xt4o	{"description":"\nKarpathy: 'Impute missing data (with web searchers)'. When a source has incomplete information about a concept, use a web search agent to fill in gaps.\n\n## Fix\n\nNew command or lint mode: `kb lint --impute` OR `kb augment`.\n\nFor each concept page, the LLM is prompted with the concept name + current definition + list of source quotes, and asked: 'Are there any standard facts about X that are not covered by these sources?'. If yes, it runs a web search (via opencode/claude's web tool), finds sources, and suggests:\n\n1. A new supplemental source to ingest (the LLM returns a URL)\n2. An inline note to append to the concept page (citing the web source)\n\nBoth routed through the review queue so the user approves.\n\n## Review UX\n\n`kb review show augment:<id>`:\n\n```\nConcept: Merkle tree\nCurrent definition: A hash-linked binary tree used in distributed systems.\nLLM suggests augmentation:\n  - Missing: use in IPFS and git object storage\n  - Suggested source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merkle_tree\n  - Suggested append: 'Widely used in IPFS and Git for content-addressable storage.'\n```\n\nApprove → offers to kb ingest the suggested URL, then recompiles the concept with the new source in scope. Reject → records a dismissal so the same gap doesn't re-fire.\n\n## Config\n\nRequires opencode/claude with web-search tool enabled (should already work — opencode has web by default).\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb lint --impute` on a corpus with a known-incomplete concept surfaces a review item with a suggested source URL + inline note.\n- Approve → ingests the URL, recompiles, concept page is updated.\n- Manual verification on a small real corpus.\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't apply augmentations without review.\n- Don't run on every lint invocation — expensive + depends on external network.\n- Don't run in --json mode or CI.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(lint): --impute web-search-backed gap backfill"}	blake3:j8rHIhqG6y8GEWLIwi_SQ_hZoV9yQK2Zuz6fGfzE_Cg
1776713323200441	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtggY		item.create	bn-3dkw	{"description":"\nbn-1geb made images first-class in the filesystem (copied into normalized/<src>/assets/, paths resolve through compile + publish). But `kb ask` still treats images as inert text references — the LLM sees `![fig](../../normalized/.../assets/foo.png)` but can't see the image itself.\n\nOpencode + openai/gpt-5.4 is multimodal. Claude 4.X is multimodal. We can pass images to them.\n\n## Fix\n\nIn the ask pipeline:\n\n1. When assembling the retrieval context, for each selected source/concept page:\n   - Parse its body for image references pointing at a local asset (file-relative resolution)\n   - Resolve to absolute paths\n2. Include those asset paths in the prompt bundle sent to the LLM runner.\n3. Opencode/claude runner adapters need to accept image paths as part of the request. Check each adapter's CLI:\n   - Opencode: `opencode run` may accept `--attach <path>` or similar\n   - Claude: `claude --add-file <path>` / `--attach <path>`\n   - If neither supports it cleanly via CLI args, fall back to base64-encoding the image and including it in the prompt with a markdown image reference (model-specific — gpt supports data URIs)\n\nResearch required before implementation.\n\n## Prompt change\n\nUpdate `ask.md` to mention:\n\n```\nSome sources include embedded images. When an image is relevant to the answer,\nreference it in your citation and describe what you see.\n```\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- When retrieval picks a source with an image asset, the image is passed to the LLM.\n- Ask answer can describe image content ('the diagram shows X connected to Y').\n- Retrieval plan JSON shows image paths under each candidate.\n- Works with opencode backend. Claude fallback if time permits.\n- Integration test uses a mock LLM adapter that asserts image paths are present in its invocation.\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Scope guardrails\n\n- Only images referenced in the body of candidate pages — don't walk the whole corpus.\n- Cap to e.g. 5 images per query to avoid blowing context.\n- Skip if retrieval candidate list contains no images (zero-cost fast path).\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't implement image generation (matplotlib/charts) here — that's a separate bone.\n- Don't OCR images as a fallback when multimodal isn't available — markitdown's image-OCR path handles that at ingest time.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ask): multimodal retrieval — pass image assets to the LLM"}	blake3:7HP5uThSdXdQjDXUs_YpfwzWSH7Ux33Fky1xz5yR_Qo
1776713342711447	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgwY		item.create	bn-eqx7	{"description":"\nKarpathy's diagram lists 'Categories' alongside Backlinks and Concepts as a core Knowledge Store property. kb today has a flat wiki/concepts/index.md alphabetical listing — no hierarchy.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdd a `category:` field to concept frontmatter, assigned by the LLM during concept_merge.\n\n### Prompt change (merge_concept_candidates.md)\n\nAsk the LLM to pick a high-level category for each concept (1-3 word label):\n\n```\nFor each concept, assign a category from a domain-relevant taxonomy. Examples:\n- Rust topic: 'concurrency', 'async', 'macros', 'ownership', 'ffi'\n- Distributed systems: 'consensus', 'storage', 'networking', 'observability'\n\nThe category is a short tag, not a long description. Choose freely — the system\ninfers a taxonomy from whatever categories you emit across concepts.\n```\n\nResult: concept frontmatter has `category: async`.\n\n### Index rendering\n\n`wiki/concepts/index.md` groups concepts by category:\n\n```markdown\n# Concepts\n\n28 page(s) in 6 categories.\n\n## async\n- [Tokio runtime](tokio-runtime.md)\n- [async fn state machine](async-fn-state-machine.md)\n...\n\n## consensus\n- [Raft](raft-consensus.md)\n- [Paxos](paxos.md)\n...\n```\n\nConcepts with no category (older/manual) go under a final 'Uncategorized' heading.\n\n## Optional: hierarchical categories\n\nAllow `category: distributed-systems/consensus` (slash-delimited path) for deeper structure. v1 can be flat.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- After recompile, concept frontmatter has a `category:` field populated by the LLM.\n- `wiki/concepts/index.md` renders grouped by category.\n- Concept pages with no category fall into Uncategorized.\n- Categories persist through forget/edit/promote cascades (handled like source_document_ids).\n- Integration test: fixture with concepts tagged into 2 categories; assert index has 2 sections.\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't require a pre-defined taxonomy. Let the LLM pick tags from the corpus.\n- Don't require every concept to have a category (some are genuinely generic).\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(compile): concept categories / tags for hierarchical index rendering"}	blake3:L9C6xwQ7lnSHdhny5odiBIkbtpVIXAyoHRH-4gbpjr0
1776713370056036	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthAY		item.create	bn-35ap	{"description":"\nKarpathy's diagram has 'Charts (Matplotlib)' as an output format. Today `kb ask --format=png` errors cleanly. Add a `--format=chart` (or `--format=figure`) that instructs the LLM to write matplotlib code + execute it via the agent's existing bash/python tool. No embedded sandbox needed — opencode/claude already have tool access.\n\n## Fix\n\n1. Add `chart` (or `figure`) as a supported value for `--format` in clap.\n2. When `--format=chart`, the ask pipeline uses a different prompt template (`ask_chart.md`) that:\n   - Tells the LLM it has python + matplotlib available via its bash tool\n   - Instructs it to write a complete python script that writes a PNG to a specific path\n   - Provides the output path: `outputs/questions/<q-id>/chart.png`\n   - Warns it to use matplotlib's Agg backend (no display needed)\n   - Asks for a brief markdown description to accompany the chart\n3. After the LLM's tool calls finish, kb writes:\n   - `chart.png` (created by the LLM's script)\n   - `answer.md` containing the description + an image reference to chart.png\n   - `metadata.json` with `requested_format: chart`\n\n## Prompt template\n\n```\n# Chart-generation ask\n\nYou are answering the user's question by producing a matplotlib chart.\n\n## Question\n{question}\n\n## Retrieved sources\n{candidate_list}\n\n## Instructions\n\n1. Identify what data in the sources answers the question visually (time series, comparison, distribution, etc.).\n2. Write a complete Python script that:\n   - Imports matplotlib (use `matplotlib.use('Agg')`)\n   - Reproduces the relevant data (you can embed small datasets as literals)\n   - Produces a well-labeled chart with a title, axis labels, legend as needed\n   - Saves to the exact path: {output_path}\n3. Execute the script via your bash tool.\n4. Provide a 2-3 sentence caption describing what the chart shows.\n\nDo not produce any image file other than {output_path}.\n```\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb ask --format=chart 'compare raft election timeout across implementations'` produces:\n  - `outputs/questions/q-<id>/chart.png` — actual PNG\n  - `outputs/questions/q-<id>/answer.md` — caption + image ref\n  - `metadata.json` records requested_format: chart\n- Failed generation (LLM produces no PNG or wrong path) → clean error, no silent fallback.\n- Integration test with a mock LLM adapter that writes a fixture PNG.\n- `just check` passes.\n\n## Requires\n\n- opencode or claude runner with bash tool enabled (default in kb.toml)\n- matplotlib + python available on system\n- `kb doctor` should check for python + matplotlib when chart format is exercised\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't embed a Python interpreter. Reuse the LLM agent's tool.\n- Don't auto-file charts back to wiki; let user --promote if they want.\n- Don't support other chart libraries in v1 (plotly, altair) — just matplotlib.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(ask): --format=chart generates matplotlib via LLM agent (no sandbox needed)"}	blake3:fzdlkuSguBARgoSSUSDU4HYXO99P7PPHHUmmK7oIM6Y
1776713396146078	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthQY		item.create	bn-6y85	{"description":"\nKarpathy's IDE front-end is Obsidian. kb produces an Obsidian-compatible wiki tree but has no editor integration. User has to run `kb ask` in a terminal and Alt-tab back to Obsidian to see the wiki. Close that gap with a native plugin.\n\n## Scope\n\nSeparate repository or `crates/kb-obsidian/` directory containing a TypeScript Obsidian plugin that invokes the `kb` CLI.\n\nNot a Rust workspace member — Obsidian plugins are JS/TS.\n\n## Commands to expose\n\n- **kb: ask** → prompt for question (or use selection), invoke `kb ask --json`, render answer + citations inline as a new/pinned note. Citations link via `[[wiki/sources/...]]` syntax Obsidian recognizes.\n- **kb: chat** → side pane hosting an opencode session (or launch external terminal with `kb chat`).\n- **kb: ingest current note** → `kb ingest <current-file>`.\n- **kb: ingest clipboard URL** → if clipboard has URL, `kb ingest <url>`.\n- **kb: compile** → `kb compile` with progress notice.\n- **kb: promote this question** → if current note is an ask artifact, run `kb review approve`.\n- **kb: inspect this concept** → for current concept page, show frontmatter + backlinks in side pane.\n- **kb: search** → invoke `kb search --json`, populate Obsidian's quick-switcher-like panel with ranked results.\n\n## Settings\n\n- Path to `kb` binary (default: `kb` in PATH)\n- KB root (default: current vault root; auto-detect kb.toml walking up)\n- Model override (passes `--model`)\n\n## Non-goals (v1)\n\n- In-plugin LLM. Always shell out to the `kb` CLI.\n- Custom editor. Use Obsidian's native editor.\n- Visualization rendering. Obsidian's existing markdown/Marp plugins handle that.\n\n## Packaging\n\n- `manifest.json`, `main.ts`, `esbuild.config.mjs` — standard Obsidian plugin layout\n- Target Obsidian 1.4+\n- Distribute via BRAT (community plugin store submission later)\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- Plugin installs in an Obsidian vault containing a KB tree\n- Commands work end-to-end against the installed kb binary\n- Ask command renders citations as clickable wikilinks\n- README + install docs\n- kb-repo either hosts the plugin as a separate crate dir or points at an external repo\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't reimplement kb logic in TS. The plugin is a thin shell over the CLI.\n- Don't require any kb-specific Obsidian settings on the vault.\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(obsidian): Obsidian plugin wrapping kb CLI (ask / ingest / compile / promote)"}	blake3:f4MuhfZayQraciXf8-q3UXwLcVSitZLfxXEJy-hTTl0
1776713413677415	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthgY		item.create	bn-2t3t	{"description":"\nKarpathy's diagram lists a 'Search (Web UI + CLI)' tool. kb has the CLI; add a lightweight web UI.\n\n## Scope\n\n`kb serve` command launching a local HTTP server (bind 127.0.0.1:port by default) that serves:\n\n- Browseable wiki tree (concept pages, source pages, questions)\n- Search box using `kb search` JSON\n- Ask form that runs `kb ask` and streams the answer back\n- Read-only: no editing through the web UI\n\n## Stack\n\n- `axum` for the HTTP server (already a common Rust pick; no new Tokio complexity)\n- Server-rendered HTML with `maud` or `askama` template. No SPA — keep it minimal.\n- Markdown rendering via `pulldown_cmark`. Syntax highlighting via `syntect`.\n- Client-side JS minimal: a single `fetch` for the search/ask endpoints.\n\n## Endpoints\n\n- `GET /` — overview (wiki/index.md rendered)\n- `GET /wiki/*` — render any markdown page\n- `GET /search?q=...` — JSON results\n- `POST /ask` — streams an answer; returns answer artifact id\n- `GET /answer/<q-id>` — rendered answer page\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `kb serve` listens on 127.0.0.1:7890 (configurable), binds only localhost by default\n- Open browser, browse the wiki tree, click through backlinks\n- Search box returns ranked results\n- Ask form produces a grounded answer with citations\n- Graceful exit on Ctrl-C\n- Integration test: smoke-test GET / via `reqwest` in a test\n- `just check` passes\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't expose on 0.0.0.0 by default (security)\n- Don't add authentication (opt-in later if needed)\n- Don't allow edits through the UI — readonly\n- Don't add a database; read-through the on-disk wiki tree each request (small + fast)\n","kind":"task","title":"feat(web): optional web UI for search + ask (browseable wiki)"}	blake3:wd0UyOul9I2F5EVYFBVpjsLVjfRkFiX3nEFgVfmUBh0
1776713710723857	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthwY		item.create	bn-uh3n	{"description":"Project has no top-level README. Add one.","kind":"task","title":"docs: add README.md with quickstart, commands, and roadmap"}	blake3:F2VQu-_fbifBvUvc_RKCwuOK2tLu56Qy5axYVq7FMc4
