1776736093147505	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvQY		item.create	bn-3nvm	{"description":"bn-3dkw's image resolver lives in crates/kb-query/src/images.rs and walks `root.join(candidate.id)` — i.e. the wiki page the retrieval planner picked. For `wiki/sources/src-X.md` candidates, that's the LLM-generated SUMMARY, which does not carry the original `![](assets/foo.png)` image references (the raw image ref is in normalized/src-X/source.md only). Result on real queries: plan_mentions_images() returns false, no -f flag is added to opencode's command, no data URI is added to Claude's prompt. The feature is effectively dead code in production (bn-3dkw's tests only prove the hot path by hand-crafting a RetrievalPlan whose candidate body contains an image ref).\n\nRepro (pass-15):\n- corpus has normalized/src-1oz/source.md referencing ![](assets/hex-arch.png)\n- kb ask 'What colors appear in the diagram embedded in the hexagonal architecture source?'\n- retrieval candidates: wiki/sources/src-1oz.md (summary only, no image ref) + wiki/concepts/*.md\n- retrieval_plan.json has no image_paths, no attachments section\n- opencode still got the colors right, but only by using its autonomous bash+read tools — NOT via bn-3dkw's attachment plumbing. That's opencode-specific. The Claude fallback path would silently produce a wrong answer.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn crates/kb-query/src/images.rs, extend resolve_candidate_image_paths AND plan_mentions_images:\n\nWhen a candidate.id matches the pattern wiki/sources/src-<id>.md:\n1. ALSO scan normalized/<id>/source.md for image refs.\n2. Resolve refs relative to normalized/<id>/ (so `assets/hex-arch.png` lands at normalized/<id>/assets/hex-arch.png).\n3. Dedupe with the existing seen set.\n4. Respect MAX_IMAGES_PER_QUERY cap (5).\n\nConcept candidates (wiki/concepts/*.md) don't need this — concept bodies don't include image refs. But if a concept cites a source with an image, that's picked up when the source itself is also a candidate.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- kb ask on a corpus where the only image ref lives in normalized/src-X/source.md (summary drops it) produces a retrieval_plan whose image resolution returns that image.\n- Integration test: seed normalized/src-X/source.md with an image ref + wiki/sources/src-X.md summary without the ref; assert resolve_candidate_image_paths returns the image.\n- Existing tests (image ref IS in the candidate body directly) continue to pass.\n- MAX cap still honored.\n- just check passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't walk the full normalized/ tree — only the sources matched by the candidate id prefix.\n- Don't duplicate path resolution logic; reuse resolve_image_ref.\n- Don't change the public API of the two exported functions; add the normalized-source scan internally.","kind":"task","title":"fix(ask): multimodal resolver scans wiki summaries (which drop image refs); attachments never fire on real queries"}	blake3:H0okUg7mj8_aD4aVxNXHuMBCOHAWlEKPGj_PdO5dRJc
1776736103692576	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvgY		item.create	bn-1hyu	{"description":"The GET|POST /ask endpoint in crates/kb-web/src/server.rs reads the artifact file (outputs/questions/<q>/answer.md) and returns the whole file contents as the 'answer' JSON field. For question_answer artifacts written by kb ask, the file opens with a YAML frontmatter block (---\\nid: art-...\\ngenerated_at:...\\nsource_document_ids:\\n...\\n---\\n\\n<actual body>) — the whole block is included in the response.\n\nRepro: GET http://127.0.0.1:<port>/ask?q=... returns {\"answer\":\"---\\nid: art-1yc\\ngenerated_at:...\\n---\\n\\n# Memo: ...\"}.\n\nRelated to bn-125l's frontmatter strip for wiki pages, but that helper ships in crates/kb-web/src/markdown.rs::strip_frontmatter (or wherever the worker landed it) — the /ask handler doesn't apply it.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn the /ask handler in crates/kb-web/src/server.rs: after reading the artifact file, run it through the frontmatter-stripper helper before returning. Same function bn-125l added for /wiki/*.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- POST /ask with a simple query returns an 'answer' field whose text does NOT contain 'id: art-', 'generated_at:', 'source_document_ids:', or a leading '---' delimiter.\n- The actual answer body (# Memo / Overview / etc.) is present unchanged.\n- Integration test in crates/kb-web/tests/smoke.rs — seed a fixture answer.md with frontmatter, hit /ask with a stubbed LLM or pre-written artifact, assert frontmatter keys absent.\n- just check passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't re-parse the artifact file as YAML.\n- Don't remove content from the on-disk artifact.\n- Don't strip other code fences or headers — only the leading YAML frontmatter block.","kind":"task","title":"fix(web): /ask JSON answer field includes YAML frontmatter verbatim"}	blake3:JNtjtIlAkXaV8B2QeNJZ9B0YPHY7vCEajdkwddjyjC8
1776736120249809	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvwY		item.create	bn-31uk	{"description":"kb ask --format=chart saves an answer.md whose body begins with the LLM's tool-call narration before the real caption. Example body (pass-15 corpus):\n\n  Checking the output location, then I'll write and run a minimal matplotlib script to generate the PNG.\n  Writing the chart script now, then I'll execute it and verify the PNG was created.\n  The chart shows a simple horizontal comparison with two categories...\n\nThe first two lines are opencode streaming the LLM's inline tool-call commentary — they're not part of the answer. The actual caption starts at 'The chart shows...'.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs (run_ask or the chart-specific post-processing) and/or crates/kb-llm/src/opencode.rs: when --format=chart, the returned answer-body should be sanitized.\n\nOptions (pick the simplest that works):\n1. Keep only the content from the first '# ' heading onward, if one is present. (Chart ask_chart.md prompt asks for a caption — models often emit a header.)\n2. Strip any line preceding the last blank-line-separated block that contains no matplotlib-script-tool-call narration. Risky — too heuristic.\n3. Explicitly parse opencode's output shape so only the 'final message' portion lands in answer.md, not the streamed assistant tool-use interleaving.\n\nRecommend option 3 if the opencode output format exposes a clean 'final_message' split; otherwise option 1.\n\nIf option 1: implement a narrow strip_tool_narration(text: &str) -> &str that walks lines and returns the slice from the last paragraph that doesn't match common narration prefixes (\"I'll\", \"Let me\", \"I'm\", \"Now I'll\", \"Writing\", \"Running\", \"Checking\"), OR the slice from a '# ' heading. Apply only in the chart code path.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- ask --format=chart output's answer.md does NOT begin with narration like 'Checking the output location' or 'Writing the chart script'.\n- The caption content (description of what the chart shows) is preserved intact.\n- The image ref ![chart](chart.png) is preserved.\n- Frontmatter at the top is still correct.\n- Markdown-format ask (default) is unaffected.\n- Integration test: fake opencode that emits a script-tool-narration preamble + a '# Chart' header + caption; assert answer.md starts with the header.\n- just check passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't strip narration from non-chart asks (markdown / json default).\n- Don't rely on regex-matching the exact narration phrases the LLM emits today — that's fragile.\n- Don't remove the frontmatter.","kind":"task","title":"fix(ask): chart format answer.md leaks LLM tool-call narration"}	blake3:y-zNusQ1930OUV-kgzsN_JQNsd0rMpUijM0AauAsEZY
1776736131569598	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtwAY		item.create	bn-1hqh	{"description":"When the LLM fails to produce chart.png at the expected path (matplotlib missing, script error, LLM refused, etc.), kb ask --format=chart errors with 'LLM did not produce chart at expected path /tmp/.../chart.png' and the outputs/questions/<q-id>/ directory is never created. Debugging is blind — the user doesn't see what the LLM tried, what script it ran, or what output it produced.\n\nRepro: uninstall matplotlib, kb ask --format=chart 'make a bar chart' — error only, no q-id dir.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs (run_ask chart path) and/or wherever the chart post-run validation fires:\n\n1. Create outputs/questions/<q-id>/ BEFORE calling the LLM (as is standard for md/json formats).\n2. On chart failure, still write:\n   - answer.md with the LLM's raw returned text (whatever it produced) in a body like: '## Chart generation failed\\n\\nReason: <error>\\n\\n## LLM output\\n\\n<raw output>'.\n   - metadata.json with requested_format: chart, success: false, error field.\n3. Exit non-zero with a clear message pointing at the artifact dir: '--format chart failed: expected <path>/chart.png was not produced. See <path>/answer.md for LLM output.'\n\nKeep behavior when the LLM SUCCEEDS unchanged (chart.png + answer.md + metadata.json as today).\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- Uninstalling matplotlib + kb ask --format=chart produces outputs/questions/<q-id>/answer.md with the LLM's attempted script or explanation.\n- Metadata.json has success: false.\n- Error message references the artifact dir so the user knows where to look.\n- Exit code is non-zero on failure.\n- Successful chart runs (matplotlib installed) unchanged.\n- Integration test: mock LLM that returns prose but no PNG → assert answer.md exists with raw output; metadata.json exists with success: false.\n- just check passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't silently fall back to markdown format — the user asked for a chart.\n- Don't delete the outputs dir on failure — keep artifacts for diagnosis.\n- Don't suppress the raw LLM output; the whole point is to preserve it.","kind":"task","title":"fix(ask): --format=chart failure leaves no artifacts for diagnosis"}	blake3:wwFt5gpGiShEmqqREVQxhu4U3ux5iIq-jlbgU_yc1HY
