1777164115626388	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt-wY		item.create	bn-1hme	{"description":"After bn-3qsj shipped hybrid retrieval, RetrievalCandidate gained additive semantic_score/semantic_rank/lexical_rank fields. But the top-level `score` per candidate still carries the lexical raw score (e.g. 18, 12) rather than the RRF-fused score. Order matches the fused ranking; the displayed number doesn't.\n\nConfirmed on ~/chief/consulting/kb/outputs/questions/q-1f7-.../retrieval_plan.json:\n\n  agentic-systems-engineering.md  score=18  lex_rank=1  sem_rank=11  sem_score=0.673\n  automated-code-review-swarm.md  score=12  lex_rank=2  sem_rank=None\n  agentic-engineering-operating-model.md  score=9  lex_rank=3  sem_rank=16\n\nThe list is in RRF-correct order, but score=18 vs score=12 is a lexical-side artifact, not the fused score that placed them.\n\n# Fix\n\nIn crates/kb-query/src/hybrid.rs (where HybridResult is materialized into RetrievalCandidate): set RetrievalCandidate.score to the RRF-fused score that drove ordering. The bn-3qsj per-candidate `reasons` already surface 'lexical match (rank N, score X)' separately, so no information is lost.\n\nIf a downstream consumer reads candidate.score and expects 'token-overlap heuristic in [0, 30]ish', they'll see [0, 0.05]ish RRF values instead — but the field's documented semantics ('relevance score, higher is better') still hold. No JSON shape change.\n\n# Acceptance\n\n- retrieval_plan.json's per-candidate score reflects the fused RRF score (small float in [0, ~0.05]) when semantic is enabled.\n- When KB_SEMANTIC=0 or hash-embed yields no semantic ranks, score falls back to lexical-side scoring (or to a 1/(rrf_k + lex_rank) fused-with-empty-semantic value — pick one and document).\n- Order of candidates in the plan unchanged from before (the fix is cosmetic — only the score number changes).\n- kb search human output still shows 'score: 0.0325' style fused values (already correct today).\n- just check passes.\n\n# Don't\n\n- Don't break the JSON shape (additive optional fields stay; only the value of `score` changes).\n- Don't drop lexical_score / semantic_score / lexical_rank / semantic_rank — those carry the per-tier contributions for explanation.","kind":"task","title":"fix(query): retrieval_plan.json candidate score is lexical-native, not fused"}	blake3:tmCK8bKNztdXtYzFENOnBZWPHH9oe5Gy2GZmPBJv9D4
1777164120285523	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_AY		item.move	bn-1hme	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:1pYO-i4OMFmy8MPScgTl6rIBZQaHWgCRaISCLPgMGAw
1777164120304364	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_QY		item.assign	bn-1hme	{"action":"assign","agent":"kb-dev"}	blake3:Wpp8JJEEesXULFuNPFzELlVWZap6dZ1j7RcQ1DGwABs
1777164403173961	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_gY		item.move	bn-1hme	{"state":"done"}	blake3:s-L3iovDnc7GpJBydxSXLdf7Pps_ma9EqknDFNJNWGM
1777250463174532	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt_wY		item.create	bn-3sco	{"description":"**Why.** Without measurement, every retrieval change (MiniLM, rerank, chunking) is vibes. Eval harness is the foundation that lets us land #B/#C/#D/#N with confidence.\n\n**What.** New crate kb-eval (or kb-cli subcommand `kb eval run`).\n\n- `evals/golden.toml` holds queries with `expected_sources` / `expected_concepts`.\n- For each query: run `plan_retrieval_hybrid` (no LLM call), capture top-K candidate IDs+ranks.\n- Score: P@5, P@10, MRR, nDCG@10 against expected set.\n- Output `evals/results/<timestamp>.json` + markdown summary.\n- `--baseline <name>` diffs against a saved run; `--save-as <name>` snapshots.\n- Pin queries to a corpus snapshot hash so corpus drift doesn't silently invalidate scores.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- `kb eval run` produces a JSON+md report.\n- Baseline diff shows per-query and aggregate deltas.\n- Adding/removing queries and re-running works.\n- README in evals/ explains how to add new golden queries.\n\n**Risks.** Authoring effort; golden set drifts. Mitigated by corpus-hash pinning and treating it as a living artifact.\n\nConfidence: 90%.","kind":"task","title":"eval: golden Q/A harness with P@K / nDCG scoring"}	blake3:n8tTfvSN-tXsXKc2eL3_P371XkMXcRGJPvd3Vk38Bp0
1777250471876879	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgAc		item.create	bn-1rww	{"description":"**Why.** Hash n-gram embeddings have no semantic meaning. MiniLM closes the lexical/semantic gap and is the single biggest expected quality jump from current state.\n\n**What.** New `MiniLmBackend` implementing existing `EmbeddingBackend` trait.\n\n- Cargo feature `semantic-ort` (off by default to avoid mandatory ort linking).\n- Use `ort` crate + `tokenizers` crate; load all-MiniLM-L6-v2 ONNX (~90MB).\n- Mean-pool token outputs; L2-normalize; dim = 384.\n- `kb.toml`:\n  ```toml\n  [semantic]\n  backend = \"minilm\"   # or \"hash\" (current default)\n  model_path = \"~/.kb/models/all-MiniLM-L6-v2.onnx\"\n  ```\n- Backend ID change in `semantic_meta` triggers full re-embed (already wired).\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- `cargo build --features semantic-ort` succeeds.\n- `kb compile` with `backend = \"minilm\"` produces 384-dim embeddings.\n- Eval harness (bone bn-eval-harness) shows ≥+15% nDCG@10 over hash-embed baseline on golden set.\n- Falls back gracefully (clear error) when model file missing.\n\n**Risks.** Model download UX; ort linking finicky on some machines (off-by-default feature mitigates). Cold-start latency.\n\n**Depends on.** Eval harness bone (to measure improvement).\n\nConfidence: 80%.","kind":"task","title":"semantic: ONNX MiniLM-L6-v2 embedding backend (replaces hash-embed)"}	blake3:9AiEqU3GVEYq4LyJbbS_YY-lqWIrqhtLakAmu9z8eYg
1777250481631779	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgQc		item.create	bn-3rzz	{"description":"**Why.** Long sources currently embed as one blob — a 5000-token source about many topics averages out and matches nothing well. Per-section embeddings dramatically improve precision.\n\n**What.** Chunk and embed at section granularity.\n\n**Chunking rule.**\n- Split each source by H2 (`##`); if chunk > 800 tokens, split by H3 then by paragraph.\n- Min chunk 100 tokens (merge upward).\n- Track heading text per chunk for snippet UX.\n\n**Schema (embeddings.db).**\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE chunk_embeddings (\n    chunk_id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,         -- \"<source_id>#<idx>\"\n    source_id TEXT NOT NULL,\n    chunk_idx INTEGER NOT NULL,\n    heading TEXT,\n    content_hash TEXT NOT NULL,\n    embedding BLOB NOT NULL\n);\nCREATE INDEX idx_chunk_source ON chunk_embeddings(source_id);\n```\n\n**Retrieval.** Semantic tier returns chunks; aggregate to sources by max-chunk-score; pass best chunk (not full source) into the LLM context to save tokens.\n\n**Citation surface.** `[src-id#section-name]` resolves to chunk; renderers fall back to `[src-id]` if no anchor.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Long source produces multiple chunks; each independently retrievable.\n- Eval harness shows nDCG@10 improvement vs whole-document embedding.\n- Citations render correctly for both chunk-anchored and bare forms.\n\n**Risks.** Chunk-boundary semantics (splitting mid-thought). Mitigated by H2/H3 hierarchy + paragraph-aware fallback.\n\n**Depends on.** Eval harness.\n\nConfidence: 85%.","kind":"task","title":"semantic: per-chunk (section) embeddings"}	blake3:u0_2pd2zTbxuyJEjiGcvYPZ89o6Cg7Sk5bxt1Caa1yg
1777250490250550	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtggc		item.create	bn-1cp2	{"description":"**Why.** Bi-encoder retrieval (MiniLM) is fast but imprecise. Cross-encoder reads (query, candidate) jointly and is dramatically better at discrimination — the standard 2-stage IR pattern.\n\n**What.** After hybrid RRF returns top-K (K=30), apply ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2 cross-encoder; keep top-N (default 8).\n\n- Module: `kb-query/src/semantic/rerank.rs`. Reuses `ort` crate from MiniLM bone.\n- API:\n  ```rust\n  pub struct CrossEncoder { /* ort session */ }\n  impl CrossEncoder {\n      pub fn score(&self, query: &str, candidate: &str) -> f32;\n      pub fn rerank(&self, query: &str, candidates: &mut [&mut RetrievalCandidate]);\n  }\n  ```\n- Hook into `plan_retrieval_hybrid` after RRF sort, before truncation.\n\n**Config (kb.toml).**\n```toml\n[semantic.rerank]\nenabled = true\ntop_k = 30\nkeep = 8\n```\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Rerank can be toggled on/off via config.\n- Eval harness shows ≥+10% MRR on golden set with rerank on, MiniLM baseline.\n- Rerank latency for K=30 is < 300ms on CPU.\n\n**Risks.** Latency budget on large K (capped). Adds a second model artifact.\n\n**Depends on.** ONNX MiniLM bone (shares ort plumbing) + eval harness.\n\nConfidence: 80%.","kind":"task","title":"semantic: cross-encoder reranker on top-K hybrid results"}	blake3:lJOPboI_m9Al6nK9bjvSQGFEZiEi3ibJOoCVr2G4LV0
1777250503014785	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgwc		item.create	bn-2qda	{"description":"**Why.** Screenshots of diagrams, charts, and architecture pictures contribute zero to retrieval today — they have no text. This is the original use case from the conversation that kicked off semantic retrieval. Captions make images first-class searchable through the existing pipeline (no new infra).\n\n**What.** During `kb compile`, caption every image whose alt-text is empty/generic.\n\n**Pipeline.**\n1. New module `kb-compile/src/captions.rs`.\n2. Walk each source's markdown for `![alt](path)` refs.\n3. If `alt` is empty / equals \"image\" / equals filename stem, mark for captioning.\n4. Compute image content hash (sha256 of bytes); look up `.kb/cache/captions/<hash>.txt`.\n5. On miss: invoke configured vision runner (default: claude-haiku via Claude Code) with a prompt like:\n   > \"Describe this image in 2-3 sentences for a knowledge base. Focus on what is depicted, any text, diagrams, charts, or relationships shown. Plain prose, no markdown.\"\n6. Persist caption to cache.\n7. Inject into compiled wiki page next to the image:\n   ```markdown\n   ![original alt](path)\n   <!-- kb:caption -->\n   <caption text>\n   <!-- /kb:caption -->\n   ```\n8. Caption text is part of indexed content (lexical + embedding pipelines see it transparently).\n\n**Config (kb.toml).**\n```toml\n[compile.captions]\nenabled = true\nrunner = \"claude\"\nmodel = \"claude-haiku-4-5\"\nallow_paths = [\"wiki/\", \"sources/\"]   # privacy guard\n```\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Source with bare `![](diagram.png)` produces a kb:caption block after compile.\n- Re-running compile is no-op (content-hash cache hit).\n- Caption text appears as snippet hits in `kb search`.\n- Eval golden query that targets a screenshot retrieves the source.\n\n**Risks.** LLM cost (mitigated by per-image hash cache — pay once per image forever). Quality variance. Sensitive images (mitigated by `allow_paths`).\n\nConfidence: 85%.","kind":"task","title":"ingest: vision-LLM auto-captions for undescribed images"}	blake3:kSucICKCojnx8F6EPACrOtmAP6A8iKkJDc5uNwiZHLk
1777250512472862	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthAc		item.create	bn-3ij3	{"description":"**Why.** A citation `[src-some-200-page-pdf]` is uncheckable. With page numbers, a reader (or future verification pass) can land on the right place and trust the answer.\n\n**What.** Preserve page numbers from PDFs through ingestion → markdown → chunking → citations.\n\n**Approach (single bet).** Use `pdftotext -layout -f N -l N` page-by-page (already on system as poppler-utils) to extract per-page text; concatenate with HTML-comment markers:\n```markdown\n<!-- kb:page 1 -->\n... page 1 text ...\n<!-- kb:page 2 -->\n... page 2 text ...\n```\n\n**Pipeline.**\n1. Detect `.pdf` source → call new `pdf_page_extract` instead of markitdown.\n2. Inject `<!-- kb:page N -->` markers between pages.\n3. Chunking respects page boundaries (chunk never spans pages unless page is too small).\n4. Each chunk gets a `page_range` field.\n5. Citation renderer: `[src-id p.7]` or `[src-id pp.7-9]`.\n6. New lint: citation `[src-id p.N]` is valid iff `kb:page N` marker exists in `src-id`.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- PDF source compiled with markers; chunk metadata includes page_range.\n- `kb ask` answers citing PDFs render with page numbers.\n- Lint catches stale page references.\n\n**Risks.** pdftotext output quality on complex layouts (mitigated: this is the same backbone markitdown uses for many PDFs anyway). Falls back to current markitdown path if pdftotext absent.\n\nConfidence: 75%.","kind":"task","title":"ingest: PDF page-aware citations"}	blake3:LW41mCtOJ6In9LA-4SRcLiuhKRxZCidQDCZzuIlJIH4
1777250523561519	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthQc		item.create	bn-166d	{"description":"**Why.** \"Required citations\" lints presence of citations. They don't catch fabricated quotes — a common LLM failure mode. Verification closes that gap.\n\n**What.** Post-process `kb ask` answers AND compiled concept pages: every quoted span adjacent to a citation must exist in the cited source.\n\n**Algorithm.**\n1. Parse text for patterns:\n   - `\"<quoted text>\" \\[(src-id)\\]`\n   - `\\[(src-id)\\] \"<quoted text>\"`\n   - `\"<quoted text>\" \\(src-id\\)`\n2. Normalize: collapse whitespace, lowercase, drop markdown emphasis.\n3. For each (quote, src-id): check `quote ⊂ normalized(source.content)`. Allow ≤1 char per 100 fuzz via Levenshtein bounded distance.\n4. Emit `unverified-quote` warning per failure.\n\n**Surface.**\n- `kb ask` answer footer: `verified: 4/5 quotes found in sources` and lists failures.\n- `kb lint`: configurable level (warn/error) for `unverified-quote` in compiled concept pages.\n\n**Config.**\n```toml\n[lint.citation_verification]\nenabled = true\nlevel = \"warn\"\nfuzz_per_100_chars = 1\n```\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Hand-crafted concept page with a fabricated quote raises lint.\n- `kb ask` footer accurately counts verified vs unverified quotes.\n- Quotes that span paragraph breaks/whitespace differences still verify (normalization works).\n\n**Risks.** Punctuation edge cases (smart quotes, em-dash). Quotes spanning chunk boundaries when source was rewritten by ingestion. Mitigated by warn-not-error default and span normalization.\n\nConfidence: 70%.","kind":"task","title":"trust: citation verification — verify quoted spans exist in cited sources"}	blake3:wo71nH_NR6DdcADAK-mv1Py2cD3TO1mjaOQAVawCECs
1777250531845031	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthgc		item.create	bn-2n0g	{"description":"**Why.** Anything that speaks MCP (Claude Code, Claude Desktop, Cursor, Cline) gets first-class kb access. Massive leverage for low effort — just wraps existing search/ask code paths.\n\n**What.** New crate `kb-mcp` exposing tools over MCP stdio.\n\n**Tools.**\n- `kb_search(query: string, limit: int = 10) -> [{ id, title, score, snippet }]`\n- `kb_ask(question: string, sources?: string[]) -> { answer, citations: [src-id] }`\n- `kb_get_source(id: string, section?: string) -> { id, title, body_markdown }`\n- `kb_list_concepts(prefix?: string) -> [{ slug, summary }]`\n\n**Subcommand.** `kb mcp` (stdio transport).\n\n**Wiring.** README documents adding to `~/.claude/mcp_servers.json`:\n```json\n{ \"kb\": { \"command\": \"kb\", \"args\": [\"mcp\"] } }\n```\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- `kb mcp` starts an MCP stdio server.\n- All four tools callable from Claude Desktop/Code with valid JSON results.\n- Search/ask routes through the same code paths as the CLI (no divergence).\n- README has a working setup example.\n\n**Risks.** Need to keep MCP schema stable as kb internals change. Cancellation/timeout semantics — runner trait already handles these; surface them through MCP.\n\nConfidence: 90%.","kind":"task","title":"surface: MCP server exposing kb_search / kb_ask / kb_get_source"}	blake3:eeYFHvPHo6nsgKFgto5XqzjiHNiNDroQt4J6mHIruvc
1777250541505108	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthwc		item.create	bn-2n7l	{"description":"**Why.** Compile is full-rebuild today. As the corpus grows past a few dozen sources, this gets painful — especially compounded by vision-captioning and ML embedding bones, which are expensive.\n\n**What.** Per-source dependency graph + content hash; skip stages whose inputs haven't changed.\n\n**State (`.kb/state/compile.db`).**\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE source_state (\n    source_id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n    raw_path TEXT,\n    raw_hash TEXT,           -- of raw input file\n    extracted_hash TEXT,     -- of markitdown output\n    body_hash TEXT,          -- of post-processed body\n    last_compiled_at_millis INTEGER\n);\nCREATE TABLE concept_state (\n    concept_slug TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n    body_hash TEXT,\n    cited_sources_json TEXT,\n    last_compiled_at_millis INTEGER\n);\n```\n\n**Stages.** Already idempotent: embedding (by content_hash), captions (by image hash). Add: markitdown extraction (raw_hash), lint passes (body_hash), concept page rendering (cited_sources_json hash).\n\n**Escape hatch.** `kb compile --force` ignores cache.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Editing one source recompiles only that source + concepts that cite it.\n- `kb compile` with no changes is sub-second on a 100-source corpus.\n- `--force` reproduces full-rebuild output bit-for-bit.\n\n**Risks.** Stale-cache bugs are classic. Mitigation: `--force` + suggested CI weekly full rebuild + clear cache-version field bumped on stage logic changes.\n\nConfidence: 75%.","kind":"task","title":"compile: incremental compile (skip unchanged stages, not just embeddings)"}	blake3:C6T5v6t8NR8AuvOQC_k8x9cSh45nId0TeRZOpYw1WGM
1777250551249766	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtiAc		item.create	bn-o6wv	{"description":"**Why.** Single-shot ask is great for lookup but bad for understanding. Drill-down — follow-up questions that build on prior turns — is the natural mode for KB use.\n\n**What.** Multi-turn ask with retrieval refresh per turn.\n\n**State (`.kb/sessions/<id>.json`).**\n```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"s-1abc\",\n  \"turns\": [\n    {\"role\": \"user\", \"text\": \"...\", \"retrieved_ids\": [\"...\"]},\n    {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"text\": \"...\", \"citations\": [\"...\"]}\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n**Per-turn flow.**\n1. If multi-turn: build a query-rewrite prompt — condense session + new turn → standalone query.\n2. Run hybrid retrieval against rewritten query (or raw question on turn 1).\n3. Build prompt: prior turns (truncated to budget) + retrieved chunks + new question.\n4. Append user+assistant turns to session file.\n\n**CLI.**\n- `kb ask --session work-on-x \"question\"` — start or continue.\n- `kb session list` — list sessions with first question + last activity.\n- `kb session show <id>` — print turns.\n- `kb session delete <id>`.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Two-turn session where turn 2 depends on turn 1's answer (e.g. \"what about X?\" → \"and how does that compare to Y?\") retrieves correctly.\n- Sessions persist across CLI invocations.\n- Token budget management drops oldest turns gracefully.\n\n**Risks.** Token-budget management with growing history (drop oldest first). Query rewriting can drift (only kicks in turn 2+).\n\nConfidence: 75%.","kind":"task","title":"ux: conversational kb ask --session <id> with multi-turn history"}	blake3:S5jBz1tIp-LQiXyKrvNGWVAlHZMM6zqM4kD7V1FnjEs
1777250562576917	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtiQc		item.create	bn-13zx	{"description":"**Why.** Manually authoring concepts doesn't scale. Suggestions are low-stakes (user gates acceptance), and they make the KB grow with usage rather than requiring proactive curation.\n\n**What.** During compile, suggest new concepts derived from sources.\n\n**Pipeline.**\n1. Run keyphrase extraction (RAKE or YAKE — pure-Rust crates exist) per source body.\n2. Aggregate: for each candidate keyphrase, score by `frequency × novelty_vs_existing_concepts`.\n3. For top-N candidates, ask LLM:\n   > \"Is this a useful KB concept? If yes, give a slug, a 1-line summary, and the 3 most relevant source IDs from this list: [...].\"\n4. Write accepted-by-LLM suggestions to `.kb/suggestions/concepts.toml`:\n   ```toml\n   [[concept]]\n   slug = \"agentic-engineering-operating-model\"\n   summary = \"...\"\n   sources = [\"src-...\", \"src-...\"]\n   ```\n5. `kb concept accept <slug>` materializes a concept stub at `wiki/concepts/<slug>.md`; user fills in.\n6. `kb concept list-suggestions` / `kb concept reject <slug>`.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Compile with suggestion enabled produces a list of candidate concepts.\n- Accepting a candidate creates a concept stub.\n- Re-running compile doesn't re-suggest already-accepted/rejected slugs.\n\n**Risks.** NER quality unknown on this corpus; LLM cost; concept-spam if accept threshold lax. Lower confidence — iterative tuning.\n\n**Depends on.** Loosely on chunk-embeddings (better signal for novelty scoring).\n\nConfidence: 65%.","kind":"task","title":"wiki: concept auto-extraction (suggested, not authored)"}	blake3:DV8_hiNR5BACPBblTioXG3_HC9sSqdmWcDl7sU3HIQk
1777250571603939	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtigc		item.create	bn-asr2	{"description":"**Why.** Wikis rot. Three rot modes: unused content (orphan), broken pointers (stale), and content-drift away from cited spans (drift). All three are detectable by pure structural checks.\n\n**What.** Three new lints in kb-lint.\n\n**1. Orphan source.** Source not cited by any concept and not linked to from any other source ⇒ warning. Suggests \"consider linking from a concept or removing\".\n\n**2. Stale citation.** Concept (or source) references `[src-xyz]` where src-xyz doesn't exist ⇒ error.\n\n**3. Drift.** Concept body contains `\"<quoted span>\" [src-xyz]` but the span no longer appears verbatim in src-xyz body ⇒ warning. (Shares span-matching helper with citation-verification bone.)\n\n**Config (kb.toml).**\n```toml\n[lint.orphans]\nenabled = true\nlevel = \"warn\"\nexempt_globs = []   # opt-out for known-archival sources\n\n[lint.stale_citations]\nenabled = true\nlevel = \"error\"\n\n[lint.drift]\nenabled = true\nlevel = \"warn\"\n```\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Adding a source nobody cites ⇒ orphan warning.\n- Editing a source to break a quoted citation ⇒ drift warning.\n- Renaming a source-id without updating concepts ⇒ stale citation error.\n- All three lints respect exempt globs / disabled flag.\n\n**Risks.** Drift overlaps with citation-verification — share the span-match helper to avoid divergence.\n\nConfidence: 90%.","kind":"task","title":"lint: orphan source + stale citation + drift checks"}	blake3:ukEH3a5wProMHFc96lWvCBwcNBNSCtZilsB06SAviMQ
1777250581621070	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtiwc		item.create	bn-2hyr	{"description":"**Why.** Scan-only PDFs (photos of pages, OCR'd legal docs, old papers) currently produce empty text from markitdown. They become silent black holes — present in the filesystem, invisible to retrieval.\n\n**What.** When markitdown returns empty/whitespace-only output for a PDF, fall back to OCR via tesseract.\n\n**Detection.** `extracted.trim().is_empty()` or `len < 100 chars && pdf_has_images`.\n\n**Pipeline.**\n1. Rasterize each page: `pdftoppm -r 300 in.pdf out` → PNG per page.\n2. OCR each: `tesseract out-N.png - -l eng`.\n3. Concatenate with page markers (combines naturally with PDF page-citations bone):\n   ```\n   <!-- kb:page 1 -->\n   ... ocr text ...\n   <!-- kb:page 2 -->\n   ...\n   ```\n4. Cache aggressively: per-page hash → text in `.kb/cache/ocr/<hash>.txt`.\n\n**Config.**\n```toml\n[ingest.ocr]\nenabled = true\ncommand = \"tesseract\"\nlanguage = \"eng\"\nmin_chars_threshold = 100\n```\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Scan-only PDF added to corpus produces non-empty markdown after compile.\n- Re-compile is no-op (cache hit).\n- Off-by-default opt-in via config; works without OCR if disabled or tesseract missing.\n\n**Risks.** OCR is slow and noisy. Mitigation: opt-in, aggressive page-hash cache, log warning on quality heuristics.\n\n**Depends on.** Loosely on PDF-page-citations bone (shares the page-marker format).\n\nConfidence: 70%.","kind":"task","title":"ingest: OCR fallback for scan-only PDFs"}	blake3:yeP1BucaSe5I0cI3gzSKnBemflvEdS9aA_BUE-xDChc
1777250593077599	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjAc		item.create	bn-32od	{"description":"**Why.** A source cited by multiple concepts the query already matched is structurally more relevant — a signal that lexical + semantic miss. This is the bones pattern that worked in the reference implementation we cloned earlier.\n\n**What.** Build a citation graph; add a third RRF tier based on personalized PageRank from the query's seed set.\n\n**Storage (`.kb/state/graph.db`).**\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE edges (\n  src_id TEXT NOT NULL,\n  dst_id TEXT NOT NULL,\n  edge_type TEXT NOT NULL,       -- \"cites\" | \"links\"\n  PRIMARY KEY (src_id, dst_id, edge_type)\n);\nCREATE INDEX idx_edge_src ON edges(src_id);\nCREATE INDEX idx_edge_dst ON edges(dst_id);\n```\n\n**Build.** During compile, walk concept bodies and source bodies; extract `[src-id]` references and concept→concept links. Persist edges.\n\n**Use in retrieval.**\n1. Run hybrid (lex + sem + RRF) → top-K seeds.\n2. Personalized PageRank with restart on seed set, restricted to MAX_STRUCTURAL_SEEDS=16 / MAX_STRUCTURAL_CANDIDATES=128 (matches bones constants).\n3. Convert structural rank to score; fuse into existing RRF as a third term.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Graph rebuild incremental (responds to incremental compile).\n- Hybrid retrieval has lex_rank, sem_rank, struct_rank visible in `--dry-run`.\n- Eval harness shows ≥+5% MRR vs lex+sem-only on golden queries that involve well-connected sources.\n\n**Risks.** Complexity. Defer until MiniLM/rerank/chunking land and eval shows residual misses live in the structural-signal gap.\n\n**Depends on.** Eval harness; benefits from chunk embeddings.\n\nConfidence: 75%.","kind":"task","title":"semantic: citation graph + structural rank signal in hybrid retrieval"}	blake3:vSS2Xt1OZa5L2QKL7a2rKkdq5hLDP_6WZ4yOGeM5IbE
1777251762316993	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjQc		item.comment	bn-2n0g	{"body":"Rejected: user prefers agent-friendly --help and CLI guidance over an MCP surface. CLI is already the integration point; making --help and error messages discoverable for agents covers the same need without a second protocol to keep stable."}	blake3:ERFF4Eyn9GIrxKbwpY5nTc6fibIT8oKuDrGLL5Of4F4
1777251762341999	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjgc		item.move	bn-2n0g	{"state":"done"}	blake3:6JjoY4zj-oE8NOwrmInevG02MFqBL4mJYne8lgrz3bY
1777314079498982	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtjwc		item.create	bn-3hfw	{"description":"**Why.** Meeting recordings (Zoom .m4a/.mp4) are a major un-indexed corpus. Transcribed + diarized, they become first-class searchable sources alongside typed meeting notes. User has two LiveRamp recordings staged (~/chief/consulting/ops/.../USB Team Intro/, Delta Team Intro/) ready to validate against.\n\nThis bone is the **prototype phase**: a Python sidecar tool that produces kb-ready markdown. Phase 2 (separate bone, blocked by this) reimplements in Rust for single-binary shipping.\n\n**Tooling.** WhisperX = faster-whisper (CTranslate2) for ASR + pyannote-3.1 for diarization + word-level alignment between them. Quality default is whisper-large-v3 since user has a 3090.\n\n**Scope.**\n1. Standalone Python tool `tools/audio-transcribe/` (its own venv via `uv`).\n2. Input: audio path (`.m4a/.mp3/.wav`, or `.mp4` with audio extracted via ffmpeg).\n3. Output: kb-source markdown to stdout or `--out <path>`.\n4. Caches transcript by audio content-hash in `~/.kb/cache/transcripts/<hash>.md` so reruns are no-op.\n5. Speakers labeled anonymously (`SPEAKER_00`, `SPEAKER_01`, …); `--aliases <toml>` accepts a per-meeting rename map for v1+.\n\n**Output format (locked here so phase 2 can match it byte-for-byte).**\n\n```markdown\n---\ntype: source\ntitle: 2026-04-07 LiveRamp USB Team Intro Transcript\nrecording_date: 2026-04-07\naudio_file: GMT20260407-143343_Recording.m4a\nduration_seconds: 3612\nspeakers_detected: 3\nasr_model: whisper-large-v3\ndiarization_model: pyannote/speaker-diarization-3.1\nlanguage: en\n---\n\n# Transcript\n\n[00:00:00 → 00:00:25] **SPEAKER_00:** Hi everyone, can you hear me?\n\n[00:00:26 → 00:01:10] **SPEAKER_01:** Thanks, all good. So today we wanted to walk through the new architecture.\n```\n\nEach `[mm:ss → mm:ss] **SPEAKER_NN:** turn-text` is one paragraph. This:\n- chunks naturally per speaker turn for embeddings,\n- supports citations like `[src-tx-1wz @ 12:34 SPEAKER_01]`,\n- stays human-readable.\n\n**Prereqs the user must do once:**\n- Accept pyannote ToS at https://hf.co/pyannote/speaker-diarization-3.1 (HF login).\n- Set `HF_TOKEN` (or `huggingface-cli login`).\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Tool transcribes both LiveRamp .m4a recordings end-to-end.\n- Output markdown round-trips through `kb ingest` (drop into `~/chief/consulting/kb/raw/inbox/`) and `kb compile` without lint errors.\n- Resulting source pages appear in `wiki/sources/` next to the existing typed-notes sources (`src-1wz`, `src-1xo`).\n- Spot-check: pick 5 random utterances per recording, confirm transcript matches the audio and speaker labels are internally consistent (same speaker = same SPEAKER_NN throughout).\n- Re-running the tool on the same input is a content-hash cache hit (no GPU work).\n\n**Risks.**\n- Pyannote diarization can over-segment when speakers overlap (Zoom meetings have lots of \"yeah, mhm\" cross-talk). Acceptable for v1; address with `--min-speakers/--max-speakers` flags if it gets bad.\n- whisper-large-v3 hallucinates on long silences. Use VAD pre-filtering (whisperx has built-in pyannote VAD).\n- Speaker labels are anonymous — manual rename is a known gap, addressed by `--aliases` flag and a follow-up bone.\n\n**Not in scope (deferred to phase-2 bone).**\n- In-tree Rust integration (kb-ingest first-class audio handler).\n- Single-binary shipping; native model download cache.\n- Ad-hoc UX inside `kb ingest` — for now the user runs the standalone tool, then drops markdown into `raw/inbox/`.","kind":"task","labels":["audio"],"size":"m","title":"ingest: audio diarization prototype (WhisperX)","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:Zg6mfJWtPn85JsDUAZ5TtmGJH2euOhMcfWPUru3iMO4
1777314091243614	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtkAc		item.create	bn-2lp2	{"description":"**Why.** The WhisperX prototype (bn-3hfw) proves the workflow but pulls a Python venv + pyannote/HF auth into the toolchain. kb's distribution story is single static binary; audio ingestion needs to fit that.\n\n**Blocked by bn-3hfw.** Phase 1 nails the output format and behavior; phase 2 swaps the engine.\n\n**Tooling candidates.**\n1. **ASR:** `whisper-rs` (whisper.cpp Rust bindings) with whisper-large-v3 GGUF (~3GB). Battle-tested, works on CPU and CUDA/Metal.\n2. **Diarization:**\n   a. `sherpa-onnx` (k2-fsa) has Rust bindings and bundles VAD + speaker-segmentation + speaker-embedding ONNX pipelines including pyannote-derived models. Single-pipeline path — strongly preferred.\n   b. Fallback: `ort` directly running pyannote ONNX exports (`pyannote-segmentation-3.0.onnx` + `wespeaker-voxceleb-resnet.onnx`) and stitch in Rust.\n3. **Container demux for .mp4 → audio:** `symphonia` (pure-Rust audio decoder/demuxer).\n\n**Plan.**\n- New crate `kb-ingest-audio` (Rust) with feature flags for model backends.\n- First-class handler in `kb-ingest`: detect `.m4a/.mp3/.wav/.mp4`, run ASR + diarization, emit the same source markdown the prototype emits.\n- Models live in `~/.kb/models/` and download on first use (content-hash + size guard). Manifest in code references HF URLs by SHA.\n- CLI: `kb ingest --audio <path>` + `kb ingest --audio-aliases <toml>` for speaker renames.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- Same two LiveRamp recordings produce markdown that diffs cleanly (modulo timestamps within ±0.5s) against bn-3hfw output.\n- `kb ingest --audio file.m4a` works end-to-end on a fresh machine after first-run model download.\n- No Python in the runtime path. Single kb binary suffices.\n- Quality: WER on a held-out 5-minute clip within ±2% of WhisperX prototype.\n- CPU fallback works (acceptable to be slow); GPU via CUDA/Metal when available.\n\n**Risks.**\n- Diarization model availability in ONNX is the main unknown. pyannote-3.1 is gated and ONNX exports are community-driven; may need to pin a known-good export. sherpa-onnx supposedly handles this — needs validation.\n- whisper-rs CUDA build complexity vs portability. Default to CPU build; gate CUDA behind feature flag.\n- Model-download UX: ~3GB whisper + ~150MB diarization is real bandwidth. Surface progress; allow --model-cache <dir> override.","kind":"task","labels":["audio"],"size":"l","title":"ingest: native Rust audio diarization (single binary)"}	blake3:qQbAp52hpN-XouExFQu3YjfyBDJEY2g9tqCQZWOK2qM
1777314094706819	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtkQc		item.link	bn-2lp2	{"link_type":"blocks","target":"bn-3hfw"}	blake3:Jkr1BSF9a-KApMrLK-A8JLUWSIyrw9DXD8JSzNPd3jk
1777323187536026	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtkgc		item.create	bn-3h4h	{"description":"**Why.** Meeting transcripts are now a real source type (audio ingestion landed in bn-3hfw). The current Markdown is \"good enough\" but inconsistent — speaker IDs are anonymous, action lines are unmarked, there's no roster, no formal parser. Define a small, well-shaped convention now so:\n- The Rust port (bn-2lp2) has a target to parse and render.\n- Future audio sources read the same way.\n- Citations can resolve to specific speaker turns reliably.\n\nThe spec should be **Fountain-analog**: one-page, plain-text, parses with ~50 lines of code, renders cleanly in any Markdown viewer.\n\n**Out of scope.** This is just the format spec + a parser/renderer pair. The diarization engine selection (whisperx → Rust) is the sibling bone bn-2lp2.\n\n**Format draft (to be refined in the spec doc).**\n\nYAML frontmatter for source metadata (already done):\n```\n---\ntype: source\ntitle: 2026-04-07 LiveRamp USB Team Intro Transcript\nrecording_date: 2026-04-07\naudio_file: GMT20260407-143343_Recording.m4a\nduration_seconds: 4493.1\nasr_model: whisper-large-v3\ndiarization_model: pyannote/speaker-diarization-community-1\nlanguage: en\n---\n```\n\nSpeaker roster (Fountain's title-page / dramatis-personae analog):\n```\n## Speakers\n\n- @joshua: Joshua Cox (LiveRamp eng manager)\n- @xiaodong: Xiaodong Ma (USB team lead)\n- @bob: Bob (consultant)\n- @speaker_03: unknown\n```\n\nSpeaker turns:\n```\n## @xiaodong [00:01:35 → 00:02:20]\n\nSo USB is the new segment builder, replacing CSB. We own the API,\nbackend, job service, segment engine, and FedSQL translation.\n```\n\nAction lines (Fountain's parentheticals / scene action analog):\n```\n> [laughter]\n> [screen share: USB architecture diagram]\n> [overlap: SPEAKER_03 and SPEAKER_04 talking simultaneously]\n```\n\nOptional inline annotations for short side-events without breaking turn flow:\n```\n## @bob [00:05:12 → 00:05:34]\n\nSo the Matricule service is the part that... [phone rings, brief pause]\n...handles the actual materialization.\n```\n\n**Speaker ID rules.**\n- Real-name speakers: `@first-name` lowercase, kebab if needed (`@xiaodong-ma` if disambiguation required).\n- Unknown speakers: `@speaker_NN` matching diarization output.\n- The roster section is the source of truth; turns reference roster IDs.\n- An aliases TOML at compile time maps anonymous diarization labels (`SPEAKER_03`) to roster IDs (`@xiaodong`).\n\n**Acceptance.**\n1. Spec doc at `notes/transcript-spec.md` with examples, formal grammar (PEG or BNF), edge-case rules.\n2. Rust parser + renderer in a new module (probably under `kb-ingest-audio` once that crate exists, or `kb-core::transcript` for early shared use).\n3. Round-trip test: parse a transcript file → AST → render → byte-identical output (modulo whitespace normalization).\n4. The bn-3hfw Python tool emits the new format (renderer port).\n5. The two LiveRamp transcripts re-render cleanly in the new format, with anonymous SPEAKER_NN labels until aliases are filled in.\n6. `kb-web` renders speaker turns with anchor links per turn (`#xiaodong-00-01-35` etc.) so citations land on the right utterance.\n\n**Risks.**\n- Bikeshedding on syntax (`@speaker` vs `[speaker]` vs `> SPEAKER:`). Mitigation: pick one and write the spec; document the rejected alternatives in a \"design decisions\" section.\n- Speaker-ID renames: when a roster entry is renamed mid-corpus, all transcripts need updating. Mitigation: aliases TOML lives separately, applied at render time, so canonical files never need rewrites.\n\n**Naming.** I lean toward calling the format `kbtx` (kb transcript) for clarity; the spec doc names it.","kind":"task","labels":["audio","spec"],"size":"m","title":"spec: kb transcript markup convention (Fountain-analog)"}	blake3:fPuK8lVS0xdOTWN3y9qlb6kIVmckI513mLEFHqIiXDk
