1777326006442328	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmAc		item.create	bn-3syy	{"description":"**Why.** kbtx transcript sources have one ## @speaker-id [HH:MM:SS → HH:MM:SS] H2 per speaker turn. The kb-compile key_topics extractor treats every H2 as a topic, which adds 100-200 noisy slug entries (e.g. `speaker-03-00-00-01-00-00-53`) to the wiki source page's Key topics list and slightly dilutes the lexical signal for retrieval.\n\n**Scope.** Detect transcript sources (extension `.kbtx.md` or frontmatter `type: source` + presence of `## @<id> [...]` headings) in kb-compile and either:\n- Skip per-turn headings entirely from key_topics (preferred), or\n- Group them under a single \"transcript\" topic.\n\nThe `## Speakers` heading should also probably be skipped since it's structural, not a topic.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- USB transcript wiki source page lists ~handful of topics, not 188.\n- Retrieval ranking for transcript sources matches or exceeds the pre-kbtx baseline (USB transcript was rank ~2 for \"What did Xiaodong say about how segment materialization works in USB?\" before — should land in the same neighborhood after fix).\n\n**Background.** Surfaced during bn-3h4h validation; non-blocking for that bone since transcripts are still retrievable, just lower-ranked than ideal.","kind":"task","labels":["audio","compile"],"size":"s","title":"compile: skip speaker-turn H2 headings in key_topics extractor for kbtx sources"}	blake3:-02_nLlyLYcWtTqtTzegWA-ar_JbIPIWFdCyxoHvr98
1777326022136312	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmQc		item.move	bn-3h4h	{"state":"done"}	blake3:P8BZ-goRCvlD8bVwR4l9BYykT1C1tlf67bqYpF9lGOM
1777327005163190	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmgc		item.comment	bn-2lp2	{"body":"Stack locked in based on research (see chat 2026-04-27):\n\nASR: whisper-rs (FFI to whisper.cpp, model whisper-large-v3 q5_0 GGUF, ~1.1GB).\nDiarization: pyannote-rs (segmentation-3.0 + wespeaker-voxceleb-resnet34-LM, ONNX runtime, ~36MB combined).\nContainer demux for .mp4 → audio: symphonia (pure-Rust).\n\nWhy these specifically:\n- pyannote-rs uses pre-converted ONNX from onnx-community/k2-fsa, MIT-licensed, unauthenticated download — no HF login, no ToS click-through. Solves the prototype's gating burden.\n- whisper-rs is the battle-tested option; quality matches the prototype's faster-whisper.\n- ONNX runtime (used by pyannote-rs) supports CPU/CUDA/CoreML execution providers at runtime, so a single binary can dispatch GPU or fall back to CPU.\n- Per-platform builds still required for whisper.cpp's GPU backend (CUDA + Metal can't co-exist), so distribution is per-platform binary downloads.\n\nTrade-off accepted: lose ~few % WDER vs community-1 (the prototype default) for frictionless distribution. Revisit if community-1 gets an ungated ONNX export.\n\nRejected:\n- parakeet-rs Sortformer for diarization: 4-speaker hard cap fails 6-speaker LiveRamp meetings.\n- Pure-candle stack: example is dev-quality, no batching/VAD, too much wrapping.\n- sherpa-onnx Rust API as primary: bigger dependency surface than needed; pyannote-rs is more focused.\n\nModels auto-download to ~/.kb/models/<sha256>.onnx (or .bin for whisper) on first use, content-hash verified, cached forever."}	blake3:JHEeNg8q5OirAeoshYGk7ZIyjh-bDS0Ty8pMqxCZBIs
1777327005191806	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmwc		item.move	bn-2lp2	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:bermt_K-Lstkwj1vT6Q-qt4rrxEXg6QeYLWFH2adBzQ
