1777423490871789	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtrwc		item.comment	bn-1rww	{"body":"Considered pplx-embed-v1-0.6b (Perplexity, MIT, released ~Mar 2026) as an alternative to MiniLM-L6-v2.\n\nQuality\n- 68.6 avg nDCG@10 (INT8). Beats Qwen3-Embed-0.6B (61.2) and BGE-M3 (62.3); beats Qwen3-Embed-4B in 3/5 BERGEN tasks.\n- 1024-dim, 32K context, multilingual, native INT8 (no instruction prefix needed).\n- ONNX export ships in the HF repo, so it fits the same `ort`-based wiring.\n\nCost vs MiniLM\n- ~5.9 GB on disk vs ~90 MB (~60x download).\n- 0.6B params vs ~22M (~25x compute per embedding) — magnifies the cold-start / CPU-embed risks already called out in this bone.\n- 1024-dim vs 384-dim — higher per-vector storage and cosine cost.\n\nRecommendation: keep MiniLM as the default backend for this bone (small, fast, proves out the trait + ort feature flag + model-path + re-embed flow). File a follow-up to add `backend = \"pplx-embed-v1\"` once the eval harness can quantify the quality jump against the 60x model-size cost. The pluggable EmbeddingBackend trait makes the second backend cheap.\n\nRefs:\n- https://huggingface.co/perplexity-ai/pplx-embed-v1-0.6b\n- https://research.perplexity.ai/articles/pplx-embed-state-of-the-art-embedding-models-for-web-scale-retrieval"}	blake3:JTlznKiFp2n1jCd7yNPIicDv-F33EZSMP3pgUKmyTn0
1777424191075598	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtsAc		item.create	bn-12zh	{"description":"**Symptom.** A failed LLM pass during \\`kb compile\\` floods the terminal with hundreds of lines that turn out to be the rendered prompt itself (document body + template task block). One failure can dump ~2 KB; multiplied across N stale sources, the actual error reason is unfindable.\n\n**Repro.**\n- \\`kb compile\\` in \\`~/chief/consulting/kb\\` (job-compile-28r) failed source_summary on src-3u8 (520 KB normalized doc).\n- Each \\`[err]\\` line in \\`.kb/state/jobs/<id>.log\\` is followed by ~70 wrapped lines containing the trailing 2 KB of the rendered prompt.\n\n**Root cause** — two layers compounding:\n\n1. \\`crates/kb-llm/src/opencode.rs:311-321\\` puts raw subprocess stdout/stderr into \\`LlmAdapterError::Other\\` whenever opencode exits non-zero:\n\n       let details = if stderr.is_empty() { output.stdout.trim().to_string() } else { stderr };\n       Err(LlmAdapterError::Other(format!(\"opencode exited with error: {details}\")))\n\n   When opencode's stderr/stdout echoes the prompt back (which it does on certain failures — see bn-1gx7-sibling for the underlying ARG_MAX/shell-passing issue), the prompt body lands in the error string verbatim.\n\n2. \\`crates/kb-compile/src/pipeline.rs:1037-1043,1158-1164,1281-1287\\` then forwards the same \\`stderr_tail\\`-truncated message (last 2 KB) to **both** the terminal reporter and the log file:\n\n       let err_str = stderr_tail(&err.to_string());\n       let err_line = format!(\"  [err] source_summary: {doc_id} ({:.1}s) — {err_str}\", ...);\n       reporter.error(&err_line);\n       log_message(options, &err_line);\n\n   Embedded \\`\\\\n\\`s in the prompt expand into many displayed lines on the terminal. The 2 KB cap is appropriate for the log, but ridiculous on stderr.\n\n**Fix.**\n- **Adapter side:** Strip the prompt content from \\`details\\` before wrapping into \\`LlmAdapterError\\`. Heuristics: trim leading whitespace then drop any prefix that matches the rendered prompt (the adapter has it in scope as \\`rendered.content\\`). If nothing usable remains, fall back to the exit code + a short reason like \\`opencode exited with code N (no diagnostic on stderr)\\`.\n- **Pipeline side:** split the err line into two views.\n  - Terminal (\\`reporter.error\\`): one-line summary, ≤ 200 chars, ending in a pointer like \\`(see .kb/state/jobs/<id>.log)\\`.\n  - Log file (\\`log_message\\`): keep the 2 KB tail (or even the full \\`err.to_string()\\`) — log files are meant to be searchable.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- A failing compile pass renders ≤ 1 line per failure on stderr.\n- The same job log file still contains the full diagnostic for offline inspection.\n- Existing tests in \\`pipeline.rs\\` (\\`compile_captures_stderr_tail_on_llm_failure\\`, \\`stderr_tail_truncates_long_input\\`) updated to assert the new split.\n- Add a test that a fake LlmAdapterError whose message embeds the prompt does NOT echo the prompt to the reporter sink.\n\nConfidence: 90%.","kind":"task","labels":["cli","compile","dx"],"title":"kb compile: error formatting dumps prompt body to terminal"}	blake3:G9Gr59qeS9pvSncQtLVJG9RwTLdkNIntNgeNiDCx1Fw
1777424215417316	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtsQc		item.create	bn-18xw	{"description":"**Why.** Today the opencode adapter assembles a single shell string (\\`OPENCODE_CONFIG=... opencode run --agent ... '<prompt>'\\`) and runs it via \\`sh -c\\` (\\`crates/kb-llm/src/opencode.rs:188\\`, \\`crates/kb-llm/src/subprocess.rs:run_shell_command\\`). The prompt is shell-quoted with single quotes (\\`shell_quote\\` at \\`opencode.rs:914\\`).\n\nThis is fragile for large prompts:\n\n- ARG_MAX on this box is 4 MB, but the limit applies to **argv + envp combined**, so a fat environment can effectively halve it. A 520 KB prompt (real example: src-3u8 in \\`~/chief/consulting/kb\\`) plus a normal env still works, but anything north of ~1 MB starts blowing up unpredictably across machines.\n- Every byte of the prompt has to be re-parsed by \\`sh\\` before being handed to opencode. That's purely lost work and adds a quoting failure mode.\n- Errors that propagate back from opencode in this mode embed the *rendered prompt* in stdout/stderr (likely because the failed command line is echoed by sh), which then gets baked into \\`LlmAdapterError\\`. See sibling bone (\\`kb compile: error formatting dumps prompt body to terminal\\`).\n\n**What.** Two options, in preference order:\n\n1. **stdin (preferred).** Drop the prompt positional. Spawn \\`opencode run --agent <name> [--variant V] [--session S] [--format json] -\\` (or whatever opencode's stdin sigil is — verify in its --help) and write the prompt bytes to the child's stdin. argv stays tiny; no shell quoting at all. \\`run_shell_command\\` already drains stdout/stderr concurrently — extend or add a sibling that also writes stdin in a third thread to avoid pipe-fill deadlock.\n\n2. **argv-direct fallback.** If opencode does not accept prompt-on-stdin, switch from \\`sh -c\\` to \\`Command::new(...).args([...])\\` so we no longer pay the shell-quoting tax. The prompt still rides argv, but we sidestep the sh-level command-line length penalty and the prompt-echo-on-failure behavior.\n\nEither way, drop \\`shell_quote\\` from the prompt path entirely.\n\n**Acceptance.**\n- \\`OpencodeAdapter::run_prompt\\` no longer composes the prompt into a shell string.\n- A test compiles a 1 MB prompt without spawning a subprocess that hits a length limit (use a stub \\`run_*\\` to assert argv shape).\n- The existing tests for \\`build_command\\` and \\`shell_quote\\` are removed or rewritten to match the new contract.\n- \\`kb compile\\` on \\`~/chief/consulting/kb\\` no longer 0.0s-fails on src-3u8 (or fails for a real reason, like context-window overflow, with a clean error).\n- The Claude adapter (\\`crates/kb-llm/src/claude.rs:951\\`) gets the same treatment as a follow-up — file a sub-bone if it's not in scope.\n\n**Risks.** opencode's stdin contract may not exist or may differ between versions. Verify against the user's installed opencode before committing to option 1; fall back to option 2 if so.\n\n**Depends on.** None blocking; can land independently of the error-formatting bone.\n\nConfidence: 80%.","kind":"task","labels":["kb-llm","opencode","robustness"],"title":"kb-llm: pass opencode prompt via stdin/argv-direct, not sh -c"}	blake3:urzcFTCwQRS6BFNhtpsKgOfW57KIHBZd9Ew_FuvX6tc
